pan style=\"color: #000000;\"> </span>','Women helpline number in Delhi NCR region','','publish','open','open','','women-helpline-delhi','','','2014-06-26 00:26:49','2014-06-25 18:56:49','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/?p=721',0,'post','',0),(798,7,'2014-06-27 00:40:00','2014-06-26 19:10:00','Rewind a little back to your <strong>social studies classes</strong> and recall how your teacher would tell you that we love in a multi-cultural world and should be tolerant towards people from other ethnic groups, culture or religions. Remember it took ages for certain sections of society to be accepted and break the barriers of racism and communism?\n\nAnd yet, how easily we make racist comments or jokes on people who are different than us! Making someone laugh is one thing but it is another when done at the expense of somebody’s dignity. Unfortunately, we live in a society where racism is very common and often goes unnoticed (not by the offended). What happened to our cultural values? This is not what we learnt and this is certainly not what you want your kids to follow.\n\nRemember it is easy to make snide remarks and offensive comments at people from other communities and backgrounds. But it will not be half as fun when you are at the receiving end of it. So let us all raise our voices against racial discrimination. Let us<strong> teach our kids</strong> to respect other cultures and not stand disrespect to any community or culture. Let us be tolerant towards arts and culture and truly live in the spirit of ‘unity in diversity’.\n','Respecting Culture','Rewind a little back to your <strong>social studies classes</strong> and recall how your teacher would tell you that we love in a multi-cultural world and should be tolerant towards people from other ethnic groups, culture or religions. Remember it took ages for certain sections of society to be accepted and break the barriers of racism and communism?\n','publish','open','open','','respecting-culture','','','2014-06-27 00:40:00','2014-06-26 19:10:00','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/?p=798',0,'post','',0),(801,2,'2014-06-27 00:53:12','2014-06-26 19:23:12','','Day in India','a Day in India','inherit','open','open','','2926924222_0a7bdb06a0_b','','','2014-06-27 00:53:12','2014-06-26 19:23:12','',798,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2926924222_0a7bdb06a0_b.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(804,2,'2014-06-27 17:59:59','2014-06-27 12:29:59','[vc_column_text width=\"1/1\" el_position=\"first last\"]\n\nYou can add any Event, Volunteering oppurtuinty, Internship or Articles and we will publish it for you.The only condition is that motive behind your content should be benefit of society.\n\n[oa_social_login]\n\n[oa_social_link]\n\n<strong class=\"nowrap\">[wppb-login]</strong>\n\n<strong class=\"nowrap\">[wppb-register]</strong>\n\n<strong class=\"nowrap\">[wppb-edit-profile]</strong>\n<h5 class=\"grid\">Fill the Form</h5>\n[contact-form to=\'Support@helpiez.org\' subject=\'Add Content on helpiez\'][contact-field label=\'Type of content \' type=\'select\' required=\'1\' options=\'Article,Event,Volunteer Drive,Hiring Internship\'/][contact-field label=\'Heading\' type=\'text\'/][contact-field label=\'Content\' type=\'textarea\' required=\'1\'/][contact-field label=\'Project/Organisation Name\' type=\'text\'/][contact-field label=\'Cause\' type=\'text\'/][contact-field label=\'Facebook Page\' type=\'text\'/][contact-field label=\'Youtube video URL\' type=\'text\'/][contact-field label=\'Your Name\' type=\'name\' required=\'1\'/][contact-field label=\'Email\' type=\'email\' required=\'1\'/][contact-field label=\'Phone number\' type=\'text\'/][/contact-form]\n\nIf you need to attach any photo, PDf, or any other document you can mail us on support@helpiez.org.\n[/vc_column_text]\nHave a query ? [vc_button title=\"Contact us\" href=\"http://www.helpiez.org/contact\" color=\"wpb_button\" size=\"wpb_regularsize\" icon=\"wpb_mail\" target=\"_self\" width=\"1/1\" el_position=\"first last\"]','Add content on Helpiez.','','publish','open','open','','add-content','','','2014-06-27 17:59:59','2014-06-27 12:29:59','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/?page_id=804',0,'page','',0),(850,5,'2014-06-28 13:31:06','2014-06-28 08:01:06','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Dadri wetland area in Greater Noida, which is home to over 220 species of birds, including the very rare Bristled Grassbirds, is facing destruction from encroaches and builders alerted bird-watcher and environmentalist. The breeding of the rare Bristled Grassbird has been recorded for the first time ever in this habitat. But private builders are wreaking havoc and the state also is out to destroy it instead of protecting it.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">‘Once gone, it’s gone forever. It will be a big national loss in terms of wildlife several environmentalists are asking the government to declare the wetlands as a protected area, a bird sanctuary or an eco-sensitive zone so that there is no change in the land use.</p>\n Bird watchers from Delhi, Noida and adjoining areas have recorded the presence of over 220 species of rare migrant and resident birds in and around Bil Akbarpur village, about 3 km from Dadri and about 40 km south-east of Delhi.\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The huge lake in the Dadri wetland area is what attracts some of the rarest varieties of migrant birds from Central Asia and Ladakh.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Birds like the bar-headed geese that fly in from Siberia across Mount Everest are also seen in thousands at Bil Akbarpur. One can spot over 5,000 birds at any given point of time here. There are tens of thousands of birds in this habitat and many more are coming. It is also home to hundreds of resident birds throughout the year.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">According to report, the wetlands have some of the most threatened species like Sarus Crane and Black-Necked Stork that are difficult to spot anywhere else.It is one place that represents all families of birds – migrant or resident – and is richer in habitat than the Sultanpur or Okhla bird sanctuaries</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Among the 220 species recorded in the Dadri wetlands during the last four years, environmentalists have spotted Sarus (state bird of UP), Blue Throat (rare bird from Alaska) and waterfowls like Mallard, Pintail, Shoveler ducks, Garganey teals, Pochards, Wigeons and Waders.</p>\n<a href=\"http://www.sify.com/news/dadri-wetland-faces-destruction-environmentalists-news-national-lcfvufhdaejsi.html\">Refrence</a>','\'Dadri Wetland\' faces destruction','','publish','open','closed','','dadri-wetland-faces-destruction','','','2014-06-28 13:31:06','2014-06-28 08:01:06','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/?p=850',0,'post','',0),(851,2,'2014-06-28 13:24:24','2014-06-28 07:54:24','','Surajpur bird sanctuary','','inherit','open','open','','surajpur-bird-sanctuary','','','2014-06-28 13:24:24','2014-06-28 07:54:24','',850,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/surajpur-bird-sanctuary-e1408371820862.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(883,4,'2014-06-29 14:27:25','2014-06-29 08:57:25','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\">Being a history student, studying<strong> Roman civilisation</strong> can be immensely interesting. Apart from the fact that you get to know about the famous Julius Caesar and how Rome was an immensely powerful and glorious empire, you are also drawn towards its reputation of being dark, ruthless and cruel in its dealings. However, while studying it, I could not help but draw parallels between their and <em>our system of governance</em> and lifestyle. The more I looked into it, the more I wondered about it. So that’s when I thought to pen down my wandering thoughts and give a shape and conclusion to them, and see what comes out of this thought process of mine.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\">The first thing that caught my attention was the various kinds of punishments that the Romans had. The sheer creativity and innovative ideas just swept me off my feet. For example, there was a law according to which if a soldier is caught stealing, then he was taken to a donkey, whose stomach was cut out, and then the soldier was stuffed into it with his head hanging out. After that the stomach of the donkey was sewed up and he was left in the forest where it was pretty sure that the wild animals will find the awesome duo, and give them farewell. Unbelievable? Nevertheless it was true. When I came back to<strong> 21<sup>st</sup> century</strong>, I wondered what is the difference here? Sure we don’t stuff donkeys with live humans, and that the police is not really in power to do all this stuff, but the brutality remains. We see rapist inserting an iron rod to the <a title=\"2012 Delhi Rape\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012_Delhi_gang_rape\" target=\"_blank\">victim\'s stomach</a> and drawing her intestines out. We see people’s head and tongue being chopped off by pirates or terrorists organisation and worse, we see generations being destroyed by dropping of a single bomb. True we have come a long way since the Romans, but the ruthlessness and cruelty are those aspects of being human which we can never truly let go away from ourselves.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\">From lifestyle, now lets pay attention to the system of governance. Romans had some variety of rulers and emperors and kings and what not. But only a few of them learnt the tricks of the trade. And no, Julius Caesar was not one of them sadly. It is true that people on the top would invariably be influential and rich in their lifestyle. But very few of them understand that to do even that, the common people will make a part of your life and that the king, emperor, or the ruler, has to deliver positively. And that’s exactly what Augustus Caesar did. He created an illusion of republic and won the trust of the people by ensuring them that they still have power over him, still had power to throw him out. But behind the scenes, he took all the power in his hands and became a monarch. But how is this welfare? Well, he did lots of things that the common people of Rome at that time desired. He gave them free grains( yeah so much money!), gave them jobs and made people his loyalists. I don’t deny that he was filling his own Swiss bank account present at that time, but he also worked for the welfare of the people because he was afraid of them. He knew that if he loses their loyalty, the Romans could turn into a mob and kill him in his own bedroom. Thus, he kept everyone happy, and ensured long term peace in his empire.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\">Cut to scene of 21<sup>st</sup> century, we see politicians filling their <a title=\"Indian Black money \" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_black_money#Black_money_in_Swiss_banks\" target=\"_blank\">politicians filling their coffers</a> but no one is bothered about the welfare of the common man. I am sure there are people who know how to govern, but they need to polish their skills and remember that Rome was not built in a day. They should work towards keeping people happy and not do it just for their own vote bank, just like the Romans. </span></p>\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/caliope-olga/1160053757\">Pic</a> <a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/ramesh_lalwani/\">credit</a>','Roman civilisation and our modern lifestyle','','publish','open','open','','roman-civilisation-modern-lifestyle','','','2014-06-29 14:27:25','2014-06-29 08:57:25','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/?p=883',0,'post','',0),(894,4,'2014-06-29 14:38:53','2014-06-29 09:08:53','','Cruel king','Punishment in Roman empire','inherit','open','open','','1160053757_6c8456f9f0_o','','','2014-06-29 14:38:53','2014-06-29 09:08:53','',88