hey get to manage according to their needs.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Helpiez, sincerely believes in the cause of bridging the wide gap between the motivated volunteers and the different NGO\'s supporting different causes. This portal will directly help welfare organizations in increasing their online presence which will enable people to look through their agenda and contribute correspondingly. Hence, it will increase awareness in the society for both the Cause and about the NGO which works for the Cause.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Through Helpiez, the social developers of the present will find a new platform to raise their concerns from and on the other hand it will also make the volunteering more efficient and easily available to the people. This social venture in the long run and in many ways will take community service in India to a whole new level and giving it the required push. We, at Helpiez shall bring together those people who demand a social change and make world a better place for future generations.</p>','About Us','','publish','open','open','','about','','','2014-12-21 06:51:04','2014-12-21 06:51:04','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?page_id=2171',0,'page','',0),(2173,2,'2014-12-21 06:52:30','2014-12-21 06:52:30','<blockquote style=\"text-align: justify;\">This is a testing website and would be used strictly for non commercial purposes and all the transactions would be kept transparent to the public. All views expressed herein are solely of the writers. Helpiez does not support any bias against any caste, creed, color, sex, religion or region whatsoever. Furthermore, if the contents displayed on the website seems offensive to the users for any reason whatsoever, the users are at their liberty to contact the organization on the following email: support@helpiez.org and we would be obliged to help the users with their problems.</blockquote>','Disclaimer','','publish','open','open','','disclaimer','','','2014-12-21 06:52:30','2014-12-21 06:52:30','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?page_id=2173',0,'page','',0),(2198,2,'2014-12-21 08:11:17','2014-12-21 08:11:17','\n[authors_gj]','Our Authors','','publish','open','open','','our-authors','','','2014-12-21 08:11:17','2014-12-21 08:11:17','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?page_id=2198',0,'page','',0),(2200,2,'2014-12-21 08:13:51','2014-12-21 08:13:51','[dropdown_gj]','Tags','','publish','open','open','','tags','','','2014-12-21 08:13:51','2014-12-21 08:13:51','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?page_id=2200',0,'page','',0),(2211,2,'2014-12-21 09:09:15','2014-12-21 09:09:15','','10432010_794586510559880_412477034_n','','inherit','open','open','','10432010_794586510559880_412477034_n','','','2014-12-21 09:09:15','2014-12-21 09:09:15','',2200,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/10432010_794586510559880_412477034_n-e1420966341838.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2214,2,'2014-12-21 09:20:26','2014-12-21 09:20:26','','10432010_794586510559880_412477034_n','','inherit','open','open','','10432010_794586510559880_412477034_n-2','','','2014-12-21 09:20:26','2014-12-21 09:20:26','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/10432010_794586510559880_412477034_n.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2222,2,'2014-12-21 09:27:43','2014-12-21 09:27:43','','keshav','','inherit','open','open','','10547640_750266331678849_8839380658011679858_n','','','2014-12-21 09:27:43','2014-12-21 09:27:43','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/10547640_750266331678849_8839380658011679858_n-e1420967860693.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2223,2,'2014-12-21 09:35:07','2014-12-21 09:35:07','','10547640_750266331678849_8839380658011679858_n','','inherit','open','open','','10547640_750266331678849_8839380658011679858_n-2','','','2014-12-21 09:35:07','2014-12-21 09:35:07','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/10547640_750266331678849_8839380658011679858_n1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2230,23,'2014-12-22 07:14:04','2014-12-22 07:14:04','It has been a tough day for Sheetal. Well, to be fair all days are the same for her. Tough and tiring and in search for identity. She is a resident of India but she also is a transgender. Hence, the government has been turning a blind eye to her existence for the longest time now. It was only in mid-April 2014 that the court finally came up with some relief- documents could now have a third box to tick when asking for gender. However, Sheetal and others like her haven\'t found much relief. A little bit of legal acknowledgment still doesn\'t mean that they have become equals or that they are not discriminated against anymore. Transgenders still find it hard to find jobs. They can have the highest degrees from the best colleges but to the world, they are still the third gender that, according to tradition, was and has to be excluded.\n\n<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/kl.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-2232\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/kl.jpg\" alt=\"kl\" width=\"267\" height=\"312\" /></a>\n\nHowever, as a society it is high time we do some introspection. Is it justified to excommunicate people just because of they are different? Is it ok for families to abandon their own children because the society doesn\'t accept them? So not hiring someone with a good education because they belong to that part of the society that isn\'t accepted is justified? The answer to all these seemingly complex questions is a simple no.\n\nEvery human being deserves acceptance and dignity. They should be taught to love themselves. Nobody should be telling them that they will have to live through this accident of birth. We should not refer to it as accident of birth at all.\n\nWe have come so far since Independence. We assume we\'ve become modern but that can\'t be so till we keep denying identity to a whole group of people who live within the society that we live in. People like Sheetal deserve to be acknowledged and accepted if we need to progress and develop as a modern society.','DILEMMAS OF THE THIRD GENDER:','','publish','open','open','','dilemmas-third-gender','','','2014-12-22 07:14:04','2014-12-22 07:14:04','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2230',0,'post','',2),(2231,2,'2014-12-21 15:40:25','2014-12-21 15:40:25','','lk','','inherit','open','open','','lk','','','2014-12-21 15:40:25','2014-12-21 15:40:25','',2230,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/lk.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2232,2,'2014-12-21 15:42:25','2014-12-21 15:42:25','','kl','','inherit','open','open','','kl','','','2014-12-21 15:42:25','2014-12-21 15:42:25','',2230,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/kl.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2236,23,'2014-12-22 07:26:50','2014-12-22 07:26:50','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Arnab sits across his mother who smiles at Abhishek. To Arnab\'s relief, his mother aproves of Abhishek. In fact, she seems to love him. They\'ve bonded over common interests -cooking and Jane Austen. Arnab reminisces about the day he first told his mother that he is into boys. His mother tried to digest the fact very hard. She cried over how there won\'t ever be a big fat Indian wedding and how there will be no kids. However, she read up about it and realised that functions and non-existent grandchildren do not trump her son\'s happiness.  She took time and some counselling but she finally reached a point where she agreed to meet her son\'s boyfriend. She understood it as the \'21st Century Love\'. On meeting Abhishek, she was delighted to know that her son had a partner who loved him. Abhishek was going to take care of Arnab just like she would.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"> It is amazing how laws come and go but parents are finally giving more leverage to the emotions of their children rather than their reputation in the society. They seem to have accepted that their children can fall in love with anybody, as long as they are happy. Families have finally welcomed the \'new age\' where alternate family structures exist and are accepted. However, 20 years ago, things were very different. Being gay was a disease and parents did everything from going to a doctor to paying heed to the baba who sat under the tree to save their children and their children.   Homosexual individuals almost never came out of the closet and readily married and put up a facade for the sake of their families.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/ty.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-2237\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/ty.jpg\" alt=\"ty\" width=\"320\" height=\"267\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"> Things are looking postive today but not all the way through. Kanika\'s marriage has been fixed to a boy with an excellent family and an even more awesome job. The people are warm. The boy calls every now and then. His mother is wonderfully sweet and an amazing cook. His sister always invites Kanika for shopping trips and movies. However,  Kanika can\'t get her mind off her girlfriend. She has done the whole ritual of returning the gifts given and saying the last goodbye but is sure that she simply can\'t emulate a bond like that with a man. What choice did she have? Kanika belongs to a conservative family and had she told them that she wants to pursue a life with her girlfriend, they would have definitely killed her and her girlfriend. She would become the classic example of a homophobia based honour killing. However, there is no one way to tackle a situation like this.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"> Considering that the government refuses to acknowledge the current scenario regarding the issue, it is very important that the media and the people of this nation start working towards changing views and opinions. We don\'t control who we love and neither should the society. The sole basis of one\'s life isn\'t procreation but</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>','21st Century Love','','publish','open','open','','21st-century-love','','','2014-12-22 07:26:50','2014-12-22 07:26:50','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2236',0,'post','',2),(2237,2,'2014-12-22 07:24:40','2014-12-22 07:24:40','','ty','','inherit','open','open','','ty','','','2014-12-22 07:24:40','2014-12-22 07:24:40','',2236,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/ty.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2238,2,'2014-12-22 07:24:57','2014-12-22 07:24:57','','yt','','inherit','open','open','','yt','','','2014-12-22 07:24:57','2014-12-22 07:24:57','',2236,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/yt-e1419261498303.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2242,23,'2014-12-22 07:42:57','2014-12-22 07:42:57','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Patriarchy is an institution which places women at the bottom most place. It makes it hard for women to move around or breathe. Considering times have changed, one would expect that the world has become more modern, that women now have a new found freedom. However, this is far from the truth. Till date, women are stopped from progressing because of an invisible glass ceiling placed above them.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Modern India grapples with the issue of who makes a perfect bahu. Is it the woman who stays at home or the woman who works outside? Or is it the woman who does both, barely managing to breathe? The answer is that  India hasn\'t been able to comfortably accept that women can have 9to5 jobs too. The society wants a bahu who does all house chores while trying to allow this same bahu to have bigger aspirations in the name of modernity.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"> Sareena got married 2 months ago. Her in-laws seemed to be fine with the idea of having a daughter-in-law who worked in a bank but didn\'t stop taunting her about her poor household management which wasn\'t all that poor considering she woke up at 5 every morning to make sure every member of the family got breakfast and a clean house. Now, her married life doesn\'t seem all that blissful. She tries very hard to meet the never ending expectations of her family and to do her job to her best ability.This story isn\'t unique but is a feature of the Indian society which assumes that a woman can manage only one thing.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/rw.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-2244\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/rw.jpg\" alt=\"rw\" width=\"600\" height=\"399\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Take the example of Nithya who is expecting her first child. She is very highly placed in her company but others have already started talking about who will take her position once she has her baby and kisses her job a goodbye. They are unaware of the fact that she plans on working even after having her child and getting further promotions.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is very important that we realise that we are a growing economy. We are faced with a huge population. Instead of looking at this population as a burden, we should look at it like a boon. We should develop human resources to help the economy. This won\'t happen till one half of the country is stopped by placing the barriers of tradition on them. Women deserve equal pay for equal work. Women deserve promotions for which they work. They shouldn\'t be shunned from the workforce just because they have the biological gift of being the vessel for life.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is high time that we realise that women are equal to men. More importantly, we should start acting upon this realisation. The sign of a developed economy and society is the sort of encouragement provided to everybody despite of their gender.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>','Women Of Today','','publish','open','open','','women-today','','','2014-12-22 07:42:57','2014-12-22 07:42:57','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2242',0,'post','',1),(2243,2,'2014-12-22 07:39:03','2014-12-22 07:39:03','','wr','','inherit','open','open','','wr','','','2014-12-22 07:39:03','2014-12-22 07:39:03','',2242,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wr.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2244,2,'2014-12-22 07:39:16','2014-12-22 07:39:16','','rw','','inherit','open','open','','rw','','','2014-12-22 07:39:16','2014-12-22 07:39:16','',2242,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/rw.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2278,27,'2014-12-23 19:08:07','2014-12-23 19:08:07','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As it started to dawn, my alarm rang. It was a rare occasion when I woke up at wee hours of the morning. I got ready at the earliest to rush to the railway station. I skipped the breakfast, so my mother packed it for the journey. I got to the railway station just in time. While running towards the platform, I checked my train’s status. It was late by 20 minutes. I heaved a sigh of relief and started moving towards the platform at a normal pace to show everyone that I am cautious enough to reach at the railway station before the scheduled arrival of the train.\n<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/helpiez-rail.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter  wp-image-2280\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/helpiez-rail.jpg\" alt=\"Helpiez Rail\" width=\"318\" height=\"211\" /></a>\nI took a seat in the waiting area. Railway stations are like my second home. I have spent a hell lot of time at railway stations, thanks to our Indian railways, which is accustomed to late arrivals. However, I have always found railway station to be an amusing place. You get to see so many forms of human feelings, from happiness of receiving a long gone relative to sadness of seeing off someone who will be gone for quite a while. Mothers, pampering their kids and telling them what to-do and what not to do at their hostels. Fathers worrying about their kids well being. A huge upsurge of human emotions, all at one place. Quite endearing isn’t it.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I waited there, quietly observing different colors of human interactions. I kept on glancing from one place to another. Suddenly, my eyes caught sight of a beggar. He was quite old, covering his body with rags. His situation was miserable. He kept on wandering here and there, probably in search of food. I have always felt pity of those who don’t even have access to basic amenities we enjoy so profoundly and at times take for granted. My heart was moved at his situation. I offered him food that my mother had packed for me. He took it from me and went to a place at some distance to eat. I felt glad that I could be of help to someone in need. A lot of thoughts kept cropping up on my mind. I was thinking how lack of education and jobs has rendered so many people helpless that they had to opt for beggary in order to survive.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I stood up at the announcement that my train was about to arrive. I took a glance at that old man. To my surprise, he sat at the same place smoking a cigarette. I stood stunned. The same person for whom I felt pity a little while ago was causing the feelings of disgust in me. It’s not always system’s fault, people are also responsible for their circumstances, I thought to myself. There is a quotation that my mother always cites, “A man is not a slave of circumstances, he is the creator, controller and master of them”. With this, I hushed up my drifting thoughts and boarded the train.</p>','Disarray of a compassionate heart','','publish','open','open','','disarray-compassionate-heart','','','2014-12-23 19:08:07','2014-12-23 19:08:07','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2278',0,'post','',1),(2279,2,'2014-12-23 19:05:25','2014-12-23 19:05:25','','Disarray of heart','','inherit','open','open','','disarray-of-heart','','','2014-12-23 19:05:25','2014-12-23 19:05:25','',2278,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/disarray-of-heart.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2280,2,'2014-12-23 19:06:21','2014-12-23 19:06:21','','Helpiez Rail','','inherit','open','open','','helpiez-rail','','','2014-12-23 19:06:21','2014-12-23 19:06:21','',2278,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/helpiez-rail.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2283,2,'2014-12-23 19:21:16','2014-12-23 19:21:16','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">On a shivery morning of December, I was driving to work with my mind occupied by daily chores. Lost in my own so called worries, unaware of the world’s issues, which were of much more importance than my daily errands, I halted at a traffic signal. A car stopped by right next to me. What I saw next left me baffled. My mind got overwhelmed by thoughts. There is so much to do for our society in which <em>Justice for all</em> is just a notion. I was left dumbstruck with my piddling to-do list. So, what exactly made me brainsick?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As I stood at the traffic signal, in the car, which hailed right next to me stopping with a sudden halt, was seated a sturdy young man on the driver’s seat. His face was red with rage. An innocent looking young lady, terribly afraid, was sitting right next to him. She was grasping her handbag so close to her, as to protect herself from what was about to come. Yes, you guessed it right, that young man was mad at the lady, God knows for what reasons. To my surprise, he started beating her up right there in the car. The lady was too afraid to revolt. I could see fear in her eyes; she did not even try to raise her voice or to step out of the car. In her, I could easily see the image of every person who has been a victim of domestic violence.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This was probably not her first time. My mind started to ponder, what made her so helpless that she succumbed to such an inhuman behavior? I did not know why the man was so furious. I could not even guess who was at the wrong. But could there be any justification to such a cruel act? Could there be anything that made the woman liable to such a harsh treatment? Of course not! Anything did not suffice as a reason to justify the man’s behavior.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Taking the woman’s helplessness into account, I thought of doing something. What could I possibly have done? Call 100, without even knowing if the lady wanted to lodge a complaint? Stop the car and ask the GENTLEMAN to stop? Who was I to interfere in their personal matter? After few arguments with myself, I decided to do what I normally do. I gave the man a cold look, staring right into his eyes. I imitated that I was noting his car’s number down and was about to call the cops. That would at least end the misery for some time, I thought to myself. Moreover, the man would get a time-out to rethink whatever he was doing. I did just the same and it worked as expected.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The signal turned green, people honked their horns, showing their eagerness to reach their workplaces. The car drove off. I followed it for a while until it took a turn to go on a different route than mine. I was left with perplexing thoughts. How to change people’s perception that any relationship does not provide them with a license to disgrace their partner? I underwent a dilemma, felt by those who accidentally witness such conduct, to speak or not to speak? I believe the initiative should be taken by victims themselves. Before anyone else does something, they need to realize their own worth and take a stand for sake of their dignity. Only then a change can follow.</p>','To speak or not to speak','','publish','open','open','','speak-not-speak','','','2014-12-23 19:21:16','2014-12-23 19:21:16','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2283',0,'post','',0),(2296,2,'2014-12-30 06:49:09','2014-12-30 06:49:09','','copy of gaurav','','inherit','open','open','','copy-of-gaurav','','','2014-12-30 06:49:09','2014-12-30 06:49:09','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/copy-of-gaurav-e1420967442949.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2297,2,'2014-12-30 06:50:39','2014-12-30 06:50:39','','copy of gaurav','','inherit','open','open','','copy-of-gaurav-2','','','2014-12-30 06:50:39','2014-12-30 06:50:39','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/copy-of-gaurav1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2306,22,'2015-01-01 18:20:30','2015-01-01 18:20:30','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">One 13-year-old, called Saeed said he was in the auditorium of the Army Public School when the Taliban struck. He hid under a chair, but saw gunmen coming and firing. He called his mother on the phone.</p>\n\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_2310\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"464\"]<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/nn.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-2310\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/nn.jpg\" alt=\"Peshawar killings children\" width=\"464\" height=\"464\" /></a> Saeed, 13, with his parents at the hospital in Peshawar[/caption]\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">She told me she had heard what was happening from the other end of the line as the attack was taking place.</p>\n\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_2309\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"624\"]<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/nb.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-2309\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/nb.jpg\" alt=\"Peshawar Taliban Attack\" width=\"624\" height=\"351\" /></a> A man at the hospital whose brother was killed in the Taliban attack.[/caption]\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Lying next to Saeed at the hospital was another pupil, Shahrukh Khan.\nThe 17-year-old was in a classroom with his friends when the massacre began.\nHe said a gunman suddenly walked in and started firing randomly. He hid under a desk but saw his friends being shot, once in the head and once in the chest. Two teachers were also killed.\n\"They killed our classmates and teachers,\" said Shahrukh.\n\"The terrorists were in civilian clothes with long beards and long hair with lots of ammunition.\"</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Each time that the epithet of the Peshawar attack reaches our ears, chill tends to run down our spine! The blood stained uniforms and classrooms hurt the eye, and wound the soul. The menace that transpired Peshawar’s soil still makes me question humanity so badly, that words fall short.\nCan slaughtering the 140 kids actually help avenge and win battles, or just make humanity existence a predicament and myth? The moment when the Taliban terrorist association behind the attack posted pictures of the killers behind the attack, did it signify them taking a glorifying victory, or were they just killers of 140 innocent souls, who could have made their nation proud.</p>\n\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_2308\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"624\"]<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/mn.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-2308 size-full\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/mn.jpg\" alt=\"Children died in peshawar attack\" width=\"624\" height=\"351\" /></a> 140 children died in peshawar attack[/caption]\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Each tear shed, each parent’s loss, is my loss, every human’s loss, as in the middle of this turbulence, we lost a great deal of humanity.</p>','Peshawar Attacks - slaughtering of 140 innocent souls','','publish','open','open','','peshawar-attacks-slaughtering-140-innocent-souls','','','2015-01-01 18:20:30','2015-01-01 18:20:30','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2306',0,'post','',0),(2307,2,'2015-01-01 17:48:30','2015-01-01 17:48:30','','bn','','inherit','open','open','','bn-2','','','2015-01-01 17:48:30','2015-01-01 17:48:30','',2306,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/bn1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2308,2,'2015-01-01 17:48:36','2015-01-01 17:48:36','','Peshawar death','','inherit','open','open','','mn','','','2015-01-01 17:48:36','2015-01-01 17:48:36','',2306,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/mn.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2309,2,'2015-01-01 17:48:41','2015-01-01 17:48:41','A man at the hospital whose brother was killed in the Taliban attack. ','Taliban','A man at the hospital whose brother was killed in the Taliban attack. ','inherit','open','open','','nb','','','2015-01-01 17:48:41','2015-01-01 17:48:41','',2306,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/nb.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2310,2,'2015-01-01 17:48:47','2015-01-01 17:48:47','','Peshawar tragedy','Saeed, 13, with his parents at the hospital in Peshawar','inherit','open','open','','nn','','','2015-01-01 17:48:47','2015-01-01 17:48:47','',2306,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/nn.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2316,27,'2015-01-02 15:40:49','2015-01-02 15:40:49','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Christmas has just gone by and New Year is about to come. Streets are all decorated up with lanterns and lights. This festive season has always been full of presents. People exchange gifts with their near and dear ones. Happiness prevails all around. Wherever you see you will find people bubbling with laughter. On occasion of these festivals, there are some people who don’t forget to give something to the grief-stricken. To those who have always been oblivious of the joy this festive season brings along. Someone, who is not even expecting a gift. Why don’t we do something for the needful? Let us not forget them and make them a part of our celebrations.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When it comes to help the needy, one might wonder how to offer help to those in need. What can one do to bring a change in someone’s life? Which gift can be of value to them? Can it be Food, which might satiate their hunger for some time? Can it be Money, which is supposed to buy them happiness? Can it be clothing, which might make them feel good for quite some time? What can that gift be?<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-2317\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/aa.jpg\" alt=\"underprivileged Indian children\" width=\"473\" height=\"238\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Stores are full with things that are considered to be enough to make someone happy, to make them feel special. But the greatest gift one can give someone is the gift of education. Education has the power to turn someone’s life around. Other gifts can last for a day or even months but education will last for lifetime. Education enables oneself to think clearly. An educated person will never succumb to negative circumstances but will face them. An educated person has the potential to turn the situation around, however tough it might be. As a wise man has said, <em>‘Education is not preparation for life; education is life itself’.</em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"> Moreover, anyone can offer this gift. There are no constraints at all. If you have money, you can provide monetary help in the form of school fees or by paying for the uniforms. Even if you are not financially strong, you can always provide guidance to an avid mind through your teaching. And if you say you are short of both time and money there is still a way. You can give your old books to someone in need or introduce them to the right person or institution that can be of help. You just need to have the desire, the desire to be of some help, the desire to bring luck to the unlucky ones. Hold that desire close to you and help someone to turn mirrors into windows of opportunities.</p>\n','Education - Turning Mirrors into Windows','','publish','open','open','','education-turning-mirrors-windows','','','2015-01-02 15:40:49','2015-01-02 15:40:49','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2316',0,'post','',1),(2317,2,'2015-01-02 15:33:05','2015-01-02 15:33:05','In this photo taken Wednesday, Nov. 7, 2012, underprivileged Indian children attend a free school run under a metro bridge in New Delhi, India. At least 30 children living in the nearby slums have been receiving free education from this school for the last three years. (AP Photo/Altaf Qadri)','ed','','inherit','open','open','','aptopix-india-free-school','','','2015-01-02 15:33:05','2015-01-02 15:33:05','',2316,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/aa.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2318,2,'2015-01-02 15:33:17','2015-01-02 15:33:17','\"learn\" written on blackboard with apple and books','\"learn\" written on blackboard with apple, books','','inherit','open','open','','learn-written-on-blackboard-with-apple-books','','','2015-01-02 15:33:17','2015-01-02 15:33:17','',2316,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/z.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2347,27,'2015-01-08 10:04:15','2015-01-08 10:04:15','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Statistics reveal that 7 people commit suicide daily due to drug addiction related issues. If we see record of past 10 years we will find that it has been continuously increasing since then. The youth of our country, which is considered as valuable assets to our nation’s emerging economy, is falling prey to the menace of drug addiction. Our future is endangered. We must do something as this threat has been spreading out its wings at a very fast pace.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The most alarming fact is that the youth of our country indulge themselves in drugs as they think it to be a cool thing. They think they are having fun. Some report that they want to look like grown-ups and they are just following the trend. But they are ignorant of the fact that drugs in no way help them to achieve any of their stated reasons, instead drugs cause serious biological and psychological harm. By the time of realization they become addicted to drugs. Someone who was seeking temporary escape from life’s problems gets stuck in the peril of drug addiction. This all happens due to the misinformation that prevails among youth. A lot of young people claim to be experts in dealing with drugs, and they assure others that it’s not risky at all. But one should use one\'s own conscience to decide what’s right and what’s not.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/s3.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-2349\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/s3.jpg\" alt=\"s3\" width=\"600\" height=\"400\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Our prime minister, Mr. Narendra Modi, in a radio pragramme named ‘Mann Ki Baat’ shared his thoughts about drug abuse in our country. Describing it as a psycho-socio-medical problem, he said the family, friends, society, government and the law will have to work together to fight it. A toll free helpline will be set up soon to assist those seeking answers to the problem. The Prime Minister also encouraged to begin a special drive on social media against the drug menace. He also showed his desire to involve celebrities in various campaigns against drug abuse. Most importantly, there is a need for the whole nation to take a stand together against the menace of drug abuse; only then the coveted message will reach everyone and our dream of <em>Drug-free India</em> can be fulfilled.</p>','Just say No! Drug free is the way to be','','publish','open','open','','just-say-no-drug-free-way','','','2015-01-08 10:04:15','2015-01-08 10:04:15','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2347',0,'post','',0),(2348,2,'2015-01-08 09:53:16','2015-01-08 09:53:16','','s2','','inherit','open','open','','s2','','','2015-01-08 09:53:16','2015-01-08 09:53:16','',2347,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/s2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2349,2,'2015-01-08 09:53:59','2015-01-08 09:53:59','','s3','','inherit','open','open','','s3','','','2015-01-08 09:53:59','2015-01-08 09:53:59','',2347,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/s3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2354,27,'2015-01-08 11:10:55','2015-01-08 11:10:55','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Richard Loitam, a second-semester student of Architecture in Bangalore, was found dead in his hostel room. The family members and friends alleged that he was assaulted brutally by his seniors. Dana Sangma a 21 year old MBA student, committed suicide in her hostel room. Nido Tania, a 20 year old student, was beaten to death with iron rods. All these incidents have one thing in common. All the victims belonged to a particular region of our country. The country which touts so proudly about Unity in Diversity, failed at multiple instances to exhibit the same sentiments.<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/des2-e1420712759168.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter  wp-image-2356\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/des2-e1420712759168.png\" alt=\"des2\" width=\"366\" height=\"218\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Does belonging to a particular region make you less Indian than any other citizen of the country? Does different physical appearance imply you will be treated differently in your own country? Why people have set their own parameters to judge anyone? There have been multiple cases of discrimination against north-east Indians, like over-charging of rent, calling them by derogatory names, physical and mental harassment. All these examples signify how superficial our thinking has become. We don’t accept people who come to our city for sake of getting a good education or employment, yet we say proudly that our country provides us the freedom to reside and settle in any part of our country. We want our freedom yet we breach other’s right to freedom. What kind of hypocrisy is this?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Protests have been staged to assert the need of strong anti-racism laws in our country. People took a stand against the racial discrimination. Candle light processions were held. Government promised strict action against the perpetrators. Bezbaruah committee was formulated to research and suggest the measures to be taken to bring the situation under control. The panel identified the need in amendment to our existent laws. Two amendments have been proposed. The proposed Section 153-C pertains to imputations and assertions prejudicial to human dignity and makes words or signs attempting to discriminate against individuals on the basis of race, a non-bailable offence punishable with imprisonment up to five years with fine. The proposed Section 509-A attempts to make any word, gesture or act intended to insult a member of a particular race with imprisonment that may extend to three years with fine.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Some of the other commendable initiatives include, police exchange programs with north-indian states, special helpline number 1093 for northeast people, Incorporation of north-indian history and contribution to freedom in school curriculum, promoting their cultural heritage and sports. All these recommendations are to be implemented in upcoming months. Undoubtedly, Bezbaruah committee has done a tremendous job in identifying the measures to be taken. We are looking forward to the actual implementation, in the hope to be able to speak out loud that Yes, we believe in our country’s Unity in Diversity. Yes, we believe that a day would come when there would be no need to state that, it would be testified by the absence of any such cases of discrimination to our own brothers and sisters.<b> </b></p>','Awaiting a World without Discrimination','','publish','open','open','','awaiting-world-without-discrimination','','','2015-01-08 11:10:55','2015-01-08 11:10:55','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2354',0,'post','',1),(2355,2,'2015-01-08 10:16:18','2015-01-08 10:16:18','','des1','','inherit','open','open','','des1','','','2015-01-08 10:16:18','2015-01-08 10:16:18','',2354,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/des1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2356,2,'2015-01-08 10:16:37','2015-01-08 10:16:37','','des2','','inherit','open','open','','des2','','','2015-01-08 10:16:37','2015-01-08 10:16:37','',2354,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/des2-e1420712759168.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2358,22,'2015-01-08 12:18:04','2015-01-08 12:18:04','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>They came, they saw, they conquered!</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The world watched awe struck, as India propelled the much awaited “Mangalyaan”, to explore the mysteries that lay up there! From being touted as a mission that might not witness a successful outing to make a mark as the least expensive mission in the trail of missions, that failed to register success.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As Modi puts it, an auto rickshaw charges INR 10/km and the precarious journey to Mars that cost us just INR 7/km. The first among the successful greats in this capacity was Russia, which sent the ball rolling with a successful outing in 1971. Next in line was US, which nailed it in 1996 with The Mars ‘Odyssey’. Rover’s spirit and opportunity landed on mars with opportunity still sending back the nuances of Mars\' environment. India seems to have envisioned a very effective placement for itself amongst the Asian super powers, with Japan and China failing to show their prowess in this project so far.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Launched on 5<sup>th</sup> November, this mission registered several firsts to it-</p>\n\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<li>It does not follow the conventional straight flight trajectory, but will be placed in the elliptical earth orbit.</li>\n	<li>First in India to have civilian ships fitted.</li>\n	<li>For the first time, ISRO will operate spacecraft propulsion after 300 days.</li>\n	<li>A methane sensor that will indicate life possibility.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The spacecraft entered mars orbit this year on 21<sup>st</sup> September. The critical manoeuvre was nerve wrecking, yet successful. This 1350 kg craft has these features.</p>\n\n<ol style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<li>Built at Hindustan Aeronautics ltd.</li>\n	<li>Took 15 months to make<strong>.</strong></li>\n	<li>Made of mostly aluminium and carbon fibre, no exotic material.</li>\n	<li>Its manufacturing cost was Rs.450 Crore.</li>\n	<li>The orbiter is a mix of designs from INSAT and Chandrayan-1.</li>\n	<li>Its propellant has 5 payloads, and weighs 850 kg.</li>\n</ol>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Orbiter has specialised equipments to better its interpretation of mars, namely:-</p>\n\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<li>Composition analyser- to study Martian Atmosphere</li>\n	<li>Photometer- to study relative abundance of hydrogen</li>\n	<li>Colour camera- beam images and data on surface</li>\n	<li>Imaging Spectrometer- to tap surface mineralogy.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The orbit insertion put MOM in a highly elliptical orbit around Mars, with a period of 72 hours 51 minutes 51 seconds and a periapsis of 421.7 km (262.0 mi) and apoapsis of 76,993.6 km (47,841.6 mi). Commissioning and checkout operations are planned over the coming weeks to prepare MOM\'s instruments for science operations.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">At the end of the orbit insertion, MOM was left with 40 kg (88 lb) of fuel as against the 20 kg (44 lb) that was thought necessary for the six-month life span.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">On 28 September 2014, Mars Orbiter Mission published its first global view of Mars. The image was captured by the Mars Colour Camera (MCC).</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">On 19 October 2014, the ISRO reported that the Mars Orbiter Mission is healthy after the Comet Siding Spring flyby of Mars earlier that day.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">ISRO plans to send a follow-up mission with a greater scientific payload to Mars between 2018 and 2020. This mission will likely consist of a lander and rover, rather than being orbiter-only.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/mars2-e1420717034815.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-2360\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/mars2-e1420717034815.png\" alt=\"mars2\" width=\"300\" height=\"325\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This sums up the intricacies. And accolades came rushing in. With the meticulous mind behind it <strong>namely ISRO scientist C N R RAO</strong>, being bestowed the Bharat ratna, and immaculate mentions in time magazine as an invention much sought, this mission had definitely nudged India to carve a niche for itself as a distinguished superpower in the making! I salute ISRO, for pulling off such a challenge, and stepping into waters designed for the brave and the gifted.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The rover completed 100 days off late, and as Mr. Modi puts it, we had a wonderful new year indeed!</p>','India\'s Mars Mission - A Herculean Achievement!!!','','publish','open','open','','indias-mars-mission-herculean-achievement','','','2015-01-08 12:18:04','2015-01-08 12:18:04','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2358',0,'post','',0),(2359,2,'2015-01-08 11:32:59','2015-01-08 11:32:59','','mars1','','inherit','open','open','','mars1','','','2015-01-08 11:32:59','2015-01-08 11:32:59','',2358,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/mars1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2360,2,'2015-01-08 11:33:21','2015-01-08 11:33:21','','mars2','','inherit','open','open','','mars2','','','2015-01-08 11:33:21','2015-01-08 11:33:21','',2358,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/mars2-e1420717034815.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2367,2,'2015-01-09 03:57:28','2015-01-09 03:57:28','','10391012_443543659131026_747097952518649814_n','','inherit','open','open','','10391012_443543659131026_747097952518649814_n-2','','','2015-01-09 03:57:28','2015-01-09 03:57:28','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/10391012_443543659131026_747097952518649814_n1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2377,2,'2015-01-11 09:33:54','2015-01-11 09:33:54','<ul class=\"ch-grid\">\n    <li>\n        <div class=\"ch-item ch-img-1\">\n            <div class=\"ch-info\">\n                <h3>Sachin Garg</h3>\n                <p>Technology Lead<br/>B.Tech. IIT Delhi<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/sachinjnd\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://htmlsig.com/images/icon-komodo/facebook.png\" alt=\"Facebook\"></a></p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n    </li>\n    <li>\n        <div class=\"ch-item ch-img-2\">\n            <div class=\"ch-info\">\n                <h3>Keshav Sikdar</h3>\n                <p>Chief Editor<br/>B.A. Ramjas College<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/keshav0sikdar\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://htmlsig.com/images/icon-komodo/facebook.png\" alt=\"Facebook\"></a></p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n    </li>\n    <li>\n        <div class=\"ch-item ch-img-3\">\n            <div class=\"ch-info\">\n                <h3>Gaurav<br/>Jain</h3>\n                <p>Co-Founder, WebLead<br/>B.Tech. IIT Delhi<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/gauravjns\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://htmlsig.com/images/icon-komodo/facebook.png\" alt=\"Facebook\"></a></p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n    </li>\n    <li>\n        <div class=\"ch-item ch-img-4\">\n            <div class=\"ch-info\">\n                <h3>Dazi<br/>Bonal</h3>\n                <p>Co-Founder, Marketing<br/>B.Tech. IIT Delhi<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/dazi.bonal\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://htmlsig.com/images/icon-komodo/facebook.png\" alt=\"Facebook\"></a></p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n    </li>\n</ul>','Our Team','','publish','open','open','','team-3','','','2015-01-11 09:33:54','2015-01-11 09:33:54','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?page_id=2377',0,'page','',0),(2439,36,'2015-01-18 08:17:20','2015-01-18 08:17:20','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The image that the contemporary media portrays of the society, especially that of women is nothing but highly punitive. Gone are the days when beauty used to be in the eye of the beholder. Today, beauty rests only with women who have pursed lips, slender waist, high heels and lustrous hair. The skewed concepts of beauty in popular media have given birth to insecurity and discontent. The masses have blurred the line between what they see on TV and the reality. While it is implausible for everyone to look like the cover girls of Vogue, people still want to aspire for unrealistic desires.<strong>\n</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\nThe onus of looking “beautiful” primarily rests with women because it is the fairer sex that is viewed as sex objects since years. While men can get away with pretty much anything since whatever they do is supposed to be “manly” and “masculine”, women are the ones who have to toe the lines of femininity. And today’s popular media and culture is culpable of perpetuating unrealistic stereotypes and impossible notions of beauty.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\nTo illustrate my point, I would take up the example of Marion Bartoli. For those of you living under a rock, she was the first Frenchwoman to win Wimbledon since Amelia Mauresmo in 2006. While people should have been focusing on her outstanding victory, they chose to fixate on her looks. Apparently, many online bloggers and twitter users thought that since she was not a tall, skinny and blonde model, her achievement is utterly futile.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\nBinder (2013) says that these hateful and vile tweets like, “Bartoli looks like a cross between a man and an ape #notawimbledonbabe (sic)” and “Someone as ugly and unattractive as Bartoli doesn’t deserve to win” only goes to show that for a majority of people, women included, a female playing a sport is totally useless unless she is pleasing to the eye.\nAnd who decides whether a woman is attractive or not? The very same people who in reality wouldn’t stand anywhere close to the accomplishments that these women have achieved.\n</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">While Bartoli’s case is just one of the numerous examples of ridiculous notions of beauty that we see every day around us, instead of discarding such impossible expectations, people yearn to follow them. Maybe inspiration lies in actresses like Lea Michelle and Winona Ryder who were once asked to get a nose job in order to land a real acting gig, but thankfully they chose to ignore that advice.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\nHelen Razer (2010, as cited in Feminist Fatale) claims that the “efforts to expose the gruesome reality behind the beauty myth is a tiresome and unworthy battle that detracts focus from issues of real gender equality. I recall an era when feminism’s purview was not limited to banging on about the need for more fat chicks in glossy magazines. While others fight for the right to force-feed Kate Moss, I continue antique fretting over equal pay, domestic violence and federal representation. At 40, I am old and clearly out of step with a movement that demands Size 14 representation.”</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\nIt is also noteworthy to observe that the author of the personal website yourenotprettyenough.com, Jennifer Tress, chose such a URL when her first marriage ended after her husband cheated on her because, as he told her, she \"wasn\'t pretty enough.\" Tress, instead of letting such deprecating words destroy her, chose to start a body acceptance movement instead. Marie Claire (2013) ,reports that Tress was appalled when she realized as to how a huge amount of traffic on her site was generated. “I realized that so many people -- thousands every month -- were reaching my site after Googling phrases such as \"Am I pretty enough?\" It was startling. At first I thought, why are you asking the Internet? It\'s like asking a Magic 8 Ball! But that sparked something in me. I wanted to take action.”</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\nWhich is why the crux of the matter still remains that grey hair and lines around the eyes might make a woman repulsive; it does not exclude a man from being a potential love interest. This double standard that is prevailing in the society needs to be seriously addressed.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\nHowever, there are people like Marion Bartoli, who despite all the criticism and insults flung towards them, know how to take it all in their stride. As Bartoli puts it, “It doesn’t matter, honestly. I am not blonde, yes. That is a fact. Have I dreamt of having a model contract? No. I’m sorry. But have I dreamed about winning Wimbledon? Absolutely, yes.”</p>','Is Any Woman “Pretty Enough”?','','publish','open','open','','woman-pretty-enough','','','2015-01-18 08:17:20','2015-01-18 08:17:20','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2439',0,'post','',0),(2440,2,'2015-01-18 08:10:56','2015-01-18 08:10:56','','bnm','','inherit','open','open','','bnm','','','2015-01-18 08:10:56','2015-01-18 08:10:56','',2439,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/bnm.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2444,36,'2015-01-18 08:57:21','2015-01-18 08:57:21','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It was the spring of 1952 – probably an exceptionally murky chapter in the history of humanity. The man who is often referred to as the father of theoretical computer science and who played an instrumental role as a code-breaker during World War II was subjected to chemical castration as a “treatment” for homosexuality. Shortly two years later, Alan Turing committed suicide after being intolerably repudiated for his sexual orientation. In 2013, the Queen granted Turing the Royal Pardon sixty years after his suicide. One might wonder that the world has come a long way in these sixty years. However, that thought could soon be dismissed.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Today, diverse voices have emerged in this era of democracy. Different elements of society are coming together to protest against homophobia and demand rights for the people of the LGBT community. In fact, this endeavor is gaining momentum with each passing second. However, while countries like South Africa and Canada have been catapulting the issue of gay rights in their legislative policies, myriad of stereotypes and prejudices remain. Hate crimes against homosexuals have doubled in Canada – a country otherwise known for providing asylum to LGBT people facing discrimination in their own countries. According to Statistics Canada, three-quarters of hate crimes against homosexuals involved violence. Even in a country like South Africa which boasts of the most progressive laws regarding homosexuality, intolerance remains deeply embedded among the people. According to a recent survey conducted in 2013, 61 per cent of the population feels homosexuality is still unacceptable and only a mere 8 per cent felt that homosexuality was not a problem to them. And that is just the tip of the iceberg. It is ghastly to imagine the scenario in those countries where anti-gay laws are stringently enforced.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The subject of gay marriage has always been in the cross hairs during with many people even going ahead to question the basic sanctity of marriage. Many choose to seek refuge behind the garb of religion and only a handful of liberals are candid enough to lend support to the LGBT community. The apple of discord remains as to whether trans-genders or homosexuals are “against the order of nature”.  More importantly, is it reasonable to grant homosexual couples the same rights and privileges that are granted to heterosexual couples?\n\nLet us begin by acknowledging that the lesbian, gay, bisexual and trans-gender people do what every other citizen tries to accomplish in his or her life. They want to pursue their goals and aspirations, find happiness and liberty and ultimately love and marry the person of their choice. They intend to do so without the fear of being judged or discriminated against. And, like their “straight” counterparts, they also want a nurturing family. So why do certain people wish to trample upon these desires and expectation? Why are people contriving arguments that only go on to augment their bigotry and prejudice? Is the world that we live in so cruel that we need to levy a ban on love?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\nMany countries of the countries have labeled homosexual sex as “unnatural” and some political figures have even gone ahead to proclaim that since homosexual couples are unable to further the human race they are therefore frowned upon. This comes as a rude shock to many liberal-minded individuals who thought that producing babies was not the sole purpose of living. Are these countries going to penalize barren heterosexual couples as well? With close to 1,500 species of animals exhibiting homosexual behavior, is it time to understand that homophobia is unnatural but not homosexuality? Religious figures have been prescribing techniques and methods to “cure” members of the LGBT community for quite some time now.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Homosexual couples adopt children and consequently give those kids the care and affection they deserve, especially for difficult to place children. The children too, grow up in a liberal and tolerant household. In fact, compared to the fifty per cent accidental pregnancy rate among heterosexuals, gays and lesbians rarely become parents by accident thereby having a greater commitment and involvement in the child’s life. Their decision to start a family is usually well thought out. Yes, there are critics who continue to argue that only a union of the male and the female would provide an optimal environment for raising a child. However, these notions can quickly be debunked. A stable and loving family is the sole criterion for the proper upbringing of children, unlike families that fall apart due to divorce or lack of support among each other.\n\nHowever, the conservative countries continue to be at loggerheads with the rest of the world when it comes to LGBT rights. In the Commonwealth of Nations alone, 41 out of 53 countries continue to treat LGBT community as criminal, and the lacunae in their laws remain. We do not need to snatch away the rights of LGBT people to have families. Looking back in our lives, we don’t want our greatest moment in life to be the time when we deprived someone of love. As Barack Obama said, “Loving families come in many forms.” Well, they certainly do!</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>','The Times They Are Changing… Or Are They?','','publish','open','open','','times-changing','','','2015-01-18 08:57:21','2015-01-18 08:57:21','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2444',0,'post','',0),(2445,2,'2015-01-18 08:48:47','2015-01-18 08:48:47','','mnb','','inherit','open','open','','mnb','','','2015-01-18 08:48:47','2015-01-18 08:48:47','',2444,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/mnb.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2450,39,'2015-01-19 08:01:52','2015-01-19 08:01:52','<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>  <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Je ne suis pas Charlie</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Charlie Hebdo – the words that have been a part of our lives for the past few days now. I see status updates where people claim to be Charlie. I tried asking a few of them whether they even knew what being Charlie means or if they actually know who this Charlie was. The response I got was.. surprising, to say the least. Most of the people think that Charlie Hebdo is the name of a person who was killed in Paris attacks, some (read Hindutva supporters) think that Charlie Hebdo is a magazine which speaks against Islam and is therefore nice. So, it is my duty to clarify two basic things before we start this topic: firstly, Charlie Hebdo is NOT the name of a person, it is the name of a weekly magazine; secondly, it is NOT just an anti-Islamic magazine, it is an anti-religious magazine and has published numerous blasphemous cartoons of Hinduism, Christianity and Judaism as well. Having established these two basic facts, let’s take a close look at what being Charlie necessarily means.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When we talk about Charlie Hebdo, the first thing that comes to our mind is terrorism, then comes Islamic terrorism, and then comes freedom of expression. So, let’s start with the point that really matters – freedom of expression. Freedom to express your views forms the basic foundation of anything that claims to be democratic in nature, but there has always been a limitation put to the extent of this freedom. Why? Because people tend to take insults personally, and it results in the lack of harmony. One person’s freedom to express becomes the other person’s source of humiliation and when something as strong as the idea of God or religion is dragged into this debate, the result is Charlie Hebdo. Every nation varies significantly when the extent of this freedom comes to light. I’ll give you an instance, besides Charlie Hebdo, that accentuates my point. Recently, a man named Raif Badawi was sentenced to ten years’ imprisonment and 1,000 lashes by the government of Saudi Arabia because he dared to run a website that encouraged religious and social discussions. He received the first 50 lashes of his punishment just a few days ago. That’s freedom of expression for you in one of the richest countries of the world. In India, we have a fundamental right to speech and expression. But, we have limitations put, in the Indian Penal Code, that restrains our right to exercise this freedom - the section 153A which deals with criminalization of utterances that promote disharmony and feelings of enmity, hatred being groups, section 298 which penalizes the utterance of words which might hurt the religious feelings of a person., etc. So, in theory, there can be no Charlie Hebdo in India.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Coming back to the Charlie Hebdo attacks, France that cries about the freedom of expression has just recently banned the wearing of <em>niqaab </em>or veil by woman. Now, looks like a progressive step towards modernization doesn’t it? But, is it really? I mean is it not for the woman to decide whether or not she wants to wear a niqaab? On one hand you say that it is wrong to force such a thing on a woman, and then you force it away. How is that right? What if there are some devout Muslim women who want to wear a niqaab out of their own will? Aren’t you taking their freedom to choose what they want to wear away from them? The problem with us is that when a coin is thrown at us, we forget to look at its flipside. Same has happened with the case of Charlie Hebdo. While we are all one against the attack of terror which, no doubt, is highly condemnable. We fail to look at the other side of the coin when we declare ourselves to be Charlie. What does it mean to be Charlie? Doesn’t it mean drawing cartoons which are not just anti-religious or blasphemous, but are walking the line of bigotry? Having a view and expressing it is one thing but expressing it in a way that utterly humiliates the sentiments of not just one person but the entire sect of people, that is totally a different thing. To me, that is Charlie. And I am proud to say that ladies and gentlemen – I am, definitely, not Charlie. But, also, I definitely stand with Charlie. I support the fact that even if your views are so radically different, you have a right to express it. I do not support what Charlie Hebdo cartoons said and if I were put in the place of the publisher I would never, on account of decency, stoop so low. But, does that mean the answer is to massacre a bunch of people who hold a different view? Is that what we are becoming now? The answer to a humiliating cartoon is another humiliating cartoon, not a dozen of dead people! And pulling God in front of this is just pathetic. There is no God who does not have a sense of humour. And how the hell do you even know if your God is offended by something? Is that how puny a God is? Being offended by the cartoons that are drawn by mere mortals? If that is so, apparently, God has an ego problem. By justifying the killings in the name of Allah, the terrorists just managed to stain his name. By killing people because they insulted your religion, the terrorists managed to justify the blasphemy that Charlie Hebdo cartoonists did. All that the terrorists managed to do was make the life of the Muslims a lot harder than it already was. As if racism wasn’t already a problem in their lives.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">And that is the other aspect brought out by these attacks - the anti-Islam feeling. Now, what the hell is that all about? Just because a bunch of Muslim fanatics come up and shoot people in the name of their God does not, and I repeat, does NOT mean that Islam is a bad religion! If you take violence done in the name of God to be the measure of how dirty a religion is, why not start from the dark ages when there were Crusades ordered by the Pope in which thousands of people died? What about the days when Ku-Klux clan used to burn people alive? And when women were declared witches and burnt? And it’s not just the Christianity, do I need to remind people of all the disgusting harassments that the “upper-caste” Hindus have been putting the so-called lower castes through? Every religion has people who are bad and every religion also has people who are good. It is the people who are good or bad, NOT their religion and definitely not their God.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I may not be Charlie and I may find the cartoons published in the magazine outrageous, but I do think that all the Charlies have a right to live and express their opinion. In the words of Voltaire – “<em>I do not </em><em>agree with what you have to say, but I\'ll defend to the death your right to say it!</em>”</p>','Charlie Hebdo - \"Je ne suis pas Charlie\"','','publish','open','open','','charlie-hebdo-je-ne-suis-pas-charlie','','','2015-01-19 08:01:52','2015-01-19 08:01:52','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2450',0,'post','',6),(2452,2,'2015-01-19 07:56:49','2015-01-19 07:56:49','','Charlie-Hebdo','','inherit','open','open','','charlie-hebdo','','','2015-01-19 07:56:49','2015-01-19 07:56:49','',2450,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/charlie-hebdo.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2455,2,'2015-01-19 13:29:15','2015-01-19 13:29:15','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Life is short and it gives only one chance. However, many of us are not too fortunate to experience a true life. It can be due to many reasons: Accident, Diseases, Infections, etc.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">But, we who consider ourselves very civilized and literate can give them another chance.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"> While debating on this topic many would think that is it really possible? Yes, it is really possible! If you are thinking how it is possible, then I will tell you through ‘Blood Donation’. Sometimes we the so called civilized and literate people who have enough to eat, drink and wear consider money as the main solution to all problems. But donating money for a blood cancer patient or a bone marrow disorder patient would do him no good. Rather I will tell you it is just wasting money or sometimes it is an easy way to hide your black money.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"> If one really wants to help these people then why not donate your blood for them?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It won’t do any harm to you, but you may contribute a little to save a person’s life.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Donating blood should be one’s passion not a fashion. More over it gives one the joy of saving a person’s life.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"> While thinking for this people many Non Profit Organizations like <a href=\"http://www.helpiez.org\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Helpiez</strong></a> and <a href=\"http://www.bloodconnect.org\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>BloodConnect</strong></a> have come up with various innovative methods to publicize about Blood Donation and it gives real joy to see that how the young generation of our country is coming forward to be a part of this new trend and philosophy. They don’t want money for donating blood, instead their Facebook status updates tell “Feeling Happy Donated Blood”. If they can do it then why not the elders of our society who are still attached to year old traditions of Vedas? Someday or sometime it may save his own life or his family member’s or his friend’s life.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"> So let us make Blood Donation a trend. But before donating your blood consider checking the instruments is use and make sure they are using new needles for every person. Also the Health Department of each and every state of India and even the Government of India should waste some of their precious time and formulate some new policies to popularise Blood Donation Campaign. I am sure you will feel good after donating your precious blood as it will surely save a person’s life.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"> Let us make a slogan, “Blood Donation, one step towards humanity!”</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"> <strong>PS – BloodConnect </strong>is a social startup by IIT-D students with the aim to provide cheap access of blood to everyone in dire need of it. They organise many camps all across the Delhi/NCR region to achieve their noble aim. And they are starting a never-like-before campaign for the same named as ‘The Benevolence Campaign’. They are going to organise huge no. of camps throughout the city in the next month. Let us all support them in their wonderful pursuit. To know more, visit <a title=\"Here\" href=\"http://www.bloodconnect.org\" target=\"_blank\">www.bloodconnect.org</a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>','Blood Donation','','publish','open','open','','blood-donation','','','2015-01-19 13:29:15','2015-01-19 13:29:15','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2455',0,'post','',0),(2456,2,'2015-01-19 13:22:12','2015-01-19 13:22:12','','bc','','inherit','open','open','','bc','','','2015-01-19 13:22:12','2015-01-19 13:22:12','',2455,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/bc.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2463,32,'2015-01-20 04:11:08','2015-01-20 04:11:08','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Sometimes life leaves us in dilemma of what to do and what not?  We know the law but still remains silent because this time wrong is being done at our homes and neighbour. A girl in my neighbour who was married last year came back to her home from her in-laws. She was brutally abused by her husband. What was her mistake? What crime has she committed that she was so badly beaten by her husband? I think no one in this world has authority to do this inhuman act. We very well call ourselves civilised and talk about Mars but still remains in the  shackles of evil called domestic violence. It purports to be an act of inequality prevailing at our homes. People do talk about social evils in public to maintain their image but forget how to treat their own women.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In this 21<sup>st</sup> century we are talking about liberalisation but we are unable to liberalise our thoughts. The old norms of our patriarchal society are so deeply rooted in us that we consider acts of violence as normal course of life. Our society is <strong>“ok”</strong> with these acts. We often hear in our society <strong>“ <em>are itna to chalta hai” </em></strong>. We know everything but still continue to be a silent spectator. Why do we have to tolerate anything? A girl who wants to stand on her own is not allowed to work by her in-laws is acceptable by our society. Another girl who was burnt to death for dowry was also accepted by society. But the government did not accept it this time and came up with domestic violence act. And adding to it, a campaign called “<strong><em>bell</em></strong> <strong><em>bajao andolan”</em></strong> (ring the bell) against domestic violence was initiated in 2013. It says if you hear any sound of violence from neighbour then go and ring the bell. This ringing bell will let the perpetrator know that their acts are being noticed by the neighbours. And at least for that time violence can be stopped. But the real fight is to be done by victims themselves.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>What is domestic violence?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Domestic violence is creating fear in the mind of a person by another partner by abusing physically, emotionally or economically. It is misuse of power by one over another.  This is called <strong>silent crime.</strong> Domestic violence act defines it as any act which harms or has potential to cause harm.  The victim can be both men and women including children but in our country majority are women because of patriarchal system. The examples of male victims are very few. To file a case of domestic violence there is no need of a prolonged torture only an act of violence can constitute domestic violence.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Background of domestic violence</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The patriarchal society is the root cause of this violence.  Women are always considered to be weak and fragile. Male always dominated women. They used and abused them several times. Even the cultures and traditions considered women to be inferior. It is true that some women are on equal footing with men in today’s world but what about those housewives who are denied basic standard of living.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Types of violence</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Physical violence includes “beating, slapping, kicking, biting, punching or any other type of physical torture and pain. It also includes sexual violence like “marital rape, forcing to watch pornography etc”. Verbal violence like name calling (calling by degraded names), taunting in public, outraging modesty, accusing for different things, dowry demands, not giving food to eat, forcing to join or leave office etc. Or any type of act which is against the will of the victim constitutes domestic violence.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Impact of domestic violence </strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>On victim- </strong>Victim suffers from lot of physical and mental injury which leads to lifetime marks. The injuries caused by domestic violence not only give pain but sometimes destroys the reproductive health. Sometimes it makes the victim partially or fully disabled. And sometimes it results in the death too.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>On children and others</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When children see domestic violence in their family they get affected. They grow up very aggressive and can commit suicide or do wrong acts. They are more prone to drug addiction and crimes especially sexual crimes.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>What should domestic violence victim do?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Whenever any act of violence is committed the victim should not keep quiet and immediately move to the nearest police station to file a FIR against it under domestic violence act. They can also make a complaint under section 498A of IPC.. The act provides that a guilty person will be penalised and will be sent to jail.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Who is a victim?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The victim can be male, female, child or live in partner of the perpetrator. In the recent judgment court said that a women can also complaint against her daughter or daughter in law for domestic violence. So the ambit of the act is widened and more benefit to people is given. Any person who is in domestic relation with the perpetrator can make a complaint. It is not gender specific law even males can file for domestic violence but it is very less seen in our society. Sometimes this law has been misused but now strict guidelines are made to avoid harassment of innocent. No direct arrest can be made against without proper enquiry. Further, the act provides for various protection officers who can be called for help and victim can stay at shelter homes.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The law is not about man or woman it is about domestic abuse. It is about our inefficiency to ensure basic human rights to all. The government has done its part now it is us who has to raise voice against it. Because a law will not change anything it is the mindset that has to be changed. So next time if you suffer from any type of violence don’t keep your mouth shut but take a stand for yourself. As it is truly said <strong><em>“God help those who help themselves”</em></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>','Domestic Violence Act 2005','','publish','open','open','','domestic-violence-act-2005','','','2015-01-20 04:11:08','2015-01-20 04:11:08','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2463',0,'post','',0),(2464,2,'2015-01-20 04:10:18','2015-01-20 04:10:18','','hg','','inherit','open','open','','hg-2','','','2015-01-20 04:10:18','2015-01-20 04:10:18','',2463,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/hg.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2466,43,'2015-01-20 08:06:49','2015-01-20 08:06:49','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Marriage, an unconditional union of two individual souls who decide to spend the rest of their lives together till the ‘death to part us’, can also be the cause of a lifelong agony for some of us. As horrifying as it may appear, marital rape actually is an alarming factor questioning the sole basis of your concept of marriage. So when you grew up dreaming constantly about \'big-fat-weddings\' and \'happily-ever-afters\', years later, just after you are married to your \'so-called-prince-charming\', you are shattered to find out he is a wolf in sheep’s skin raping you day in day out.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rape is the word, hearing which every woman shudders and prays not to be a victim of it. You can run away from the man loitering in the dark at the end of the street, or from a stranger with a dagger, or from the devilish distant relative of yours who seeks pleasure in sexually exploiting you, but you are not left with the option of running away when that person is your husband, who was going to be the default member of your life, the person you fell in love with, the person who is or probably would become the role model of your child? What sort of love is that, when he is deriving pleasure out of you only to leave you violated?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are women, who simply are not aware of that fact that they are the victims of marital rape. They are schooled and influenced by the male chauvinist of the society mentally feeding them the concept of the husband being the god and the wife being the blind devotee. For them it’s a sin to refuse to the needs of their husbands even if it means having sexual intercourse against their will. However, the numerous source of study reveals that an equivalent number of women are aware of being a victim, do not raise their voice. They withhold themselves deepening the scar of agony and succumb into the fear, the fear of disruptive marriage, the fear of being harmed physically, the fear of their children being affected.   Not you or me or the girl with a scar or the lady in pink or blue asked for it, no one did and certainly don’t deserve to prolong this torture and stay in the marriage at the expense of their happiness.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">You don’t want to eat breakfast with a rapist every morning and not a single sane man wants to be the one raping their wife, when they swore to be the knights protecting them, not sexually assaulting them. Keeping mum about it never was and never will be an option. In the end you have to be the one to make a choice either decide to mutually resolve this into a better understanding, stating and satisfying the needs of both or you should seek for justification using the laws formed against the marital rape. Seek help if you must. Reach out to the helping hands and you’ll find a way.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Love as Human Feeling or physical satisfaction</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/bgt.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-2468\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/bgt.jpg\" alt=\"bgt\" width=\"500\" height=\"332\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>                  </strong><strong>            </strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Love is like a secret code, uniquely defined and distinguished by every single relationship, can be understood only by individual souls who share it. There are infinite shades of love. You love your dress, food, gadgets, family and it could be an endless list. The romantic love has always been one the most powerful portrayal of love and yet it is a feeling which controls you like a puppet on a string or a remote controlled toy robot. Then what is it that drives us happily towards insanity, stay up all night, sing, daydream and even kill, is beyond anyone’s comprehension.  Helen Fisher said, ‘Romantic love is one of the most addictive substances on earth. It’s a good one if things are falling perfectly into their places and a bad one if relationship is a battle field.\'</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It’s pretty much a universally acknowledged thing that your love for your ice cream is completely different than what you feel for your partner. The love which you feel for your partner starts from the desire of being desired by each other. Often the desire for lust and love has been misinterpreted. Love needs no concrete evidence to prove its existence over lust because surely Shakespeare and Jane Austen weren\'t making things up, they didn\'t mix up love with their desires. Almost everyone has gone through the phase of either being rejected by someone they really loved or has dumped someone who really loved them. In short no one has escaped from love unscathed yet they don’t turn to their backs when love comes knocking at their door. Then why do try to scale two different parameters?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Studies reveal that romantic love is about finding your partner for mating and sex is mating with whole different range of potentially attractive not for mating. Still even considering the slightest possibility that love is just a means of physical satisfaction, let’s reflect upon relationships of all ages. Starting with the teenagers, the curious cats of our society, let their physical needs drive them overboard, and the same can be the case for young adults, adults but what about the older generation, when your body is no longer craving to satisfy physical needs? How about the childhood sweethearts who end up dying together? If it was just about the physical needs, why bother making vows and spending eternity with one person? If love’s has survived for so long among us, the reason being just a mere physical satisfaction, then why do we fall in love with the person who is at the other end of the world? Whole concept of love being a physical satisfaction is a contradiction to itself.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"> Legends are told about love, stories are written and poems are composed. It’s the purest form of unconditional drive of love which binds the mankind together and there no point in doubting it.</p>','Marital Rape','','publish','open','open','','marital-rape','','','2015-01-20 08:06:49','2015-01-20 08:06:49','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2466',0,'post','',1),(2467,2,'2015-01-20 08:02:38','2015-01-20 08:02:38','','tgb','','inherit','open','open','','tgb','','','2015-01-20 08:02:38','2015-01-20 08:02:38','',2466,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/tgb.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2468,2,'2015-01-20 08:05:08','2015-01-20 08:05:08','','bgt','','inherit','open','open','','bgt','','','2015-01-20 08:05:08','2015-01-20 08:05:08','',2466,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/bgt.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2474,40,'2015-01-21 05:09:08','2015-01-21 05:09:08','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>Does today\'s generation feel its perks?</em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I recently stumbled upon a video of a famous standup comedian on YouTube where he narrates how 20s something people are shrug from the thought of marriage BECAUSE they have seen their parent\'s. And it got me thinking, why people DO GET MARRIED?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>I listed out a few reasons, which are true as per my knowledge only.</strong></p>\n\n<ol style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n	<li>Get financial security</li>\n	<li>Get consent for free sex, any time</li>\n	<li>Get emotional support</li>\n	<li>Get dowry</li>\n	<li>Get rid of parent\'s nagging</li>\n	<li>Spend live together</li>\n</ol>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">While most of the young people I know (70%) have married for the last 2 reasons, let\'s look at why other people choose the path of being someone\'s better half.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Financial security:</strong> Well, simply put, 2 people earning is better than just one. Some people may brood over marrying someone rich, so that they have extra money to blow off next sale season. And some might just think they\'re better off running a household who knows it better (a woman) than living in a 2 BHK apartment with 7 other fellows.\nBut on a serious note, folks in the earlier generations, especially women, were unfortunate to be either less educated or less persuaded to earn. So their financial security depended on the other half. But today, with couples earning almost equal individually, it’s more about living lavishly and with high self esteem if your partner earns good enough.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Consensual free sex:</strong> Unluckily sex is such a taboo in India that people would rather get married than pay bucks for it (with a risk of getting shame to family name) or stay single (and download illegal porn at a pathetic internet speed). But as we move towards a more open society, where LGBT community is starting to get accepted and Durex promotes safe sex on television, is that future very close where youngsters can tell their parents about an open or live-in relationship?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Emotional support:</strong> My question always remains, you want a family; don\'t you already have a family? How often do we call our moms and ask them about their day? Or text dad if we are in a fix? Or call our sister/brother and ask them if they\'re dating someone new? We just crib we don\'t have anyone to talk to- and the solution to that is marriage? Because REGARDLESS of how ALL OTHER RELATIONSHIPS worked out, we think this might be our pillar? Nope. I don\'t buy it. Maybe we should really talk to our family and friends first, they\'re always supportive- selflessly that too.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>The D word:</strong> Nowadays it’s not called \"dowry\". It\'s either “good luck wishes\" or \"amma appa\'s blessings\" or \"best wishes to new couple\". Well, in that case, shouldn\'t bride and groom JOINTLY prepare a list of things they want for their new life and hand it over to ALL RELATIVES; not just bride\'s.\nEven in the places Dowry is recognized as the age old <em>dahej pratha</em>, isn\'t giving good education to a girl child enough? Isn\'t bringing up a daughter as an equal to son enough? Isn\'t parting with a part of once someone\'s human body enough?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Pondering over these things, <em>maybe just maybe</em> the couples who have successful love marriages may feel like red roses and rainbows everyday; who still have a faith in the 7 pacts made around fire; who just want to spend their lives together and marriage provides a means to that.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">But to others, don\'t you think as smart independent individuals of today\'s generation, we should focus on feeling self satisfaction by being an awesome wholesome than just being known as someone\'s better half?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>','Marriage is an outdated institution','','publish','open','open','','marriage-outdated-institution','','','2015-01-21 05:09:08','2015-01-21 05:09:08','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2474',0,'post','',7),(2475,2,'2015-01-21 05:06:02','2015-01-21 05:06:02','','poi','','inherit','open','open','','poi','','','2015-01-21 05:06:02','2015-01-21 05:06:02','',2474,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/poi.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2492,2,'2015-01-23 09:21:16','2015-01-23 09:21:16','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Our country is swayed by two factions, one of them is the BOLLYWOOD and other being the political stints and gimmicks. To sum it up, it runs on ENTERTAINMENT ENTERTAINMENT ENTERTAINMENT.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Bollywood isn’t a topic to discuss (at least not here, my apologies to Big Boss fans) so we go with something even better than that, i.e. INDIAN POLITICS.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Indian politics, something that has been providing the country with its\' fair amount of laughter through its gimmicks and stature, all at a higher cost that we, the common people, end up paying. Be it the COAL GATE SCAM, 3G SCAM, KASHMIR DISPUTE or anything for that matter, our political system uses for its benefit. I know you’d be thinking why I call all these mere GIMMICKS when these have actually created a havoc in the market. Let me explain, the scenario is something like this: Our system believes in real good marketing and we have the best marketing heads in these parties. When a party can showcase RAHUL GANDHI as the PM candidate and still manage to win 44 seats, well! that shows even unimaginable can be achieved by these marketing geniuses. So getting back to the point, I call these scams as gimmicks because they are so well shaped that they come into light only after all the money is gone and when there are just peanuts left out.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">So as we speak about the political gimmicks , one such recent gimmick has caught our attention. In-fact the whole nation wants to know.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">We all love Mr. Narendra Modi, that is why we voted for him and his party emerged with absolute majority in the 2014 Lok Sabha Elections. After the campaigning in Maharashtra, Jharkhand and J&amp;K, along the similar line, Modi again is the selling point for upcoming Delhi elections. No doubt the Modi fever has gripped the nation. But our national capital, seemingly, is quite aware to be not swept by the sheer promise of Utopia. The people of Delhi have their eyes set on another party run by a self proclaimed AAM AADMI who created a stir in the local elections last year by claiming a large chunk of electoral seats, Mr. Arvind Kejriwal. Once a close associate of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anna_Hazare\">ANNA HAZARE</a> and then the founder of the AAM AADMI PARTY . The party made news when it emerged as surprise winners in the state election and when it came to power. But as the common man makes bad decisions, our newly appointed CM, Mr. Arvind Kejriwal did make a blunder i.e. by resigning his post after just 49 days . Which the whole country agrees was a blunder. We get it, common man makes mistakes and we forgive him for that.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Now let’s talk about our Delhi elections which is slated to happen on Feb 7<sup>th</sup>, 2015. Get your voter id cards ready , it is time to vote. First step to vote is to know your leaders. Let us tell you about them.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aam_Aadmi_Party\"> AAM AADMI PARTY</a>, we have Mr <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arvind\">Arvind Kejriwal</a>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bharatiya_Janata_Party\"> BJP</a>, until yesterday it was a campaign run on <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narendra_Modi\">MODI</a> and today it is <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kiran_Bedi\">KIRAN BEDI</a> (ex-super cop) , again, this is how she prefers to be called we do not want to hurt our ‘FUTURE CM’ . (You never know).</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">For congress, well, do you really want to know about Congress? I don’t think the nation wants to know about them anymore.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">So know your leaders. This is a campaign <a href=\"http://www.helpiez.org\" target=\"_blank\">HELPIEZ</a> is gonna run in Delhi till the elections, where we will speak to the COMMON MAN( now by common man, we refer to us, the bholi-bhali janta of Delhi) and give you their insights about whom to vote for and whom not to. Let’s face it, we know you are too lazy to research , so we will do it for you (no offence). All you need to do is regularly follow the blogs and we will give you the information and the views of common people on choosing your government this season and we will bring you the views that even our prestigious, \'unbiased\' NEWS CHANNELS will not give you.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Stay right here with us as we bring to you more fun and as we speak, the campaign has already started and our team is trying to dig deep for some exciting news and survey.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">We are <a href=\"http://www.helpiez.org\" target=\"_blank\">HELPIEZ</a> and we are here to help.</p>','Verdict of a common man','','publish','open','open','','verdict-common-man','','','2015-01-23 09:21:16','2015-01-23 09:21:16','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2492',0,'post','',1),(2494,39,'2015-01-23 04:52:51','2015-01-23 04:52:51','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When I was a kid being gay was considered taboo. Now, I’m not a kid anymore but being gay is still considered taboo. How are we moving ahead, then? While we are making progress on an economic front (and that, too, just on the surface of it), where are we on social development scale? Born in a nation which was, probably, among the first ones to acknowledge homosexuality and documenting it in a world renowned book – Kamasutra – it is only stupid if we cannot acknowledge gay marriages. We cannot even call it old-fashioned because in olden days, it wasn’t considered weird to be gay. As a matter of fact, among the Greeks, it was actually weird to NOT be gay. If you had never had a same-sex partner, it was considered awkward. Now, I might have confused myself between Greeks and Romans in this part, but you get the gist.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The much infamous article regarding homosexuality is the section 377 of the Indian Penal Code (NOT the constitution). Drafted in 1860, we have held on to the views of our policy makers of the 19<sup>th</sup> century. It is amazing how we talk about rights against discrimination, and right to freedom of religion when we totally ignore the most basic human right – to choose a companion! I mean, that’s not even worth mentioning. Each person should have the right to choose his or her life-partner. It is their life, they have to live it and, hence, it is only natural that they get to choose who they want to spend it with. What I don’t understand is HOW and when did it start being “unnatural”? And what do we mean when we say “unnatural”? If we see the term in its most basic sense, it would mean anything that is not natural, right? So, is the industry not unnatural? Did we have factories which were always there as a part of our nature? Is this laptop which you are using not unnatural? Is religion natural? Is a person born with an innate religion? If anything, being gay is the most natural thing there can be. One doesn’t learn or acquire a sexual orientation. It is just there! <em>Au naturel</em>!</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Now, it is a totally different thing if you don’t like something. But that does not mean that you should condemn it, dubbing it unnatural. Let’s take my example - I abhor stupidity. I cannot stand stupid people. But, stupidity is also natural. I don’t see a law that states that stupid people are “unnatural” and hence should be put behind bars! Though, I would sincerely like it very much if they introduced such a law. I also do not like people taking butt-selfies and THAT is not even natural! Why don’t we have a law that makes taking butt-selfies a crime? If we can be tolerant towards so many things and attributes, why discriminate on the basis of sexual orientation? What is wrong if a man likes another man or if a woman likes another woman? You don’t like being gay, who is asking you to be gay? You think two people of the same gender having sex is disgusting, who is asking you to have it? YOU do not decide what someone else should be or not be. It is my life, I get to choose what I want to do, how I want to do it, or who I want to do it with. It is the violation of the most elemental human right when we criminalize a gay-marriage.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are real problems in this world that we need to deal with – terrorism, energy crisis, global warming, water crisis, population explosion, unemployment.. I could go on throwing one problem after the other, but being gay is not one of them. Being gay is not a problem. Being gay is not unnatural. And I don’t see ANY possible reason how gay-marriage would affect the society in any way, apart from making it better, more tolerant and, therefore, happy. We have had revolutions which were booming with the sound of the word ‘Liberty’ and ‘Equality’. People have fought and died for this liberty and equality that we so easily think of as our own nowadays. Does this liberty not entail the liberty to choose who you want to marry? Does the equality not guarantee equality for all? Or was there a sub-clause during those revolutions which marked a * near liberty and equality and at the bottom of it, in really small font size, declared *terms and conditions applied? Let people live their lives. Government is meant, as the word suggests, just to govern not dictate the ways in which we should be living. The task of the government is to make sure that the married couples are safe, not to order who they should be marrying. As soon as the policy-makers understand this simple concept, we can move ahead together and get this dust off our shoulders.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>','Should Gay Marriage Be Legaized Or Not ?','','publish','open','open','','gay-marriage-legaized-not','','','2015-01-23 04:52:51','2015-01-23 04:52:51','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2494',0,'post','',1),(2495,2,'2015-01-23 04:46:25','2015-01-23 04:46:25','','fv','','inherit','open','open','','fv','','','2015-01-23 04:46:25','2015-01-23 04:46:25','',2494,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/fv.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2500,2,'2015-01-23 05:29:16','2015-01-23 05:29:16','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In India we are at an age wherein people who pass Whatsapp messages or keep Facebook statuses about standing up for a crime by an influential person or by standing up for something they believe in are arrested. Perplexed? Hold it there, there is more to come. On the other hand, there are people who commit hideous crimes such as rape and murder and are yet to have an FIR lodged against them. More confused? this is the sad reality.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">What is the meaning of a democratic country? It is a country where the people have the right to give their opinions openly and stand up for what they believe. But here in India when an individual or an institution starts to make sense by their ideas, there are political parties and their \"goondas \" barging into offices and indulging into vandalism.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Let us take a recent example. After the release of Aamir Khan\'s PK there were protests and top multiplexes were vandalized. We are to understand that because PK tried to put in some sense into people by sharing their ideas, their screens will be vandalized?. I mean the censor board did not have any problems and these gunda\'s of self proclaimed baba\'s are taking the law into their own hand. Absolutely ridiculous.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If the people of a country are not allowed to voice out their opinions in peace then how can anyone hope for growth in a country?. Growth happens when new ideas come in. If people want to cling on to old medieval ideas and beliefs then how will the country progress?. We are in 2015 and need to leave behind our orthodox culture behind and let people to come out of their shell and speak up.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This brings me down to a very interesting example. Malala rose up to fight for the education of women. Yes she was shot by the Taliban but her belief was strong enough to save her. My point is that shutting people up with force is not going to help. We need to let them speak so that a difference can be made. Ultimately it’s Malala being praised for the work she is doing for the society and not the Taliban.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>','Right Of Expression Of Speech Of An Individual','','publish','open','open','','right-expression-speech-individual','','','2015-01-23 05:29:16','2015-01-23 05:29:16','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2500',0,'post','',0),(2501,2,'2015-01-23 05:22:21','2015-01-23 05:22:21','','gbt','','inherit','open','open','','gbt','','','2015-01-23 05:22:21','2015-01-23 05:22:21','',2500,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/gbt.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2503,2,'2015-01-23 05:28:22','2015-01-23 05:28:22','','azx','','inherit','open','open','','azx','','','2015-01-23 05:28:22','2015-01-23 05:28:22','',2500,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/azx.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2505,2,'2015-01-23 08:43:10','2015-01-23 08:43:10','','Indian-politicians','','inherit','open','open','','indian-politicians','','','2015-01-23 08:43:10','2015-01-23 08:43:10','',2492,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/indian-politicians.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2516,39,'2015-01-23 16:38:09','2015-01-23 16:38:09','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">With the Delhi elections’ campaign going on, I was reading about the related happenings – same old accusations, bribery, promises. But suddenly,a few days ago, something happened which forced me to stop just reading and start writing about the elections as well. I am pretty sure that all those who have been following this turn of events, would have guessed what I’m talking about; for those who couldn’t, I’m talking about Kiran Bedi joining the Bharatiya Janta Party and being alleviated to the position of a Chief Ministerial candidate. The announcement took me, if not the entire nation,by a HUGE surprise. I was just thinking of a word to describe this decision of Kiran Bedi when a friend of mine did it for me – opportunism. And the word hits the spot JUST right. Here was a woman standing in front of the television cameras and waving, the same woman who criticized Arvind Kejriwal like ANYTHING when he broke away from the anti-corruption campaign of Shri Anna Hazare to from the Aam Aadmi Party. Kiran Bedi admonished this move of Kejriwal by saying that politics was dirty and that she was against politics. So, what is this then? Did she join BJP because she doesn’t like politics? Or did these past two years, somehow, brought about a phenomenal change in her perspective and made her pro-politics? Now, I don’t know what other people’s opinions are but as I am here to express my own, I’ll take some time to do that. I’ll just discuss a few points which came to my mind when I read about Kiran Bedi. And I’ll do in points:</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">1. As I have discussed above, for some strange reason, Kiran Bedi has turned from anti-politics to pro-politics within a short time-span of less than an year. It was just last year, I think in October, when she denied any news of her joining BJP or politics. Now, after just a few months down the line, we have Kiran Bedi as the CM candidate, running for elections from the Krishna Nagar constituency as a member of BJP. Now, bluntly speaking – what the hell is that all about? Were those words just some hollow rumblings of a person who considers herself to be an idealist? And why criticize Kejriwal for joining politics just a couple of years ago? Is it like those times when you suddenly have the limelight, and then you don’t, and then someone comes along and offers you the limelight again and you jump at the chance of getting it? And what’s bad if the limelight brings with it some powers as well, right?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">2. Suddenly, the face of Shri Narendra Modi has become a “beautiful” one. Kiran Bedi was found statsing that, *“BJP has got the world\'s most beautiful face with it, i.e. Narendra Modi and his leadership. After that we are just stars who are revolving around him.”* The same Mr. Modi whom she condemned, and even blamed, for the infamous Gujarat riots all of a sudden has a beautiful face and is a great leader. Anyone, besides me, who has heard the phrase “थाली का बैंगन” and finds it suitable in this scenario?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3. Do you people know what has kept India united after being through so much? All the troubles that our nation has been through, there was one organization that kept us united and is very nationalistic. Any guesses? Let me kill the suspense – it is RSS. You read it right if I heard it rightly. Kiran Bedi stated that RSS is a very disciplined and “nationalistic” organization which has kept India united. Apparently, being nationalistic means calling India a Hindu Rashtra, i.e. a land of the Hindus. Also, it is pretty clear that when it was one of the leaders in the demolition of Babri Masjid, it was all for the sake of India’s unity. Isn’t it?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4. Let’s jump to Kiran Bedi’s “illustrious” career now. As pointed out by a renowned journalist Karan Thapar, “She didn’t complete her tenure as SP in Goa, DIG in Mizoram, IG (Prisons) in Tihar Jail and IG of Police in Chandigarh.” We can very well see that running away isn’t just a remark we need to reserve for Arvind Kejriwal, Kiran Bedi is actually a senior in this respect. She was also accused of getting an admission for her daughter in a Delhi’s medical college under the seats reserved for people from Mizoram. That’s when she was posted in Mizoram.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">5. Evidently, it isn’t just the people of Mizoram who have had issues with Kiran Bedi and her performance of duties. In the year 1988, there was a peaceful protest by the lawyers of Delhi. Kiran Bedi, who was in charge at the time, ordered a lathi charge on the lawyers. There was a committee–headed by Justice Wadhwa – who looked into this case and recommended that Kiran Bedi was not to be given a senior post in Delhi as her actions were unjustified.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">She is brave, she is outspoken and she is our nation’s first female IPS officer. But is she the correct choice for the post of Delhi’s Chief Minister? Someone who was recommended by the Wadhwa committee to not be given a senior post in Delhi now runs for the highest post of Delhi. Rings a bell for me; should do for you, too. Think before you choose because this time, there will be no running away for the next 5 years.</p>','Ummeed ki Kiran?','','publish','open','open','','ummeed-ki-kiran','','','2015-01-23 16:38:09','2015-01-23 16:38:09','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2516',0,'post','',1),(2523,2,'2015-01-23 16:34:22','2015-01-23 16:34:22','','KIRAN-BEDI-OLD-TWEETS','','inherit','open','open','','kiran-bedi-old-tweets','','','2015-01-23 16:34:22','2015-01-23 16:34:22','',2516,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/kiran-bedi-old-tweets.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2525,2,'2015-01-23 16:37:29','2015-01-23 16:37:29','','KIRAN-BEDI-OLD-TWEETS','','inherit','open','open','','kiran-bedi-old-tweets-2','','','2015-01-23 16:37:29','2015-01-23 16:37:29','',2516,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/kiran-bedi-old-tweets1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2533,32,'2015-01-25 21:14:12','2015-01-25 21:14:12','I don’t know whether the new government at centre fulfilled its so called election promises or not. But yes, it is successful in adding some new words to our vocabulary like “<strong>Ghar Wapsi</strong>”, “<strong>Swachh Bharat Abhiyan</strong>” etc. The controversial debate of <strong>converting</strong> non-Hindus to Hindu has gained much fire. The initiative led by RSS and VHP, aims at converting Christians and Muslims to Hindu. The statement by RSS supporter Rajeshwar Singh, <strong>“Ek din in girijagharo ki deewarein bhi gir jayengi aur hamara desh sirf hinduon ka hoga”</strong> attacks the basic structure of our constitution i.e. <strong>Secularism</strong>. Who gave them the right to do so?\n\nAre all the big problems of our country like unemployment, poverty, sex discrimination (a glimpse of the endless list we have) eradicated? Then why are we not working on them and taking about the so called \'ghar wapsi\'. What purpose will it serve? Will it increase our GDP or will poverty be done with? Are all the Hindus living a lavish life? We need the government to help those people who can’t even afford a single meal throughout the day and not to convert their religions.\n\nBy converting these people to Hindu, RSS is doing no good to anyone. Neither the converted nor the original Hindus are happy. Converted people are not happy because they have to surrender their faith in exchange of some money. And poor Hindus are not happy because they are not getting any money by government to meet their daily needs. We can see various examples around us, where people are converting for a sum of 5 Lac rupees. The Gardner who comes to my home, told his plight that, how Muslims in his locality changed to Hindu and got 5 lac rupees. And he got nothing as he is already a Hindu. Another person who got money after conversion took a taxi of his own and started his new business. The converted children will get free education. Every benefit is being given to people who are converted to Hindu. But what about those poor people, who are already Hindu? They are getting nothing from government. When will the supposedly “<strong>acche din”</strong> come for people like the gardener narrating his plight?\n\nThe ideology behind this whole conversion is to make India a Hindu centric state. But why? Why there is a need to make India, a Hindu state? Our Constitution is a secular one. It does not profess any religion, then who are they to do so? The words ghar wapsi mean coming back to home. So they want to purport that being Hindu is being home. And other religions are alien to us. NO, our constitution gives right to everyone to practice their own religion. And their religion is their home.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nNow let me tell you some ground reality about these programmes.\n\nAn old woman who recently converted to Hindu told the true reason of her faith change; she said “<strong>the RSS people promised her to give proper food and house for living and to educate her grandchildren”</strong>. She further said I changed my religion because my religion does not give me food. Is this type of conversion which takes advantage of someone\'s miseries justifiable in any sense? It is not only legally but morally wrong. When asked, the government responds by saying that we are not initiating it; true, but you are also not stopping it.\nAnd even if we talk about swachh bharat abhiyan the reality is same. This incidence happened last month. It was about 6 in the morning when I was going for work. I saw a big truck full of garbage throwing all the garbage on the roadside. I could not resist myself from asking the driver, the reason for this absolute absurdity.  He is supposed to clean the environment, then why was he littering? The man smiled at me and said this is being done for those ministers who will later in the day visit the place and clean it in the presence of media. This is the reality of our so called \'swachh bharat abhiyan\' by our ministers.\nDo we choose our PM to take a <strong>“jhadu”</strong> and clean the roads OR a CM to go on <strong>dharnas by sitting on road</strong> and finally leaving us in middle of nowhere after 40 odd days? Do we need ghar wapsi? Where is our country going?\nI am not saying that we don’t need a clean environment or proper electricity or for that matter anything. But proper authorities are designated to do all these things. If these people are really concerned about the dire state of our country, then make the authorities strict enough to regulate all the rules and laws. If we start penalising every person who litters in public and rewarding those who use the dustbins, then clean India would not be a distant dream. Similarly, conversion of the people for the sake of giving food is not justified. If you really want to help them, then support them, nurture their families, educate them; converting is not the solution.\n\nThe father of our nation Mahatma Gandhi said, “I can’t ask anyone to change his/her faith, as this is their personal matter. And I should respect their faith as I respect mine.” Even after the division of 1947, the constituent assembly didn’t feel to convert India into a Hindu state. Instead they made India a secular one. We all Indians do not want a ghar wapsi initiative because this will destroy the social fabric and brotherhood. We are already at our home i.e. <strong>INDIA</strong>. And INDIA constitutes all HINDUS, MUSLIMS, SIKHS and CHRISTIANS.\n\n<strong><em>“Hindu, Muslim, Sikh, Isai hum sab hai bhai bhai”</em></strong>','GHAR WAPSI- A THREAT TO SECULARISM?','','publish','open','open','','ghar-wapsi-threat-secularism','','','2015-01-25 21:14:12','2015-01-25 21:14:12','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2533',0,'post','',0),(2538,2,'2015-01-24 09:14:24','2015-01-24 09:14:24','A still image of Kiran Bedi','37330-a-still-image-of-kiran-bedi.jpg','','inherit','open','open','','37330-a-still-image-of-kiran-bedi-jpg','','','2015-01-24 09:14:24','2015-01-24 09:14:24','',2516,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/kiran-bedi.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2554,46,'2015-01-25 18:11:04','2015-01-25 18:11:04','','entrepreneurship-networking-advice-1','','inherit','open','open','','entrepreneurship-networking-advice-1','','','2015-01-25 18:11:04','2015-01-25 18:11:04','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/entrepreneurship-networking-advice-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2556,32,'2015-01-25 18:37:19','2015-01-25 18:37:19','','omqpwGbjbabed_small','','inherit','open','open','','omqpwgbjbabed_small','','','2015-01-25 18:37:19','2015-01-25 18:37:19','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/omqpwgbjbabed_small.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2564,32,'2015-01-25 19:16:03','2015-01-25 19:16:03','','omqpwGbjbabed_small','','inherit','open','open','','omqpwgbjbabed_small-2','','','2015-01-25 19:16:03','2015-01-25 19:16:03','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/omqpwgbjbabed_small1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2565,32,'2015-01-25 19:19:12','2015-01-25 19:19:12','','omqpwGbjbabed_small','','inherit','open','open','','omqpwgbjbabed_small-3','','','2015-01-25 19:19:12','2015-01-25 19:19:12','',2533,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/omqpwgbjbabed_small2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2568,45,'2015-01-25 19:53:27','2015-01-25 19:53:27','','del elections','','inherit','open','open','','del-elections','','','2015-01-25 19:53:27','2015-01-25 19:53:27','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/del-elections.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2571,45,'2015-02-06 05:11:56','2015-02-06 05:11:56','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The 2013 Delhi elections witnessed the emergence of a new phenomenon \"The Aam Aadmi Party\" led by the much acclaimed <a href=\"http://www.helpiez.org/blog/verdict-common-man/\"> Mr Arivind Kejriwal </a> whose claim to fame happens to be his constant involvement with Anna Hazare in his nationwide movement against corruption towards the implementation of the Lokpal Bill. The Aam Aadmi party, the formation of which essentially stemmed from the break-up between the two front-leaders of the \"India against corruption\" campaign due to difference of opinions did manage to ignite a spark of hope amongst the much-frustrated \"aam janta\" thanks to the Congress rule. In their bid to explore the unconventional and play against the odds, first time contender Aam Aadmi Party managed to secure 29 seats which was much more than anticipated by the exit polls. And then began the political drama where swinging and vacillating between the possibility of a government or not, Mr Kejriwal finally managed to secure the coveted throne as the Chief Minister with \"outside support\" from the Indian National Congress, a decision taken for the benefit of the population of Delhi, who he believed had given him a chance to bail them out of their miseries. But this wasn’t the end of the tale, declared as hopeless and vulnerable by some and branded as a victim of “political manipulation” by others, Mr Kejriwal tried to deliver but failed to impress.What followed was more and more Drama and now we have the Delhi 2015 elections where tables have turned and fortunes have swung. The odds aren\'t in favor of any one particular party but pundits have begun their calculations.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As the 7th of January nears, we have the Bhartiya Janta Party which is the \"hot property\" at the moment thanks to Mr Modi at the center and fresh new additions of <a href=\"http://www.helpiez.org/blog/ummeed-ki-kiran/\"> Kiran Bedi </a>, former IPS officer and also an aide of Anna Hazare and Kejriwal in the India against corruption movement and  Shazia Ilmi one of the founder members of the Aam Aadmi Party who have joined the bandwagon. Not to forget the Indian National Congress which is now led by Mr Ajay Makan, former minster of Youth Affair and Sports instead of the usual Mrs Shiela Dixit. And off course we have the last time surprise package, the very own Aam Aadmi party that has pretty much gone off track but seems to re-gain its momentum.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Be it the door-to-door campaign by the AAP or the \"Abhinandan rally\" by Mr Modi, political parties have left no stone upturned to ensure that they are able to establish their regime across the capital of the country when vote counts are revealed on the 10th of february 2014.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the meanwhile, possibilities and predictions have been going on full swing but going by the past records of the Delhi Elections, these might as well take a back seat. However, the important aspect in the story is that the people realize what works best for them instead of getting carried away by promises and temptations, because they are the ones who have seen it and they are the only ones who will get to see it in the years to come. Also it is important that they go out and cast their vote.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Hence it is a sincere appeal to the voters to make a choice and a well-informed choice, as they are the ones who have the power. The POWER TO DECIDE THEIR DESTINY.</p>','Delhi Elections 2015: What the voter needs to know?','','publish','open','open','','delhi-elections-2015-voter-needs-know','','','2015-02-06 05:11:56','2015-02-06 05:11:56','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2571',0,'post','',0),(2573,42,'2015-01-25 21:03:07','2015-01-25 21:03:07','','1360671219','','inherit','open','open','','1360671219','','','2015-01-25 21:03:07','2015-01-25 21:03:07','',2533,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/1360671219.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2578,38,'2015-01-26 05:28:04','2015-01-26 05:28:04','&nbsp;\n\nThere is a lot of camaraderie between the US and India and that is the news of the moment. The US President Barack Obama along with our own Indian hero Narendra Modi took a long walk along Delhi’s rose gardens. And the two leaders seem to be clicking and both of them claim to have “chemistry”.\n\nIndians all over fell in love with the US Prez when he spoke in Hindi and said “Namaste, Mera pyar bhara namaskar”. We all love our culture and the pride that we have in our language echoes when someone from outside speaks with us even if it is just one sentence.\n\nThe friendship and display of personal bond was evident right from the moment the he arrived. Our president rushed forward and there was an impromptu hug. It was just day one of the three day visit and a lot of important deals seem to have been signed and moved forward. Modi ji also surprised the world by calling the American president by his first name. It was just like old friends who were meeting up for a drink and hanging out, irrespective of their official posts.\n\nAll this would not have been likely just a few years ago. Our countries have always been amicable but we have had our ups and downs. In 2013, when an Indian diplomat was accused of ill treating her maid, paying her less and for lying on the visa papers. The diplomat was arrested and strip-searched in New York and there was quite some controversy. This didn’t go down in good spirits and there was a ripple in the relationship. In 2008, there was another tiny issue between the US and India regarding nuclear energy.\n\nBut lets not live in the past, as both the countries have seemed to move on. Obama has already visited India previously in 2010 and now he is here with the First Lady. There were plans the couple would visit the Taj Mahal but they have been scrapped as they are flying to Riyadh to pay respect to the dead Saudi Arabian king.\n\nAll this is just within day 1 of the visit. We have our R day celebration today and then another day to go before Mr. Obama leaves back and the great Indian wedding over here goes calm and the storm dies down. We will have much more to think about and debate about what we got from this visit.','“Chemistry” and all the bromance !','','publish','open','open','','chemistry-bromance','','','2015-01-26 05:28:04','2015-01-26 05:28:04','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2578',0,'post','',0),(2580,38,'2015-01-26 05:21:05','2015-01-26 05:21:05','U.S. President Barack Obama and India\'s Prime Minister Narendra Modi (R) shake hands after giving opening statements during a at Hyderabad House in New Delhi January 25, 2015. REUTERS/Jim Bourg','U.S. President Obama and India\'s PM Modi shake hands after giving opening statements during a at Hyderabad House in New Delhi','','inherit','open','open','','u-s-president-obama-and-indias-pm-modi-shake-hands-after-giving-opening-statements-during-a-at-hyderabad-house-in-new-delhi','','','2015-01-26 05:21:05','2015-01-26 05:21:05','',2578,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2584,38,'2015-01-26 06:52:01','2015-01-26 06:52:01','Indian culture is so renowned world over and India has fame as the land of myths and mystics. India is also quite known for its belief in the institution of marriage and the great Indian weddings are quite popular. While these are the bright things to look at, our country has also a great dark evil rooted in Indian weddings and the “d word” (dowry and not daughter) is going on for long. The system has been around for centuries and there doesn\'t seem to be a way out in the near future.\n\nThese days, modern, well-educated families start saving up money for their daughter\'s dowry as soon as she is born, so what can one expect from the uneducated masses who live all around India? Every father has a small worry always nagging him at the back of his head about how he is going to get her married some day.\n\nWe all condone the dowry system and think about how to end it but with or without our knowledge, we all contribute to it. Whenever there are elder people in the house, and there is a wedding coming up, they ask about what the girl would bring to the family. As younger generation, we generally do not give up on the system and it carries on.\n\nA lot of educated young boys these days do not ask for dowry and are happy with a normal wedding but the number of these boys is quite less compared to the whole population. Such a small change is definitely appreciable and yet at the same time a bigger change is needed to make an actual difference.\n\nThere are enough terrifying stories about how women are tortured when dowry demands are not met. The number of deaths never seems to go down. Also, no one talks about the mental stress that the girl goes through   when she is subjected to torment for no apparent fault of hers.\n\nIn modern times, boy’s parents don\'t demand dowry, but our culture is such that there is an inherent obligation that something has to be given during the wedding. It is more of a societal construct and something that is built in our heads. When we do this, it is true that we are contributing to the evil ourselves. If you do want to do something, do it for your daughter in her name. Do as much as you can but not because you are expected to.\n\nDowry has been outlawed in India right in 1961 but then in practicality, it is hard to implement it. A lot of times this evil is hidden under other excuses and does not stare directly at you. In fact, more than half of the cases of domestic violence are not even reported to law. So what can we do about it?\n\nToday’s girls are well educated and career oriented. If parents have educated their daughter well, then it is the best thing they could have done for her. She can live an independent life with self sufficiency and well the groom gets a loving wife who can also contribute to the family’s expenses. If we keep this going on we can maybe change the trend and break the chain of dowry.','D for dowry, or maybe not.','','publish','open','open','','d-dowry-maybe-not','','','2015-01-26 06:52:01','2015-01-26 06:52:01','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2584',0,'post','',0),(2585,38,'2015-01-26 06:47:53','2015-01-26 06:47:53','','say no to dowry','','inherit','open','open','','say-no-to-dowry','','','2015-01-26 06:47:53','2015-01-26 06:47:53','',2584,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/say-no-to-dowry.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2589,40,'2015-01-27 15:31:50','2015-01-27 15:31:50','It has been 2 years since people of Delhi-NCR and the rest of the country have been wondering who will be the next Chief Minister (CM) of the capital.\n\nIn the 2013 elections, the <strong>Bharatiya Janata Party</strong> (BJP) fell short of majority and was unable to form the government. This led to second largest party after the BJP, to attempt to form government and hence came the short lived CM from the<strong> Aam Aadmi Party</strong> (AAP). AAP\'s leader<a title=\"About Kejriwal on Wikipedia\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arvind_Kejriwal\" target=\"_blank\"> Arvind Kejriwal</a>, who had defeated the outgoing <a title=\"About Dikshit\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sheila_Dikshit\" target=\"_blank\">Sheila Dixit</a>, became CM.\n\nHowever this government only lasted for 49 days as Kejriwal resigned on 15 February 2014. Since then Delhi has been governed by President\'s rule.\n\nTo look at the <a title=\"Go to Wikipedia page for more\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chief_Minister_of_Delhi\" target=\"_blank\">Delhi’s political history</a>, starting 1952 for 4 years and 230 days <strong>Indian National Congress</strong> (INC) candidates Chaudhary Brahm Prakash and Gurumukh Nihal Singh ruled the capital. But for the next 37 years the office of CM of Delhi was abolished till 1993.\n\nIn 1998, <a title=\"Go to Swaraj\'s Wikipedia\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sushma_Swaraj\" target=\"_blank\">Sushma Swaraj</a> of BJP became the <em><strong>first women CM of Delhi</strong></em> but only for 52 days, concluding the 5 year reign of BJP in NCR. But shortly afterwards, Sheila Dixit of INC was sworn in as the next CM.\n\nOver her next 15 years in office, she was criticized for her lack of control over law enforcement, leading to a rise of crime in Delhi. This became the main propaganda of the newly appointed BJP candidate for chief minister <a title=\"Go to Bedi\'s Wikipedia page\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kiran_Bedi\" target=\"_blank\">Kiran Bedi</a>.\n\nWith the onset of her campaign, <a title=\"Go to details of this campaign | Bedi\'s FB page\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/thekiranbedi/photos/a.249866628663.141141.248055798663/10153035646393664/?type=1&amp;theater\" target=\"_blank\">Bedi announced women safety is a major concern</a> in Delhi and promised that if she comes into office, Delhi will be safer for women. The Focus will be on 5S: Saksham, Surakshit, Swasth, Saaksher, Sanskari.\n\nIf we consider<strong> case of probabilit</strong>y, thanks to Dixit (15 years out of 25 years in Delhi’s CM office), <em>a women candidate might just get elected this time for Delhi</em>. But then again, that’s just probability- we’ll leave that to the academicians and speakers on TV debates.\n\nLet’s look at the other grey areas which will decide the fate of Delhi. For the sake of simplicity, let’s assume there are only 2 candidates- men represented by Kejriwal and women represented by Bedi.\n<h4><span style=\"color: #333399;\">1. Fight against corruption</span></h4>\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\">On one hand we have a self-made and self-acclaimed (and proven) honest party AAP; on the other hand we have Modi supported Bedi. But if we just look at the <em>mere credentials of both parties</em>, it is safe to assume they will be fair.</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\">If yes, what’s in Delhi’s fate? <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Bedi</span> – Strict/Balanced <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">OR</span> <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Kejriwal</span> – Emotional (resigned last time)</span>\n<h4><span style=\"color: #333399;\">2. Fight for injustice and justice</span></h4>\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\">None of the parties have promised any quota for any minority community- so is it safe to assume that both their offices will be fair at executing the criminals and providing fast justice to common men?</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\">If yes, what’s in Delhi’s fate? <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Bedi</span> – IPS (severe punishments for rapists, maybe?) <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">OR Kejrwal</span> – IRS (more fast track courts, maybe?)</span>\n<h4><span style=\"color: #333399;\">3. Safety (focus on women)</span></h4>\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\">If we chuck our bias that only women can understand the pain of women and hope for a fair play in elections, what’s in Delhi’s fate?</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Bedi</span> – A woman with a strong mind (led the 1975 R-Day parade of Delhi Police contingent) <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">OR Kejriwal</span> – A man with “women safety” as his top campaigns agenda, after cleanliness obviously</span>\n<h4><span style=\"color: #333399;\">4. Development</span></h4>\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\">Being the national capital, development is bound to happen here. Even if we look at the last 20 years- Metro has come, roads are bigger, flyovers have increased, trees have been planted, more malls,, electricity and water supply is more stable – regardless how many corruption charges have been raised for the previous government.</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\">In my opinion, whichever candidate comes into office – there will be development.</span>\n<h4><span style=\"color: #333399;\">5. Basic Necessities</span></h4>\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\">Yes, finally this also features on the campaign motto of candidates. Considering both candidates are self made, grounded and ‘common man’ per say, the situation should become better for Delhites irrespective of who holds the power. I mean, Delhi has been OKAY even in President’s rule. It should only get better, not worse.</span>\n<h3>So, what is in Delhi’s fate?</h3>\nIf we consider the qualifications, both Kiran Bedi and Arvind Kejriwal have a fair chance at the Delhi CM office. <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><em>But merely anything happens on just qualification basis in India. </em></span>So if we look at past track record, political backing and ofcourse luck, maybe Delhi should brace itself for another <del>sari clad</del> CM.','Is it Delhi\'s fate to get a women CM again?','','publish','open','open','','delhi-women-cm-again','','','2015-01-27 15:31:50','2015-01-27 15:31:50','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2589',0,'post','',0),(2591,32,'2015-01-26 07:30:44','2015-01-26 07:30:44','','44159771-ghar-wapsi-','','inherit','open','open','','44159771-ghar-wapsi','','','2015-01-26 07:30:44','2015-01-26 07:30:44','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/44159771-ghar-wapsi-.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2592,32,'2015-01-26 07:38:56','2015-01-26 07:38:56','','images','','inherit','open','open','','images-19','','','2015-01-26 07:38:56','2015-01-26 07:38:56','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/images5.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2593,32,'2015-01-26 07:39:27','2015-01-26 07:39:27','','flesh-trade272__2017770956','','inherit','open','open','','flesh-trade272__2017770956','','','2015-01-26 07:39:27','2015-01-26 07:39:27','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/flesh-trade272__2017770956.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2594,32,'2015-01-26 07:40:52','2015-01-26 07:40:52','','flesh-trade272__2017770956','','inherit','open','open','','flesh-trade272__2017770956-2','','','2015-01-26 07:40:52','2015-01-26 07:40:52','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/flesh-trade272__20177709561.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2595,32,'2015-02-16 06:29:55','2015-02-16 06:29:55','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Leela, a 14 year old girl who disappeared last year, came back to her village. But something was not right with her. She no more plays with her friends or goes to school. Her parents are also not happy after her arrival. And the other villagers treat her as if she is untouchable. What has happened to Leela, that people around her changed so much? Why Leela, no more weaves her dreams which she used to?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Do you think this is the first girl who met this fate? NO, we can’t even count how many Leela’s are being traded every second in our country. I think people fell short of commodities so they started selling women for money. And don’t get yourself wrong, this flesh trading is not only done by pimps even the parents of the girls force them to do this.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Sometimes it is the long felt need of money that forces the little girls to join prostitution. And sometimes the abusive parents sell them to get money. Usually the girls who come outside in search of a job becomes a easy prey to these offenders. The story goes on, some sex workers are victims of their loved ones and some are being kidnapped.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This not only happens in India but everywhere in world. In Afghanistan, girls are sold as brides to meet the big loans taken by their fathers. In India young girls are forced to dance naked in fairs, so that customers get satisfied.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">What do you think, where this trade takes place? Brothels  are not the only place where flesh trade is done it is done at various places like massage parlors, pubs and hotels. A sting operation done on a massage parlor reveals that, how sex trade is done openly. The managers give you a proper list of massages like body to body massage for 5,000 rupees and massage with intercourse 8,000 rupees. And adding to it, these virtual brothels also advertise their massages in innuendo. It is not only men who push these girls in this dirty world but women also do. Most of the managers are women.  I would like to ask those women, were men not enough to do this heinous crimes?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Whenever prostitution issue comes up we talk about morals and does not legalise it. But what about that prostitution which is going on from centuries? Is it not against morals? Now, no one points about any morality.  Legalising prostitution will at least safeguard the right of minors. They will not be forced into flesh trade and the women who do it to feed their families will be relieved from these pimps. Giving sex education to these workers will also decrease the cases of Sexually transmitted diseases such as AIDS.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Women and girls too have some dreams like men and deserve respect in society. Forcing minor girls in flesh trade not only violates human rights but also shatters them from inside. They never get out from that hell. Even if they are lucky and come out, they have same fate like Leela. Society outcasts them. Why? What were their mistakes? At some point or the other only pimps are not responsible for ruining the life of these girls, the one who do not accept these victims are also responsible and those are <strong>“us”.</strong> So take an initiative and help them to fight.</p>','Flesh Trade','','publish','open','open','','flesh-trade','','','2015-02-16 06:29:55','2015-02-16 06:29:55','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2595',0,'post','',0),(2599,40,'2015-01-26 08:37:47','2015-01-26 08:37:47','Is it Delhi\'s fate to get another woman CM?','Kiran Bedi Vs Arvind Kejriwal','Fate of Delhi CM office','inherit','open','open','','cm-candidates-for-delhi-polls-arvind-kejriwal-vs-kiran-bedi','','','2015-01-26 08:37:47','2015-01-26 08:37:47','',2589,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/cm-candidates-for-delhi-polls-arvind-kejriwal-vs-kiran-bedi.gif',0,'attachment','image/gif',0),(2603,32,'2015-01-26 11:42:30','2015-01-26 11:42:30','','flesh-trade272__2017770956','','inherit','open','open','','flesh-trade272__2017770956-3','','','2015-01-26 11:42:30','2015-01-26 11:42:30','',2595,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/flesh-trade272__20177709562.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2607,44,'2015-01-26 16:48:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00','The Delhi Assembly elections are at our doorsteps and the entire city is in frenzy with political rallies and canvassing and campaigning. In fact the entire country is eagerly awaiting the elections and the results to follow. It’s already an accepted fact that these elections comes down to the Bharatiya Janata Party and the Aam Aadmi Party lead by Arvind Kejriwal. The voters are certainly looking forward to these elections and to the prospect of being able decide on a party and leader who can form a stable government. Many among them are even first time voters who have been keenly awaiting this opportunity for some time now. But how informed are you as a voter is the question. Blindly casting your vote for a candidate is not done. Each vote that we are entitled to is not just a symbol of democracy but a responsibility. You are accountable as a citizen to cast your vote after careful deliberation and reflection. You are about to choose the person and the party who will be responsible for governance, creating and enforcing laws, ensuring your security and maintaining peace among other things. You are placing a lot of power in their hands so choose wisely.\n\n<strong>WHO WERE THEY?</strong>\n\nIn this article I shall only be sticking to the BJP and the AAP safely assuming them to be the frontrunners in these elections. Well most of the people in Delhi are already familiar with AAP, though it’s new on the political scene, due to their rather short-term last year. The Chief ministerial candidate with his activist image has always appealed to the middle-class and upper middle class but how much do we really know about him.\n\nWell as I have already mentioned Arvind Kejriwal is an activist who took part in the Anna Hazare’s India Against Corruption movement. He was a graduate from IIT Karaghpur, impressive but inconsequential because I believe though education augments certain essential qualities needed in a leader it in no way is the most essential qualification to be a political leader. I mean do you think a software engineer knows better about the predicaments of a poor, ignorant farmer than a farmer himself? Anyway getting back to the case at hand Kejriwal was awarded the <strong><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramon_Magsaysay_Award\">Ramon Magsaysay Award</a></strong> for Emergent Leadership recognising his involvement in a grassroots movement <em>(Parivartan). </em>Kejriwal gave up his lucrative job in the IRS to fight against corruption full-time and is also known to have donated his award money to found the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_Cause_Research_Foundation\">Public Cause Research Foundation</a>, an NGO.\n\n<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/aap2.png\"><img class=\"  wp-image-2610 alignright\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/aap2.png\" alt=\"aap2\" width=\"110\" height=\"152\" /></a>Now coming to Kiran Bedi, the illustrious ex-police officer, who is being fielded as BJP’s Chief Ministerial candidate. Also well-known for her involvement in the India Against Corruption as well, she is a woman of principles known for the reforms she put in place in Tihar jail - the reforms included activities for the prisoners which brought out the best from even the hardened criminals - which eventually won her the Ramon Magasayay Award. She was a former tennis player who joined the Indian Police Service in 1972 becoming its first woman officer. Hats off to her for that!\n\n<strong>CAN THEY DELIVER?</strong>\n\nI think we have established where these two have come from and what kind of backgrounds they have. We have also established in the process that they are indeed good human beings but will they be capable as leaders is another question that needs to be pondered upon.\n\nWhile Kejriwal comes off as an honest, common man sometimes that might not be enough. He is infamously known for deserting his seat last year after 49 days as a Chief Minister. That is indeed a black mark on him but should that be a reason to not give him a second chance is something you as the voter must decide. In just the 49 days he was in power he was known to have taken great pains to involve the common man in the governance process. He did this by holding open meetings with the people of Delhi encouraging them to bring their demands and troubles to him personally. How effective that was eventually is also to be considered of course. And he also showed signs during his term that he meant to keep his promise in eradicating corruption. Something to contemplate over, right?<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/aap1.png\"><img class=\"  wp-image-2609 alignright\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/aap1.png\" alt=\"aap1\" width=\"272\" height=\"181\" /></a>\n\nBut these last few days he and his party have seemed to be clutching at straws. This can be corroborated by the recent incident where AAP accused the central government for not inviting him to the R-day celebrations. He claimed that as an ex-CM he should have been invited as protocol demanded it. How correct or incorrect it might have been on the Centre’s part this is really of no consequence at this point. Its times like this when you wonder if he is best suited for the role of the Chief Minister.\n\nBut then again this is the man who successfully spearheaded an anti-corruption movement and also was responsible for creating the Jan Lokpal Bill all at the age of 45!\n\nThe AAP was fruit of the frustration of a common man and as the famous Shah Rukh Khan dialogue goes ‘Don’t underestimate the power of a common man’.\n\nKiran Bedi though a well-known social activist whose activities corroborate the strength of her character, the circumstances under which she joined the BJP leaves one skeptical. Also though the BJP managed to win the Lok Sabha elections riding on the Modi wave they have managed to disappoint the Delhi-ites. The crime rate against women has risen by 40% since BJP took power at the Centre and since the Delhi police reports to the Centre this is disconcerting.\n\nBut then Kiran Bedi is known for her indomitable spirit and her association with Anna Hazare during the anti-corruption movement puts her in a favorable light. And she is someone who can provide Delhi with an honest government.\n\nAll in all the plain facts have been laid down before you now. It’s up to you now. You have the facts now decide responsibly.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','HOW INFORMED ARE YOU AS A VOTER?','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-01-26 16:48:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2607',0,'post','',0),(2608,44,'2015-01-26 16:25:47','2015-01-26 16:25:47','','aap','','inherit','open','open','','aap','','','2015-01-26 16:25:47','2015-01-26 16:25:47','',2607,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/aap.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2609,44,'2015-01-26 16:29:17','2015-01-26 16:29:17','','aap1','','inherit','open','open','','aap1','','','2015-01-26 16:29:17','2015-01-26 16:29:17','',2607,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/aap1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2610,44,'2015-01-26 16:40:49','2015-01-26 16:40:49','','aap2','','inherit','open','open','','aap2','','','2015-01-26 16:40:49','2015-01-26 16:40:49','',2607,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/aap2.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2611,44,'2015-01-26 16:44:00','2015-01-26 16:44:00','','aap3','','inherit','open','open','','aap3','','','2015-01-26 16:44:00','2015-01-26 16:44:00','',2607,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/aap3.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2616,42,'2015-01-26 18:48:14','2015-01-26 18:48:14','U.S. President Barack Obama and India\'s Prime Minister Narendra Modi (R) shake hands after giving opening statements during a at Hyderabad House in New Delhi January 25, 2015. REUTERS/Jim Bourg','U.S. President Obama and India\'s PM Modi shake hands after giving opening statements during a at Hyderabad House in New Delhi','','inherit','open','open','','u-s-president-obama-and-indias-pm-modi-shake-hands-after-giving-opening-statements-during-a-at-hyderabad-house-in-new-delhi-2','','','2015-01-26 18:48:14','2015-01-26 18:48:14','',2578,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download-300x2121.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2621,40,'2015-01-27 18:32:37','2015-01-27 18:32:37','The <a title=\"Read more on Wikipedia\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swachh_Bharat_Abhiyan\" target=\"_blank\">Swachh Bharat Abhiyan</a> was launched on 2 October 2014 at Rajghat, New Delhi by Prime Minister Narendra Modi who initiated this drive by cleaning the road himself. Mr. Modi nominated nine famous personalities for this campaign, and they took up the challenge and further nominated nine more people and so on. It has been carried forward since then with famous people, government employees, locals and students of schools and colleges.\n\n<span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>How this was a “game”?</strong></span>\n\n‘<a title=\"Read more on Wikipedia\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory\" target=\"_blank\">Game Theory</a>’ is a concept which uses maths to study strategies in business and military decisions. The players in a ‘game’ can be people, companies, armies or other things. Each player wants something; sometimes the players work together, but often they are competing against each other.\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">If we analyse <a style=\"color: #ff0000;\" title=\"Read more on mygov.in\" href=\"http://swachhbharat.mygov.in/\" target=\"_blank\">Swachh Bharat Abhiyan</a> through Game Theory, we would get the answer to: was this campaign a need or a well-timed move?</span>\n\nThis Campaign would not have been a necessity had there been no <a title=\"Read more on Wikipedia\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prisoner%27s_dilemma\" target=\"_blank\">Prisoner’s Dilemma</a> i.e. why two parties/sides/players might not cooperate even if it is in both their best interests to do so. In simpler terms, the  need for the campaign arrived because everyone just wants to keep their backyard clean and not to take the responsibility of an extra inch beyond their homes.\n\nIf a proper mechanism was adopted to collect trash from each household, there will be no need for such a campaign and for everyone to participate in the cleanliness drive.\n\nBut in reality, people think cleaning their home is enough.<em> (For all we know, they would be dumping the trash outside someone else’s home)</em>. And that is why<strong> this was just a game played at the right time</strong>- to unite people for a common goal to fight a common enemy.<strong> </strong>Although there is no denying there was a dire need for this step too.\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">If all players decide to keep city clean, then the outcome of the campaign will be positive – because everyone will be cleaning i.e. <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">“WIN WIN”</span>.</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">If everyone decides they won’t work for the cleanliness of the nation, then some stricter actions will be taken by the government to force the citizens to clean Bharat i.e. <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">“LOSE LOSE”</span>.</p>\nIn both the above situations, the government takes a call what to do next.\n\nBut here comes what we call <strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Prisoner’s Dilemma</span></strong>: Few people decide not to work towards this campaign. Even then some people WILL BE working to clean the city. But they will see no fruits of their outcome because the first group of people is still being the cause of non-cleanliness. And eventually this ‘good people’ group might have a switch in behaviour even they will stop working and join the others. Leaving us to where we were before the campaign was launched.\n\nThough this will lead to a slower <del>failure</del> shut-down of the campaign AFTER all the praises that have already been hailed for this simple yet brilliant <del>idea</del> game of Mr. Modi.\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\">Why this move was a ‘game’:</span></strong>\n\n<span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><em>1. High relevance in today’s time:</em></span> People want to see a change; they are more informed of the pros and cons if this campaigns works.\n\n<span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><em>2. High influence on people:</em></span> This being a cause which affects everyone in the country- people do not shirk away from the thought of contributing; they get influenced when famous personalities pick up a broom in their locality.\n\n<span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><em>3. High social media activity:</em></span> Since all nominated people are on some or the other social platform and it is one of the fastest (also cost-effective) method of reaching out to the masses, everyone wants to show that they have done their bit. Nobody wants to be an outcast of the rave; if my friends are doing it, I might as well join.\n\n<span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><em>4. Promising nature of outcome:</em></span> When 9 people with millions of followers do something which they propagate is good (and obviously it is), and these people further nominate or inspire others- it is bound to have an impact.\n\nIn my opinion, ONE government or ONE campaign cannot change every one of the 1.252 Billion people of the country. And after all for how long those small groups of people keep working for the cleanliness with their spirits and hopes high?\n\n<em><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">So where are we headed? WIN WIN or LOSE LOSE or back to where we were 6 months ago?</span></em>\n\n<strong>It’s in the players’ hands after all..!!</strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_2624\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"960\"]<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/sample31.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-2624 size-large\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/sample31-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"Swachh Bharat Abhiyan\" width=\"960\" height=\"540\" /></a> Where are we headed?[/caption]','Swachh Bharat Abhiyan: A need or a well-timed move?','','publish','open','open','','a-look-at-swachh-bharat-abhiyan','','','2015-01-27 18:32:37','2015-01-27 18:32:37','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2621',0,'post','',0),(2622,40,'2015-01-27 10:10:38','2015-01-27 10:10:38','A need or a well timed move in the game?','Swachh Bharat Abhiyan','Swachh Bharat Campaign','inherit','open','open','','final-swachh-bharat-mib-google-cover-page_01','','','2015-01-27 10:10:38','2015-01-27 10:10:38','',2621,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/final-swachh-bharat-mib-google-cover-page_01.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2624,40,'2015-01-27 10:18:49','2015-01-27 10:18:49','Where are we headed?','Swachh Bharat Abhiyan','Swachh Bharat Abhiyan','inherit','open','open','','sample31','','','2015-01-27 10:18:49','2015-01-27 10:18:49','',2621,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/sample31.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2634,39,'2015-03-10 17:29:23','0000-00-00 00:00:00','&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<img class=\" aligncenter\" src=\"http://i2.cdn.turner.com/money/dam/assets/141010114115-crude-oil-stock-chart-october-620xa.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"620\" height=\"348\" />\n\n&nbsp;\n\nWe have all heard about the crude prices falling down that its prices have gone down to $47 per barrel. I also read the news and it was when this topic came up in a discussion (which I had in a train), I realized how important it was for me to write about it because people, really, don’t know what it is all about. And I don’t blame them for the superficial readings because I have indulged in the same superficial news-reading for a better 22 years of my life – and I’m just 23. So, we’ll start right from the basics and then move ahead to discuss the causes of this price fall, and its effects on the economy.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>1. <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Basics:</span></strong> Let’s start with defining what crude is and what a barrel is. I need to clear the fact that Crude oil is NOT the petrol that we fill our automobile tanks with. Crude Oil is the raw thing which we extract from beneath the ground by drilling into the Earth. It is when we refine the Crude Oil that we get gasoline (which is the petrol that automobiles use) among other things. Now, we get to the barrel. One barrel of crude oil does not equal one liter; it equals 159 liters of it. Also, while we are on the subject of clearing the basic doubts, let me make it extremely clear that the fall in the prices of crude is not the outcome of BJP’s policies. It is because of a simple reason that the prices have fallen – a mismatch in supply and demand. We’ll discuss this in detail in the following sections.\n\n<strong>2. <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Why the fall in demand?</span></strong> The fall, as mentioned above, is because of a mismatch in the supply and demand. The demand has gone down and the supply is still the same. Now, there are numerous reasons which are being thrown around as to why the demand for crude has gone down. I’ll just state the reasons below:\n\ni. The Eurozone crisis. I won’t go into the details of this so let it just be enough that there was a monetary crisis in the Eurozone countries a couple of years ago and they have still not fully recovered from the crisis. This has led to decrease in their consumption and import of fuel;\n\nii. Given the high prices of crude earlier, there was a widespread increase in the use of alternative sources of energy;\n\niii. Japan’s economy has taken a wrong turn and it is slipping into recession. Being one of the biggest importers of crude, this has affected the global demand;\n\niv. Some say that China’s economic slowdown has also affected the global demand of crude because China is, again, one of the biggest importers of crude oil. China’s growth has registered to be just 7.4% which is the lowest it has seen in the past 24 years.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>3. <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Why not reduce the supply?</span></strong> The next logical question that follows is – why not just reduce the supply if the demand has gone down? The answer – Saudi Arabia doesn’t want to. Saudi Arabia is one of the major producers of crude oil and it is the most powerful member of OPEC, an organization of 12 oil exporting countries. Why has Saudi Arabia refused to reduce its oil production? Following are the possible reasons that I have come across:\n\ni. To render the Shale production of USA unviable. Shale is another source of fuel and USA recently found a lot of shale reserves in its country. It was projected that if the shale reserves were exploited properly, USA would become the net exporter of petroleum by the year 2020. Given the fact that right now USA is an importer of crude, Saudi Arabia’s interests would be hurt if the projection would come true;\n\nii. Saudi Arabia wants to hurt the economies of Russia and Iran with whom it has never been on good terms. And, Russia &amp; Iran are definitely hurting because their economy highly depends on the oil exports.\n<strong>4. <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Its effect on countries’ economies</span></strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">:</span> This will have to be divided into two parts: effect on the importing countries and that on the exporting countries. For the importing countries, it is a good thing because.. Well, because they’re buying a lot of crude oil and its prices just went down. So, they have more money now to spend on other things. India comes under this category. As the prices of crude have more than halved, ideally we should be getting petrol at around 35/- per liter. But we’re not, because the government has hiked the excise duty and the extra revenue will help the government spending on the development of our country. For the exporting countries, though, it is a bad thing. Countries like Russia, Venezuela and even Saudi Arabia come under this category. Russia relies heavily on its oil exports and as the prices have gone down, Russian economy is not a happy thing right now. The currency of Russia has fallen by more than 40%. Saudi Arabia can afford to lose a little bit because its foreign exchange reserves are close to $900 billion whereas for Russia, the readily available foreign exchange reserve is just over $200 billion.\nSo, this is the gist of whole story behind the crude oil’s prices falling down. It is just so that you people know the basics of this much-talked-about phenomenon and so that you don’t make a fool out of yourself by believing the people who say things like BJP has reduced oil prices or that the price of one liter crude is $47 while in India we have it at almost $1 per liter.\n\n&nbsp;','When the Crude falls..','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-03-10 17:29:23','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2634',0,'post','',0),(2637,44,'2015-02-04 09:33:43','2015-02-04 09:33:43','<p style=\"text-align: justify\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: Calibri\">Dear Netaji’s</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri\"><span style=\"color: #000000\">How are you? I am a 10 year-old studying in the 5</span><sup><span style=\"color: #000000\">th</span></sup><span style=\"color: #000000\"> std. My teachers call me inquisitive and my mother calls me a curious child. But my brother doesn’t agree with them. He just thinks I ask too many questions. But I’ve so many doubts and I don’t see how I’m supposed to clarify them without asking someone. </span></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: Calibri\">Well as I’m sure you’ve already guessed I’m writing this letter, asking you to shed light on some issues that have been bugging me. You see we have been learning about freedom fighters and netaji’s in class and they seem like such wonderful people. And I thought to myself finally someone who will probably answer my questions without asking me to shut up. So here I am writing this letter to you.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: Calibri\">Last year my father took me to a political rally. It was during the elections and I heard one candidate making many promises, among them he made a promise to eradicate poverty. I looked up ‘eradicate’ in the dictionary that night. The dictionary said it meant ‘to put an end to’. But only this morning I saw some people begging outside a temple. I don’t understand why these people are begging. I thought only the poor begged for money. But then how is that possible? Didn’t that candidate promise to eradicate poverty? Does that mean the dictionary was wrong? </span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: Calibri\">There’s something else that’s been worrying me. I’ve been hearing of something called scams on television for some time now. My father explained what it meant and he also mentioned that many of the people involved in these ‘scams’ are politicians. These scams sound very much like stealing to me. And my teachers have been telling me since kindergarten that stealing or thieving of any kind is unacceptable. What does this mean? Is it okay to steal then? Does this mean our teachers haven’t been teaching us right? Please could you ask them to stop feeding us with wrong values? </span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: Calibri\">Am I nagging you? My aunt keeps telling me to stop nagging her when I go to her with my questions. I’m not sure what ‘nagging’ means but I’m sure it’s nothing pleasant. She also keeps saying that children should be seen and not heard. But I’m sure you don’t believe in such an awful principle.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: Calibri\">I read something yesterday that worried me deeply. You know how there exists an ozone layer to protect us from the sun\'s harmful rays. Apparently there is a big hole in the ozone layer because of pollution. Did you know this? But you obviously wouldn\'t know anything about this otherwise you would have done something I\'m sure.  But I found this very scary. I told my mother that I wouldn’t go to school today as I was scared of falling ill because of the UV rays. But she wouldn’t listen to me of course. My father told me that a lot of this pollution is being produced by factories and industries which do not follow the rules set by the government. I also heard something being mentioned about some politicians getting commissions and turning a blind eye. I didn’t get what he meant but I’m really worried. I heard you get cancer if exposed to UV rays. I don’t want to get cancer. My friend’s mother died of cancer and he told me it’s not something very nice to have. Won’t you do something? I don’t want to die!!!</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: Calibri\">I have dreamed all my life of seeing a tiger in the jungle, a herd of elephants bathing in a river, wild animals roaming freely in the forests but now I’m afraid I might not get to see that. Apparently people called poachers are killing them for their bones, ivory and their fur. I don’t understand. When someone murders someone they are put in prison and punished severely. Doesn’t killing animals merit the same? But I’m sure you know what you are doing. So I won\'t worry. </span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: Calibri\">I think I have troubled you too much already. My brother says you are very busy people and you probably won\'t even read this letter. And even if you did, you probably would not care but I know better. I know you care. And I know you will reply as well. So until I hear from you goodbye.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: Calibri\">Love </span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: Calibri\">A concerned 10-year old</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: Calibri\">P.S. I hope you don’t consider me nosy like my brother. </span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"></p>','A Letter From a Concerned 10-Year Old To Our Netaji\'s','','publish','open','open','','letter-concerned-10-year-old-netajis','','','2015-02-04 09:33:43','2015-02-04 09:33:43','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2637',0,'post','',2),(2639,39,'2015-02-12 20:24:07','2015-02-12 20:24:07','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Whatever be said about her, there is one thing for certain – India has been making great adances in the field of space science. Isn’t it? I mean the Mangalyaan, GSLV III, GSAT 16, ISRO has been doing a wonderful job. Now, let’s take a look at how the politics is demeaning what the scientists have been achieving. JUST when the world had bowed down in front of India after its spectacular Mars Orbiter Mission, the time couldn’t have been more appropriate to hold an all India Science Congress to look at the scientific achievements of India. So, begins the ceremony – the only national level science congress to be inaugurated by the prime minister of a nation and not a veteran scientist – with the topic of “Ancient Sciences through Sanskrit”. All that took place during these hours of the Indian Science Congress took the heads of almost all those scientists which were held high due to the recent triumphs, and made them hang like the ripe fruits on a tree – waiting to fall off. The details of the proceedings are available online if those with a scientific temper wish to embarrass themselves. What I’ll do here is take a few of the claims of our political leaders, of this year’s Indian Science Congress, and discuss them one-by-one. So, let’s begin to discuss this ridiculous attempt that shall harm the scientific temper for ages to come:</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>\n1. <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Lord Ganesh was given the head of an elephant by plastic surgery</span></strong> – Any believers of that? ANYONE? I really hope not. I don’t suppose that I have to get into the medical details of this assumption. To be quite honest, I’m not even capable of doing so because I have no history with medical science. Even then, I think we all know that it is simply not possible to place an elephant’s head on a human neck. Be it any surgery. Let’s take a simple reason – its weight. I read it somewhere that an elephants ears weigh almost 40-50 kg each. Now you combine that with the rest of the head and place it on a human spinal cord. We can all imagine how fast the spinal cord would snap. Anyways, even if the head was somehow put without damages, it was said that a kind of sugar was used to attach the head to the torso. Sugar pasting animal head on human body. Need I say more?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>2.</strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong> Heisenberg’s Uncertainty Principle was borrowed from us</strong> </span>– Rajnath Singh ji, our honourable Home Minister, went on to claim that Heisenberg’s Uncertainty Principle was inspired by the talks of particle physics that he had with Rabindranath Tagore when he came to India in 1929. Now, people could have given this claim a second thought IF Heisenberg wouldn’t have published his principle in 1927, that would be 2 years before he came to India and met Tagore. And that’s not even the worst part, the worst part is that Rajnath Singh ji holds a master’s degree in Physics!</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>3. <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Indians flew planes 7,000 years ago</span></strong> – Now, this claim, prima facie, sounds ridiculous. But, how could someone make a claim so ridiculous on a national stage? So, I decided to read about this claim. This is what I found when went through a few websites and a couple of newspapers. The claim was made by citing the “ancient Vyamanika Shastra written by Mahrashi Bharadwaj.” It was further claimed that we indulged in not only international flights, but also inter-planetary journeys! On a very little research, one finds that almost 40 years ago in the year 1974, a group of scientists from IISc did a study on this text and they found 2 things:</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">i. The text was written by a man named Subbarya Shastry and not before 1904. Not so “ancient” after all, eh?\nii. The geometry and design was declared ‘horrendous’ and it was concluded that the vimanas actually went against the Newton’s laws of motion! Also, it was aerodynamically not possible to fly such a design.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>4. <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Finding groundwater using cow’s urine</span></strong> – Alright, I won’t go into the details of this one because I couldn’t, given lack of unconsciousness, get myself to type and search about this claim in detail. The claim was just that using a paste made of some seeds and cow’s urine which would help us find groundwater. Who needs drilling when we have cow-pee, right?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>5. <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Bacteria that turns anything into gold</span></strong> – So, there was this paper presented which claimed that cow has a bacteria inside it which can convert anything it eats into pure, 24-carat gold. Well… holy cow!</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">So, these were 5 of the best claims. There were others, but these 5 topped my chart. As the fundamental duties which are stated in the constitution of India tell us to develop scientific temper, I have very clearly fulfilled the latter half of my fundamental duty and developed an adequate amount of temper. What these people need to realize is the fact there was ACTUALLY some great work done in the field of science in ancient times. Making such claims would only lead to the rising doubts in some of the fields where our ancestors may really have gotten a breakthrough. It is not just embarrassing to see the top leaders of our country talking scientific nonsense, it is visibly harming the reputation and the work done by the real scientists of our age. It isn’t bad to look back at our past and feel proud of it, I do it all the time. But, we already have enough substantiated facts to be proud of. We don’t need such unsubstantiated and un-scientific claims to mar the facts which are. For the sake of serious science, and Indian pride, I hope we won’t see such a day ever again. And, by the way, there’s an Indian-origin NASA scientist who is filing a petition against the space-ship claims made in this Science Congress. From what I know, he already has more than 200 scientists who have signed this petition. I think that this is what a metaphorical “Stop” sign would look like.</p>','Political \'Science\'','','publish','open','open','','political-science','','','2015-02-12 20:24:07','2015-02-12 20:24:07','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2639',0,'post','',0),(2643,39,'2015-02-09 15:03:00','2015-02-09 15:03:00','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">So, just when there were cries of freedom of expression in Paris and Indians stood up for them, I saw a statement in the newspapers which restored my faith in the fact that all religious-fundamentalists are, necessarily, alike. The words were – <em>Writer Perumal Murugan is dead</em>. As I was just defending the cause of Islam against some people who blamed the entire religion based on the act of a couple of “religious warriors” as they call themselves, these words gave the answer for me, if the seekers were ready to take the truth. Before we start discussing the freedom of expression, and we’ll do that just keeping our nation in view because I do not know to what extent is the freedom free in other nations, I would like to brief you as to the relevance of the words in italics. Perumal Murugan happens to be an author. He wrote a book named Madhourubhagam which was published in the year 2010 and recently translated in English. It told the story of a girl who lives in a town of Tiruchengode, in Tamil Nadu. The special thing about this town is that, traditionally, it allowed consensual sex in married couples. For instance I’m married to a girl and if I give her a consent, she can have sex with another person. Basically, it was for the women who could not conceive for some reason, to give her a chance to become a mother and carry the generation on.  Some ardent “Hindus” got to know about this, they proclaimed that this stains the image of the town, burnt the author’s books and asked him to apologize, change the content of his book and take back the unsold books from the market. Not a rebel by nature, and afraid for his family’s well-being, the author obliged them. With this obligation, he also announced that he will not be writing anymore. So, on this note, let’s start the discussion on the freedom of expression in our country.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">What comes to your mind when someone mentions that a book was burnt publicly? To me, it reminds me of a book I read which told about the practice of the Nazis who used to collect books which they thought went against the idea of Germany - pardon me, THEIR idea of a Germany - and they used to burn all of them. Thousands of books were burnt this way. Now, how different is that situation from this situation? Except, of course, for the scale on which this was carried out. Is this the extent of freedom we give to our writers? Is THIS how a pen is mightier than a sword? Because from where I sit, the sword appears to have quite an edge over the pen. And this isn’t just one instance, this curbing of freedom-of-expression, just a couple of months ago a book on Hinduism by an author named Wendy Doniger was banned because some people decided that it disrespected the religion. Also, there was a public display of the expression of love in a few cities. The “Kiss of love” they called the protest. The result? This non-violent display of love was intervened by the police forces, people were beaten up and they called it an anti-social thing. Who are the ‘they’ I talk about here, ‘they’ are the same ardent “Hindus” who call themselves the Moral Police. Ironic, isn’t it? All my life I was taught that to love was the most moral thing and now there’s a Moral Police which stops me from expressing the most basic moral feeling – that of love. And that’s not all, you can see the Moral Police in action every year on the 14<sup>th</sup> of February, PROTECTING our society and its values from the wretched shackles of this overrated “love”.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are more than just a couple of questions that rise in my mind. Who died and made them the moral police? How is love ruining cultural values? What is wrong with a kiss? And last, but not the least, what the fuck am I supposed to do with this freedom-of-expression when I cannot express love, cannot criticize a religion, cannot question someone’s God and cannot ask questions which might incite the feeling of disharmony? Am I just supposed to express only those ideas which make others happy? What’s so freeing about that? An amazing author, George Orwell, summed up my thoughts in a very wonderful line. He said, “If liberty means anything at all, it means the right to tell people what they don’t want to hear.” And it is a very ominous moment where love and truth is what people DON’T want to hear. From here, we can only end up in a dark pitch where we will be seeing what the fundamentalists want us to see, hearing only what the fundamentalists want us to hear, doing only what the fundamentalists want us to do and saying what the fundamentalists want us to say. In short, it will be our life, but we won’t be the one living it, the fundamentalists will be doing that for us. The breathing part, though, magnanimously, would be left for us to do as we want to. Because that’s all there is to life, isn’t it? Breathing. Exhaling and inhaling this polluted air that our forefathers have left for us to pollute even more and leave it for our children to choke on.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Is this that “better society” for realization of which our forefathers gave up their life? Is this that society which the ones who fought and died for our nation dreamt of while they happily accepted that knotted rope to be tied across their necks? Is this really freedom? Though we all know the answer to these questions, I’ll leave you to dwell upon these as you reason with yourselves. But, be careful, don’t speak your mind out loud while you ponder, you never know.</p>','Freedom of Expr..','','publish','open','open','','freedom-expr','','','2015-02-09 15:03:00','2015-02-09 15:03:00','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2643',0,'post','',0),(2645,44,'2015-01-28 17:59:17','2015-01-28 17:59:17','','10yr','','inherit','open','open','','10yr','','','2015-01-28 17:59:17','2015-01-28 17:59:17','',2637,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/10yr.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2653,38,'2015-02-09 14:51:45','2015-02-09 14:51:45','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As I was driving to work today, I wondered about how I meet strangers on the road everyday and all the drivers in Indian traffic can be classified into one of the following kinds.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>1) The Tipsy Ones</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This kind of species can be identified by the following traits – they start out at one extreme end of the road and zip zap and zoom over to the other end without any indication and it is a nightmare for driving behind them. In a minute or two, they realize that they were happier in the other lane and cut across over and over again. It is a pain to be stuck behind one of them. Another common characteristic is they do not realize the existence of a certain thing that we call indicators. This species can be found in many parts of India and their favorite habitats are the Metropolitan cities.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>2) The Honkers</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This is the second most common species on the Indian roads. They love their horn and cannot stop honking. It is totally okay if you are at a red light, they would still honk at you. They also believe in the magical power of honking. They believe that honking can clear away all the traffic, get them better roads, eradicate poverty and also save the world. What do you do when you meet one of them on the roads? Do not look into their eyes as they will honk at a higher decibel that human ears cannot survive. When you meet them, you do not greet them, just give way and watch them honk at the next person in front of them.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>3) The Niki Lauda</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">We have all seen Rush and loved it. But do not fret because India has a lot of James Hunts, Niki Laudas, Vettels and more. They are in such abundance that they flourish all around you. They could be on a bike or in a car. Certain rare species of this kind are also known to drive heavy vehicles. The most distinct feature of this kind is that they do not have a lot of respect for their own lives and as a result they are also indifferent to others lives too. When you sight one of them, let them pass and silently pray for a minute that they shouldn’t erase the human clan.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>4) The Novice</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">They look like they were born yesterday but are on the road driving today. They often look young, inexperienced and get frightened easily. The infants are often given a vehicle by their parents or sometimes without their knowledge. Stand next to the traffic police as they love to spot this species. They are often in school uniforms and that is how you realize they cannot be old enough to drive for sure. Also sometimes there are older people who fall under this category. You can spot them by looking for fear. You can smell their fear from anywhere. They often look like deer frozen in front of a headlight.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>5) The flawless ones</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This is an almost extinct species on the Indian roads. They are often threatened by drivers of the first three categories. They are textbook perfect drivers, who follow the rules, do not try to kill pedestrians, know to use the brake, realize the use of an indicator and are always aware of the way they drive. Such species are valuable to the Indian society. So if you do spot one of them, please save them from the other kinds and try to increase their population to save the human species.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>','An ode to the Indian traffic..','','publish','open','open','','indian-traffic-an-ode','','','2015-02-09 14:51:45','2015-02-09 14:51:45','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2653',0,'post','',0),(2654,38,'2015-01-30 04:23:57','2015-01-30 04:23:57','','India-loses-Rs-60000-crore-due-to-traffic-congestion','','inherit','open','open','','india-loses-rs-60000-crore-due-to-traffic-congestion','','','2015-01-30 04:23:57','2015-01-30 04:23:57','',2653,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/india-loses-rs-60000-crore-due-to-traffic-congestion.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2659,38,'2015-02-10 10:48:34','2015-02-10 10:48:34','<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Can we live without Face book and Twitter anymore?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This generation has brought out a new debate on whether life can exist without social media or not. Well, personally I think I wouldn’t know what to do if I am not surrounded by the constant buzz of technology around me. I have stark contrast examples of people though. When I ask if I can live a life without social media, my parents reply saying that’s how they have lived their entire lives. I can still brush that apart saying it is a generation gap and that a teenager these days cannot survive without social media. That is when I met another friend of mine. This girl has been my roommate for the past two years in SNU. She is very outspoken and a lively person who speaks to almost everyone on campus from day one. She has plenty of friends from her past and right now. She was very active on Facebook and Twitter. Her journey with social media began with accounts on Orkut, Myspace and hi5 when she was 14 and went on to make social media a part of her everyday life. She had a great online presence with something or the other happening all the time. One fine day, she decided to quit Facebook. We all thought she wouldn’t survive and would eventually come back to it as we are all almost addicted to it in some way or the other. It has been almost two years now and she hasn’t been back. I often ask her how she survives and why she quit. She has simple answers to all my questions. She says she has time to study, time to be herself, time to spend with friends in reality and above all she feels more at peace now. I see her sleep early and catch up on a book regularly. Initially I thought the idea of de linking oneself from social media is not practical but I have seen her live it day in and out.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">She occasionally asks me what is happening or I have this inner urge to show her pictures on Instagram or on Facebook, but she always seems oblivious to it all. She says that not knowing what your friends are doing every second is liberating. It’s amazing how much more free time she has while compared to me, given that the only difference is social media. She always was a peoples’ person and had around 500 friends on Facebook. But now, the number of friends she is in touch with has gone down but she argues that the quality of her friendship has gone up. She ends up spending more time with her family and only the people who are of great value. I feel that in a way, she has deleted certain people out of her life with such ease that doesn’t even affect her and I constantly wonder if I can do the same with my life.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">People are always complicated and life isn’t easy. My roommate argues that she lives without the constant fear of writing an innocent comment and wondering if it was morally right or wrong and if it hurt anyone’s sentiments. This fear is something that most people in our age group can very easily relate to. We live in a society where there are certain norms of what is right and what is not. Before I post a picture on Instagram, I wonder if my family would think it is right, would my friends approve of it. All of us live in a bubble where we constantly crave approval from the society. So, life without social media might be a good way to live more originally and not worry about such things.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Time seems to be a major factor in the whole concept of social media. There is a recent research that shows that the <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-2449632/How-check-phone-The-average-person-does-110-times-DAY-6-seconds-evening.html\" target=\"_blank\">average user actually checks their phone around 110 times a day</a>.<sup> </sup>The same research also states that although 110 times a day seems a high figure, other research suggests it may be even higher. What I infer from this is that an average human being spends so much time checking their phone and it is majorly because of social media. Being a social media addict, I think I spend at least 2 hours everyday. These 2 hours are an addition of looking at various apps on my phone and sitting on Facebook for longer stretch at the end of my day. Living in SNU’s hostel, I can see that most people come in the same category as me. We might sleep early at home but here we tend to stay up for longer hours, sleep very late and be online on Facebook for a major part of that time. I think that if people were not so addicted to Social Media, they would add at least a couple of hours to their day “magically” and this time could be used for more productive purposes.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Recently, in June 2014 Facebook, the world\'s biggest social networking site, is facing a storm of protest after it revealed it had discovered how to make users feel happier or sadder with a few computer key strokes. It has published <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/jun/29/facebook-users-emotions-news-feeds\" target=\"_blank\">details of a vast experiment in which it manipulated information posted on 689,000 users\' home pages</a> and found it could make people feel more positive or negative through a process of \"emotional contagion\". Facebook filtered users\' news feeds – the flow of comments, videos, pictures and web links posted by other people in their social network. In this study, it was shown that when people were exposed to happier stories from their feeds, they themselves felt more positive and it showed in their posts. On the other hand, people who saw negative posts, feel more disappointed and end up posting more negative posts. This clearly shows that Facebook and other social media have this power to control our emotions also and they have a say in making us feel happy or sad in a subconscious way. As Facebook had not informed its users about this study, there are people saying that it is not ethical. I also believe that such experiments are not right as we are human beings who created technology and this is a classic case where it becomes our own master.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Talking about the having better life, more time to be productive and to spend quality time with people who really matter, I wonder how our life would be if Facebook didn’t exist. Let me make it more interesting with a story that goes somewhat like this. This is inspired by the book “Hitchhiker’s Guide to the Galaxy” by Douglas Adams that I read as a kid. The book starts by saying that aliens are discussing ways to bring down the human race and destroy planet Earth because they want to build an inter galactic highway. I wonder if the same thing had to happen today, aliens could just take away social media. A majority of the society would be left deprived and would feel “empty” without any other major change. This may seem like science fiction, but it has possible practical implications. In the future, it is said that warfare wouldn’t be over land, air and water but would all be electronic warfare. The communication network is the backbone of every economy and attacking it would disrupt the country. It could be something as simple as sending high frequency radio waves that interferes with all communication right from data connectivity to secure bank transactions. If someone, someday hacks into the main server of Facebook and brings it down, he would rule the world with the amount of information that he would have on his hands. People would do anything to keep their privacy and ensure that it is not used against them in any way.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">While I might sound negative towards social media, the point that I am trying to bring out is that all humor aside, life without social media would definitely be disorienting at first, but eventually people have lived in the past and can live in the future without it. The reason that this now seems like a unfathomable idea is because of the dependency that we have developed and a sense of attachment and belonging. This phenomenon would keep growing with future generations being born into the culture and when a 2 year old can operate an iPad, he would definitely not agree to living life without this constant touch with technology in the future. Wherever this trend will take is for time to answer but we humans are always in control and should keep this grip over social media.</p>','Life without social media today!','','publish','open','open','','life-without-social-media-today','','','2015-02-10 10:48:34','2015-02-10 10:48:34','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2659',0,'post','',0),(2663,38,'2015-01-30 16:33:12','2015-01-30 16:33:12','','Social Media today','','inherit','open','open','','download-6','','','2015-01-30 16:33:12','2015-01-30 16:33:12','',2659,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download11.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2664,38,'2015-02-12 20:34:30','2015-02-12 20:34:30','<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Does modern technology make life easier and remove vulnerability ?</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">“<em>It has become appallingly obvious that technology has exceeded our humanity.</em>” This quote by Albert Einstein is said to be about the bombing of Japan. Everything in life is said to be either black or white but a lot of things exist in both shades. Technology is the best example of a double edged sword and Einstein’s this particular quote brings out the flip side of the coin.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It has been proven time and again that technology is so interwoven with human life that the two seem inseparable. Coming to the first part of the statement, we can prove with a lot of examples that modern technology makes life so much easier. It can be with something as simple that my grandmother finds cooking so much easier, the entire world seems to be better connected in terms of communication, easier transport, easier commerce through the internet, easier medi-care facilities, so on and so forth. Social media keeps us entertained; the internet keeps us up to date with all that is happening in the world. Technology helps anyone and everyone to build their business. These uses are so powerful that they often overwhelm us and we tend to look at technology with quite a positive outlook.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I want to talk about another very innovative and interesting use of technology. There a number of online raising charity websites where people can donate money. There also exists sites like Freerice.com where a person plays a word game, answer the meaning of the asked word and because of that rice is donated through the World Food Program. Such examples tend to prove that technology is actually unleashing humanity and not making us vulnerable in any way. A most recent example for the same is that <a href=\"http://imgur.com/JZUXw\" target=\"_blank\">Reddit</a> <a href=\"http://imgur.com/JZUXw\" target=\"_blank\">raised around 65,000$ in less than 24 hours and donated it to an orphanage in Nairobi</a>. Another example where technology helps touch human lives is based on something that I have seen personally. I am a permanent volunteer with an orphanage in Chennai called Christ Faith Home for Children. I was actively involved in the fundraising and complete functioning of this NGO. When I made a page on Facebook it got more people talking about the home, more people turned up to be teaching volunteers to the kids and also a lot more money came pouring in. Then, we developed a website which brought in more attention to the noble work done by the home. They give up kids for adoption and the touch of technology helped them in this process in terms of spreading news about such cases, updating waiting parents on news about the kids that they sponsor or they want to adopt and it also brought them a lot of contacts from people who live abroad and can provide well for the kids. The kids in this case are the ones whose lives are made easier because of technology. These examples make me a firm believer that technology is the medium through which goodness is spread.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The other half of the statement says that technology removes vulnerability. Again, this statement can be debated upon and we can look at it from different perspectives. The use of technology lies completely in the hand of the user and we have seen a lot to show that it can destroy humans if not used properly. Cyber warfare is something that has come up in recent times. I think it also includes something as simple as stalking a person on the internet to more dangerous crimes like identity theft, data theft and impersonation etc. This has opened us to newer vulnerabilities that were unheard of before. Recently, <a href=\"https://www.publicsafety.gc.ca/cnt/rsrcs/pblctns/ntrnt-ffndrs/index-eng.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">Canada has introduced new laws to combat online sexual offenders</a>. It shows that offenders are using technology to make and distribute child pornography often commit such crimes directly in life also. Such a problem is very grave and has opened up a whole new plethora of problems. This vulnerability has been created by humans themselves that affects innocent children.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In olden days and not so far ago, money laundering schemes involved opening up new schools, colleges or hospitals and also hoarding all the money in a foreign offshore account. These days, people are more creative and have taken to online money laundering. A <a href=\"http://arxiv.org/abs/1310.2368\" target=\"_blank\">report by the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime</a> describes how technology has helped such crimes. People use innovative methods like asking someone to anonymously forward large sums of money from their account so they become accountable for the crime, converting money into online currency which can then be converted back to real money, offering fake online work from home jobs etc. Such scams have come up only with the rise of technology making humans vulnerable in terms of monetary funds and privacy at the hands of technology.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Technology has no doubt made life easier but at the cost of opening up humans to a whole Pandora’s box of vulnerabilities. It is up to each individual human being to stay cautious, stay smart and use technology for their own good and the society’s good. While there are some exposures like large scale cyber wars, nuclear wars or organized crime aided by technology that we cannot protect ourselves against, we can definitely protect ourselves from other smaller crimes through increased awareness about them.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Technology can help you rise or bring you hard down to the ground, depending on your own use or abuse of it.</p>','Modern technology removes vulnerability ?','','publish','open','open','','technology-removes-vulnerability','','','2015-02-12 20:34:30','2015-02-12 20:34:30','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2664',0,'post','',0),(2668,38,'2015-01-30 16:58:54','2015-01-30 16:58:54','Technology removes vulnerability','Technology removes vulnerability','Technology removes vulnerability','inherit','open','open','','download-1-5','','','2015-01-30 16:58:54','2015-01-30 16:58:54','',2664,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download-15.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2675,41,'2015-01-31 17:27:54','2015-01-31 17:27:54','','lgbt1','source: astt.org','inherit','open','open','','lgbt1','','','2015-01-31 17:27:54','2015-01-31 17:27:54','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/lgbt1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2678,41,'2015-02-11 17:34:52','2015-02-11 17:34:52','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It was raining when I first saw him; he was busy arguing over some school issues. And then he gave a warm and comforting and soothing smile, I fell in love with him, then and there. Apart from being the clichéd ‘tall-dark-handsome’ package, he also happened to have been the smartest and brightest student of my school. I started showing all the symptoms of a love sick teenager. I would make up thousands of excuses to my friends and my family to go to places where there would have been a possibility of him showing up, just to get a glimpse of him.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The teenage love lasted more than my friends had expected. Tragedy being a part of every sensational love story, mine was no different, hit me right in my gut on the day I came to know he was in love with someone else. Dramatic as it may sound but I felt as if my world came to a crashing end. Although the heartbreak was short lived and I grew out of the teenage phase, but I never stopped loving him secretly. Three years of teenage crush turned into another two years of unrequited love.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">On one not-so-random day, I discovered that he discovered that he was gay. He acknowledged himself, in front of the known crowd, fearlessly. He dropped the word ‘gay’, which is still a taboo word in our country, so casually like he had time traveled from a place in future where being gay was as normal as being straight, which ideally should be the case of ‘now’. I, being the only person in that room, wearing a smile like a fool, was completely immersed in thinking ‘<em>he is available only for men, ladies! Only for men! And no room for jealousy now.</em>’ But when the whispering and murmuring started in the room, I noticed that people were horrified to learn the truth about him.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">He was still the same and so was my love for him. That was the day when I truly realized the power of love. My heart never once hesitated or stopped loving him even after knowing the truth. And I still can’t comprehend the fact that how someone being lesbian or gay would actually make that person different from being a perfectly normal person. They still have two eyes, two ears, a nose and a mouth, a heart, red blood, everything which you and I have. Then why take away the rights which you and I have?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It’s quite a disturbing fact that same sex marriage is an illegal activity in India, when there are other major issues like female infanticide and child marriage which are easily over looked. People treating \'LGBT\' like a disease, trying to cure it with pill, yoga and Ayurveda, are the ones in the need of hour for their treatment. They surely cannot be mentally fit if they have conjured up the thought of distinguishing \'LGBT\' any different than just normal human being.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Someone once told me, ‘First love is painful, but unrequited love is heartbreaking.’ But to me what is more heartbreaking is that considering of being with the love of your life is a crime in our country.</p>','Unrequited Love','','publish','open','open','','unrequited-love-2','','','2015-02-11 17:34:52','2015-02-11 17:34:52','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2678',0,'post','',0),(2681,41,'2015-02-04 09:54:57','2015-02-04 09:54:57','Feminism may seem to be dated for the privileged class of our society, but what about the rest of the unprivileged section? Being a student of an all-girl’s college, I was, eventually, given the tag of being feminist by few of my non-college friends. But I was not the only one. The other set of my college friends came and said the same thing to me, and it got me wondering why were we being tagged with “feminism”? To my surprise, some of them thought that being called a feminist was an insult because those who called them ‘feminist’ intended to do so. Why? Because we were talking about how gender equality is still a prominent issue in our country.\n\nSurprisingly, every one out of three women, in the world, is tortured every single day. There are women in our country who are forced into marriages, prostitution. They have no control over their bodies or lives. They have no education, no freedom. They are raped, beaten up and sometimes killed with impunity.\n\nIf it means standing up and fighting for them, even if that means arguing it over with someone, then yes I am a feminist and so are my other friends from my college. And I feel proud of being one, simply because we haven’t overlooked this equally important social issue that others have. One thing that I have experienced in this college is the freedom of being a women and doing things without thinking what someone would say or think. It’s a whole lot different world out here, which every woman should see, but not in confined walls of a college premises, but in the society, in our country, in the whole world.\n\nThe poor and undeveloped sections in the world are always those that put women down and clearly our government has decided to ignore this obvious truth. Why is that we are living in this 21st century, turning impossible dreams into reality, and still letting the alpha male of our society to define rules and reality and let them abuse the power. Isabel Allende has once said, ‘Abuse trickles down from the top of the ladder, where the men are, to the bottom. Women and children, especially the poor, are at the bottom. Even the most destitute of men have someone they can abuse, either a woman or a child ’.\n\nThese are not the issues which came at stakes over a fortnight ago, no these are the issues which have been there and are still continuing down its road since ages and have their buried roots in the history of mankind now. So I am still hoping, hoping for a basic fundamental change in our society, so that this world becomes a place where the quality of life is enriched for everyone; not just for the handful of privileged, but also for those who have been the victims of inequality through gender, income, race and class. Our world needs to nurture the feminine energy in every aspect of our civilization, starting from the mindset of men in our society and let feminine energy be a part of the management of the world.','\'Feminism\' is dated?','','publish','open','open','','feminism-dated','','','2015-02-04 09:54:57','2015-02-04 09:54:57','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2681',0,'post','',0),(2682,41,'2015-01-31 22:57:27','2015-01-31 22:57:27','','fight-women_2520457b','source: www.telegraph.co.uk','inherit','open','open','','fight-women_2520457b','','','2015-01-31 22:57:27','2015-01-31 22:57:27','',2681,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/fight-women_2520457b.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2688,40,'2015-02-08 13:52:16','2015-02-08 13:52:16','<em>The question is will voting give them a ray of hope to make a change or will it be yet another redundant law in our constitution?</em>\n\nEither by watching movies, TV series, documentaries, news coverage or by reading newspapers, journals and novels, <strong>a commoner might get a jist of the life of a prisoner</strong>. Either he must have done something terribly wrong or been at the wrong place at the wrong time.\n\nBut does that mean there is no chance of him feeling normal or be as equal to someone outside prison with regard to human rights? Why does our democracy bar prisoners to vote? More essentially, <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">should ALL prisoners be allowed to vote?</span>\n\nWhat about the criminals who <span style=\"color: #0000ff;\">show progress</span> by doing corrective actions? Or the murderers who have <span style=\"color: #0000ff;\">pleaded guilty</span> because they were overcome by a force higher than themselves for a moment?\n\nWould it harm in government formation if these people cast their votes? Maybe campaigning for elections will be tougher here, as politicians can influence prisoners to vote for them on false pretenses. But then that\'s happening in the free world too, is anyone complaining? Or even seeing? Or recording? And sending it to election commission?\n\nIn my opinion, prison can be<strong><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"> a more controlled environment</span></strong> for politicians to contest as everything can be monitored and pre-decided with concerned authorities.\n\nBut at the bottom if this question lies,<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"> what does this freedom to cast vote mean for a prisoner?</span> Just a mental satisfaction that yes, I am a part of the community! On the other hand, this law can be misused largely by groups supported by corrupt politicians. A prison war might break out or some prisoners could be forced to vote against their will for a candidate.\n\nEventually, will this law actually make a difference in the lives of prisoners and make them feel like a part of a democracy or will it become like just another redundant law in our so-called-longest-constitution in the world.\n\nAs a nation we probably will come into<span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"> limelight</span> if we allow all prisoners to vote. Criteria could be set up, basis which a panel of prison administration may pick a few responsible and deserving citizens who can get a voting right.\n\n<em><strong>For others, will it even be an excuse enough to become a better human?</strong></em>','Should Prisoners be allowed to vote?','','publish','open','open','','prisoners-allowed-vote','','','2015-02-08 13:52:16','2015-02-08 13:52:16','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2688',0,'post','',0),(2689,40,'2015-02-03 09:37:10','2015-02-03 09:37:10','','Prisoners Vote','Should prisoners be allowed to vote','inherit','open','open','','prisoner-voting-rights','','','2015-02-03 09:37:10','2015-02-03 09:37:10','',2688,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/prisoner-voting-rights.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2693,45,'2015-02-24 10:21:39','2015-02-24 10:21:39','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">February doesn’t just have the rare distinction of being the shortest month of the year, rather it brings with a lot more.For starters, the weather is lovely because it’s the most amazing season of the year, SPRING TIME!! But then something about this month is just too sad. Rings a bell? It definitely should, and if it doesn\'t, means that you\'ve not yet been subjected to the torturous procedure of going through the  physically, mentally and off-course socially tiring and grinding and irritating and suffocating Examinations, precisely THE BOARD EXAMS. March is the month where the actual drama takes place but the penultimate month prior to this “biggest battle foe life” isn’t any less taxing.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When we were in school all of us grew up watching how our seniors tackled the pressure and went through the grind as we admired their efforts and froze with the very thought that one day we too will have to go through this. But, ironically when we almost reached there i.e. the 12th standard, for most of us studies took a back-seat. “I am so going to fail” becomes the word of the season especially because Every internal assessment exam would turn out to be extremely horrible and the extensive curriculum coupled with the burdedn of expectations would only add to the woes. Passing in every subject becomes a big deal for people who had averaged over nine points in their class 10th examinations. Those shock waves sent across to students when they score a 59 instead of the actually expected 95 in their exams. The pre-board scenario was pretty much awful.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2694 aligncenter\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/board-exams.jpeg\" alt=\"board exams\" width=\"288\" height=\"175\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">All of us who have been through this phase can actually feel shivers down our spine when we see young kids who go through the grind year-after-year. Too much to study, too less time, the need to score well and get admission in a great college and all that jazz. Sometimes all of this becomes a little too heavy on the young minds that are still not out of their childhood bliss. It is not just their parents who pass on the burden of their expectations but in the Indian society “board exams” are more like a social phenomenon where all you kith and kin and the entire neighborhood comes, not to your rescue but to cement your grief further.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The point is that all of us know that the results of these exams do not decide your success rate in life. Not that they are extremely insignificant but the amount of reliance that our education system and our society places on the marks obtained in these examinations is absolutely ridiculous. Not that we take a cue from those school dropouts who have gone out to make it big in life and shun studies in totality. But the approach needs to be changed. Even the most talented ones fail to deliver under pressure and that is what happens when we see adverse consequences when it comes to kids taking the board examinations. This isn’t as trivial an issue as it seems to be because it jeopardizes the future of these kids who are the future of our country. A more pragmatic and flexible approach is required when it comes to children dealing with the pressure of board examinations. They are extremely vulnerable and need to be dealt with delicately instead of being pressurized unnecessarily so as to ward off this social evil “THE BOARD EXAMINATIONS”.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>','Peril of a board examinee','','publish','open','open','','peril-board-examinee','','','2015-02-24 10:21:39','2015-02-24 10:21:39','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2693',0,'post','',0),(2694,45,'2015-02-03 18:45:09','2015-02-03 18:45:09','','board exams','','inherit','open','open','','board-exams','','','2015-02-03 18:45:09','2015-02-03 18:45:09','',2693,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/board-exams.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2696,32,'2015-02-04 03:58:53','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p><a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/abortion-300x199.jpg\"><img class=\" size-medium wp-image-2697 aligncenter\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/abortion-300x199-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /></a></p><p>ABORTION has been a sensitive matter since ages in India. It was considered ethically and religiously wrong in the ancient time. To abort a child meant going against the will of God. Every religion had its own understanding about abortion and criticised it in one or other forms. Still, India was the pioneer in legalising abortion in 1971. The reason behind such a remarkable step was to save the life of mothers. Death of women during pregnancy was on rise. To provide safe motherhood, abortion was legalised by passing Medical Termination of Pregnancy Act (MTP) in 1971.</p><p>According to the act, abortion is permitted if it affects physical or mental health of the mother, or the unborn child is potentially handicapped, if the pregnancy is the result of rape or failure of sterilization. The whole act is to provide “safe motherhood” and abortion in extreme cases only. Then why instances of abortion occur daily? Why the health of women during pregnancies is deteriorating so much?</p><p><a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/anti-abortion.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-2703\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/anti-abortion-300x167.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"167\" /></a></p><p>The act was made to ensure safety of child and mother but is being used for some other purposes. Now, let’s look at some realities about abortion (which in no way protect mother’s health).</p><ul><li>Rashmi, a girl who was expecting was forced to abort three times. Why? Because she had girl child in her womb. This type of sex based abortion is most common in India. Technologies like pre natal diagnosis were meant to protect women but became weapons of their destruction. Pre- natal diagnosis is allowed only to detect any abnormalities in the child and not to determine sex of child. But people misused it and killed several small unborn girl children. Although there is prohibition on determination of sex of child, still it is prevalent all over India. Obviously we, Indians don’t care about the legal or illegal part of a law; we do what we want to do. Sex based abortions finds root from our patriarchal society. To have a son is blessing and a daughter is cursed. We always talk about equality and gender justice but never practise it. What an irony, this is the same country where goddesses are worshiped and girls are killed.</li><li>Abortion is used by many couples as an alternative to contraception. Some couples are uneducated about family planning and contraceptives, and choose abortion as an option to maintain child gap. Some other aborts them due to poverty and to decrease family size. They even don’t know about contraceptives. And others, who know about it, still prefer abortion over contraception because they find it inconvenient to use them. Wow! What a smart choice of family planning. We are lucky that our parents do not choose us to abort.</li><li>Physical violence also leads to abortion in major cases. We have seen various cases where husband doubts about the father of child and abuses her to abort it. Sometimes abortion is resorted to solve some family issues too. They don’t even realise they are taking life of a baby in their own tussles.</li><li>No, matter in which century do we live, we, Indians do not forget to relate everything with our religion. Some myths like not giving birth in particular month or to a particular number of children also resort to abortion. A woman is forced to abort her third child as 3 is not a lucky number. Every religion has its so called myths and the real sufferers are women. Some religion even does not allow use of contraception to avoid pregnancies.</li></ul><p>Abortion is an exception not an option. It should only be exercised in case of extreme emergency like life issues to mother or child. Or when there is permanent disablement to child or mother. It should not be carried out on the whims and fancies of individuals or as an alternative to contraception. Don’t abort for some stupid myths of the society. It may be a game for people to tell such myths but it is very harmful for the health of mother. Woman suffers a lot of physical and mental pain after abortion.  In some cases abortion may also lead to permanent infertility. There are not even trained doctors to carry abortion, this also adds to plights of mother. It’s about life of mother and child. So, please use it as a last option not as an alternative.</p>','Some realities about ABORTION!!!','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-02-04 03:58:53','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2696',0,'post','',0),(2697,32,'2015-02-04 03:29:30','2015-02-04 03:29:30','','abortion-300x199','','inherit','open','open','','abortion-300x199','','','2015-02-04 03:29:30','2015-02-04 03:29:30','',2696,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/abortion-300x199.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2699,32,'2015-02-04 03:53:14','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p><a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/stop-child-labour-by-szaidi-1-.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-2700\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/stop-child-labour-by-szaidi-1--300x148.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"148\" /></a></p><p>Do you remember, last time when you saw a child labour? You don’t have to constrain your minds, you can see them everywhere. They can be seen working in a “<em>dabbha”</em>, general store, rag picking etc. Whenever you step out of metro, you can see many children below the age of 10 years demanding you a penny. Or when you go on a road they sell you newspaper, flowers. Sometimes they even sell “<em>gutkas” </em>in trains without even knowing the product. No matter where you are you can see child labour in one form or the other.</p><p>But the real problem comes when these fragile ones are forced to work in hazardous conditions. Our laws prohibit children to work in hazardous industries but what is the real definition of hazardous to them. They (owners) say petty works done by them in factories is not hazardous. True, it may be not hazardous for an adult to stand and work 10 hours a day but it is hazardous for a 5 year child to work 18 hours a day. Sumit, a 12 year old boy who worked in bangle factory at Firozabad lost his eyes while working in factory. As the dust which comes out while polishing these bangles is harmful for eyes. 7 out of 10 people in his family lost their eyes partially or completely while working in same factory.  Another 7 boys who were sleeping in cotton factory after working were crushed in big machines with huge cotton balls. What will be the fate of our country whose children either die or become permanently disabled till attaining the tender age of 25 years? And what about poor children like Sumit who have become permanently disabled? Who will take their responsibility? The childhood of these children is stolen and they are forced to work in pity conditions.</p><p> “Child is the father of man” are the words by William Wordsworth. These words itself implies the importance of children in a society. Childhood is the inevitable part of a human life. It is the time when a child’s intellect is grown. When he physically develops and learns every important lesson of life. It is that part of our life when we used to sketch colourful dreams. Lots and lots of toys was our world. But reality of these child labours is totally different from our childhood. When they should have toys in their hands they have tools to cut stones. And even worse they are abused also. Can you even think what type of lifetime impression this abuse can cast on the little minds of these children?  </p><p>India itself is a country which talks about the glory of our children. Our country’s name Bharat is named after a fearless child Bharat. We do worship bal ganesh, bal gopal. And the story about courageous luv- kush are also not hidden. The importance of childhood is so much in our mythodology that we even say “bacche to bhagwan ka roop hote hai”. Then what had happened to us why can’t we see plights of these million innocent gods?</p><p>What is child labour?  It means employing children in any type of work which is not fit for child of that age. Stopping them from going to school.  Abusing them physically, emotionally or economically.</p><p> What are the causes of child labour? The foremost reason of child labour is need of money (poverty). The families are so poor that they can’t afford basic necessities, so they force their children to work. Owners are also happy to recruit child labourers as they do disguised works at very cheap rates. Neeta a 10 year old girl who washes dishes in houses gets 200 in a month. And the statics of child labours working in factories is even worse. They work for 2 rupees a month. YES, 2 rupees. Did you think 2 rupees are nothing, think again and ask these children about it?  <em>Chhotu</em> a small boy who works in a <em>dhabba</em>, his job is to collect plates, wash them, clean all the mess etc is paid only 2 rupees a month. This is the value of their precious childhood.</p><p>These children are so young that they even don’t realise what wrong is being done to them. They even don’t know what is legal and what is illegal. And we are also adding to it, as nothing serious is done to stop this labour. We never take any initiative against it.</p><p>Child labour is the biggest crime against humanity. It is not only legally but ethically wrong. It is spread worldwide and India contributes a huge to it. Among many causes of child labour one of the biggest cause is illiteracy. If every children below the age of 14 years start going to school, child labour can be abolished. Our constitution provides for free and compulsory education till age of 14 years. If a proper check is made and all the dropouts are re-enrolled then child labour will be eradicated.</p>','Child Labour','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-02-04 03:53:14','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2699',0,'post','',0),(2700,32,'2015-02-04 03:47:12','2015-02-04 03:47:12','','stop-child-labour-by-szaidi-1-','','inherit','open','open','','stop-child-labour-by-szaidi-1','','','2015-02-04 03:47:12','2015-02-04 03:47:12','',2699,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/stop-child-labour-by-szaidi-1-.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2703,32,'2015-02-04 03:58:14','2015-02-04 03:58:14','','anti-abortion','','inherit','open','open','','anti-abortion','','','2015-02-04 03:58:14','2015-02-04 03:58:14','',2696,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/anti-abortion.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2712,45,'2015-02-08 12:57:56','2015-02-08 12:57:56','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It was one of its\' kinds. Regarded as one of the boldest experiments in the history of the Indian entertainment scenario. The famous comedy group All India Bakchod a.k.a AIB brought out the relatively unfamiliar “roast” format for the Indian Audiences by their event AIB Knockout which was basically an event organized in Mumbai and graced by the who’s who of the entertainment Industry.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Famous actors Arjun Kapoor and Ranvir Singh who were at the receiving end of the roast were witnessed in a never seen before avatar, which won hearts of fans and critics alike.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">AIB Knockout was an attempt to try something new and bring the roast format to a country where celebrities aren\'t often known to laugh at themselves.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The format was the same as any international roast i.e. insult comedy, delivered in the form of one-liners designed to be as rude as possible. It is performed with the understanding that none of the material is meant to be taken seriously.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The YouTube video garnered not just millions of views but also immense adulation as this was seen as a welcome step towards the emergence of a new trend. A couple of days post the event, the AIB knockout had become a talking point among the youth but also came under the scanner for more than one reasons.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">So much was the drama surrounding it that the video had to be taken off you tube sending shock waves across to fans. A plethora of reasons were anticipated for the same which ranged from lodging an FIR against the actors Ranvir and Arjun along with the host Karan Johar and the threats they received which included a ban on the display of their films and another very strange reason cited was the fact that the show which took digs at Arpita Khan apparently drew the ire of her elder brother Salman Khan who expressed clear disappointment at the same.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Whatever the reason may be, before we could anticipate the emergence of a new phenomenon it just died! Or maybe we should say it was brutally MURDERED by the section of the society that declares itself as the “moral police”.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In a country where bigger issues like rape, corruption, political problems are rampant, something like this is way too trivial to even pay heed to. But then who cares, those bigger issues may not be as melodramatic as this and probably raising controversies on such progressive trends seems like more entertainment. How do we justify that?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">We talk of democracy in the \"real\" sense. We talk of freedom of speech and expression. We TALK of \"coming off age\" and we also TALK of \"defying norms\" and \"breaking conventions\". But then as always \"sheer double standards\" and hypocrisy creeps in and the superficial \"morals\" and the ethics of the so-called Indian Society start getting fenced, lest their existence gets thwarted. Let us all hail the fragile foundations of our respected \"culture\" which is being so pathetically jeopardized by a mere attempt to actually bring some humor and entertainment.\nAn attempt to push the envelope and you have the world pushing you back.\nBecause being regressive is the new Swag.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>','AIB \"Knocked-Out\"','','publish','open','open','','aib-knocked','','','2015-02-08 12:57:56','2015-02-08 12:57:56','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2712',0,'post','',1),(2713,45,'2015-02-05 15:40:42','2015-02-05 15:40:42','','aib knockout','','inherit','open','open','','aib-knockout','','','2015-02-05 15:40:42','2015-02-05 15:40:42','',2712,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/aib-knockout.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2716,41,'2015-02-10 11:21:39','2015-02-10 11:21:39','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Are you an inventor? Let’s get a glimpse of the history first to get a clear picture of how inventions started. So it started with Philosophy. Philosophy is like a tree, and has many branches, and science is one of them. Philosophy needs extensive thinking and imaginations. And Imaginations comes from observations. Newton sat under the tree and thought, imagined and then came up with gravity. All the inventors first observed, then questioned, then wondered and finally reasoned. Imagination became a default process in their invention. That was back then.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Now, with the growing world, and advanced technology, somehow, all the important packages come with a customized option. We live in an era in which, since the day we are born, everything around us tries to replace the default option, Imagination. When a child imagines the sun being made up of gold, stars made up of diamonds, sky being a colorful blanket, we might joke about it, but those kids have the power to imagine and we don’t. Imagination gave us the eyes to realize the earth is not flat, but round. Imagination of such kind gave us the ability to fly, with the help of airplanes.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When was the last time we invented a new word? Yes you read it right; I meant ‘word’ and yes you can do it to. I mean do you really know who invented ‘omg’ or ‘lol’? It’s not that we have given up imagining, we have limited ourselves into thinking that only a certain set of ‘so-called-creative’ members of our society has the birth right to do that. If you make such wide and sweeping assumption and then put a jammer on your brain, you stop yourself from inventing. You have murdered the inventor within you right then and there.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I once read somewhere that, ‘An inventor is person who sees what everybody sees, but perceives in a different way.’ Now, here is another theory, we all are same, yet different from each other. It’s our difference that makes us unique. No two people in the world have same past or present or the future. If the world is at 360 degree, with infinite angles, then everyone has a unique angle of their own and they all have the potential to be an inventor.\nNow that certainly doesn\'t mean that you have to sit under a tree or in bath tub; which is perfectly normal if you do, but invent like your life depends on it. So what are you waiting for? Go ahead and do things differently because at the end everybody is an inventor at heart.</p>','Are you an Inventor?','','publish','open','open','','inventor','','','2015-02-10 11:21:39','2015-02-10 11:21:39','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2716',0,'post','',0),(2717,41,'2015-02-05 16:58:54','2015-02-05 16:58:54','','Invention-Ideas','source: www.arvashow.com','inherit','open','open','','invention-ideas','','','2015-02-05 16:58:54','2015-02-05 16:58:54','',2716,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/invention-ideas.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2725,2,'2015-02-06 05:16:48','2015-02-06 05:16:48','','Delhi Election','','inherit','open','open','','nomination','','','2015-02-06 05:16:48','2015-02-06 05:16:48','',2571,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/nomination.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2730,32,'2015-02-09 14:48:04','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/stock-photo-made-in-india-stamp-131488163.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-2731 size-medium\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/stock-photo-made-in-india-stamp-131488163-287x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"287\" height=\"300\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nYou must have been hearing a lot of hue and cry in media and public over make in India initiative. Some appreciate PM Modi’s initiative of manufacturing in India and some simply criticise it. The endless debate will continue forever but what we have to focus is how it will help us?\n\nLet’s try to understand some facts about both “MAKE IN INDIA” and “MADE IN INDIA”.\n\nMake in India means domestic manufacturing of products. Technologies and license to manufacture will be taken from concerned countries and the products will be manufactured in India.  There are many advantages of this initiative, first and foremost is- it will create jobs. As labour will be needed to manufacture products on large scale. We have abundance of skilled workers but we don’t have job to provide them. This initiative will help in giving job to these people. Secondly, this will increase foreign investment in manufacturing sector. Thirdly, it will decrease imports of foreign products. And in turn Indian markets will grow.\n\nBut is it enough to buy technology from outside and then manufacture in India? Will this serve purpose in a long run?\n\nNo, <strong>Make in India</strong> could help us in short run but we need to focus on <strong>Made in India</strong> for long run. Under Make in India policy every time we need to manufacture anything we will have to buy technology and manufacturing rights from other country. Let’s see example of MiG 21. In spite of several decades of hard work we didn’t gain much. First, we spent crores of rupees in buying manufacturing rights and again we have to go back to Russia to upgrade it.\n\nThis cycle never ends. First we give bundles of money to buy technology then we spent crores every time that technology is upgraded. We spent huge money on their maintenance, repair and overhauling. And all this money goes back to that country. This does not stop here only, the seller country forces India to buy raw materials from their country. The actual overall cost for manufacturing that product exceeds 10-20 times the price of that product.\n\nMake in India is in favour of our economy? Think yourself.  Every single penny that we spent on foreign products adds to their economy. Then why to buy foreign goods? Instead we should focus on making Indian products. The government should provide research centres and equipments so that techniques should be made in India only. Intellectual properties should be owned by us and we will be the real owners.\n\nI know this is an era of globalisation. Our markets have to compete with world. But instead         of starting globally which will only burden us, we should start locally. “Cavin Kare” is the biggest example of this approach. A small company of daily products which started in a small place of India became a global giant today. Every single paisa which it earns either in India or outside comes back to India. This is the benefit of made in India. And it is the correct approach to follow.\n\nMake in India is a good move to meet today’s problem but not for future. For long term stability we need to focus on make in India.\n\nBy make in India we can create workers but can’t create masters.','WHAT DO WE NEED- “MAKE IN INDIA” OR “MADE IN INDIA”?','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-02-09 14:48:04','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2730',0,'post','',0),(2731,32,'2015-02-06 09:54:21','2015-02-06 09:54:21','','stock-photo-made-in-india-stamp-131488163','picture credits- shutterstock.com','inherit','open','open','','stock-photo-made-in-india-stamp-131488163','','','2015-02-06 09:54:21','2015-02-06 09:54:21','',2730,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/stock-photo-made-in-india-stamp-131488163.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2735,45,'2015-02-06 16:14:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<em>“Childhood is the kingdom where no-one dies”</em>\n\n<em> <a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/child-trafficking.jpeg\"><img class=\"alignnone  wp-image-2736\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/child-trafficking.jpeg\" alt=\"child trafficking\" width=\"297\" height=\"201\" /></a></em>\n\nChildren are the most precious gifts that god has bestowed upon this planet. They need strong roots to grow and wings to fly but then their lives begin to end the day they fall victim to such social hazards.\n\nChild trafficking is one such harsh-reality widely rampant in our society and in-spite of rigorous efforts being done in this regard this ceases to perish.\n\nChild trafficking, according to <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UNICEF\">UNICEF</a> is defined as “any person under 18 who is recruited, transported, transferred, harbored or received for the purpose of exploitation, either within or outside a country. If we talk about India, children are trafficked for several purposes, which include begging, labor and sexual exploitation.\n\nAs regards to the carrying out of this process, there is basically a source from which children are trafficked and a destination to which they are taken.\n\nIf we talk about India, Northeastern states or States affected by Naxalites or other such disturbances mainly act as source or suppliers for children who are transported to bigger and lucrative destinations mostly in Delhi or other big cities. Jharkhand, West Bengal, Chhattisgarh and some parts of South India are some of the major “sources” or suppliers. This is because the level of vulnerability is higher amongst those children due to poor socio—economic conditions and also lack of awareness both among the children and their families.\n\nAs a matter of fact there is a ground network that is widespread across remote locations of the country and the whole mechanism operates in a sync making it an industry in its domain. There are village level facilitators who work in disguise and try to win over the confidence of the child and their families and more often than not taking advantage of their condition they exploit the kids by either coercing them or giving them lucrative offers.\n\nThereafter they are taken to their specific centers and from there dispatched to work as household servants or as prostitutes where they suffer extreme oppression. Some children are also made to work as combatants and insurgents, which totally destroys their childhood.\n\nBut no matter how hard we try; it becomes very difficult to prevent innocence from being trapped into cages. A victim of child trafficking not just suffers for that particular period, but bears scars which stay with him for the rest of their life. Their basic rights of freedom, education are snatched away and they are pushed into a dark tunnel from which does not ensure a safe return.\n\nHowever there is another side to the story as well. There are these children who are lucky enough to land up as domestic helpers in households where they receive extremely nice treatment. Amidst the comfort and luxury of Air conditioners and television sets they do not crib about their absence from home. Some families treat them so well that even provide for their education an in-fact make their lives so much better than what it used to be.\n\nBut such cases are very rare and more often that not any experience of trafficking leaves victims traumatized as they are subjected to extremely harsh treatment.\n\nWhat we can reasonably conclude is the fact that “child trafficking” is a menace to the society, a spoiler to those tiny buds which grow up to become beautiful flowers someday.','','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-02-06 16:14:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2735',0,'post','',0),(2736,45,'2015-02-06 16:14:27','2015-02-06 16:14:27','','child trafficking','','inherit','open','open','','child-trafficking','','','2015-02-06 16:14:27','2015-02-06 16:14:27','',2735,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/child-trafficking.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2738,41,'2015-02-07 08:35:49','2015-02-07 08:35:49','We all carry without ourselves a jar of hopes, hopes of finding happiness in every aspect of life. For some of us, it contains the hope for living a life in a city that makes us happy. Figures say that in 75 percent of energy consumption occurs in the cities of our country. 80 percent of gas emissions that cause global warming occur in our cities. One third of the population in every city are living in slums. Name any major issue, like climate change or poverty, are in many ways, are city problems. And certainly we cannot expect some superhero to magically appear, out of nowhere, and solve our problems. This is not new news and we have been hearing this for far too long. So until and unless, people living in the cities take the initiative to solve this problem, they are not going away anywhere.\n\nBut with the last Lok Sabha elections, which took place previous year, the highest voter turnout with 66.4 percent was recorded. With this our country noticed a change and it clearly showed that people were willing to engage in activities with the democratic institution of our country. Finally I believe that we are willing to change what our cities look like by involving ourselves to change the decision-making processes that have given us the results that we have right now. The idea of voting as our only exercise in citizenship which was not making sense earlier is now the most awaited thing for the people living in Delhi. Today, when the voting will be taking place for the Delhi elections, people will decide their own fate of happiness for a better city.\n\nHere we have two most influential personalities, fighting against each other on the political battlefield; both of them have the potential to be the beholder of the power of changing lives and bringing a revolution in the city. Arvind Kejriwal(From AAP) who decided to stand up against the cliché of “Iss desh ka kuch nhi ho sakta”, the man who realizes the turmoil the city is in, is against Kiran Bedi(From BJP), the woman who has served more than half of her life in bringing social reforms in our country. At this point of time, we have already pinned down the pros and cons of electing one of them, and have come to the conclusions of voting one of them. Despite all that, and whatever the result might be, I believe, the results will still bring a positive revolution in the city.\n\nNow, the basic question rises, why? I remember my social science teacher explaining this to me by saying, ‘If you see a healthy competition among the political parties before the elections, you can rest assure, a revolutionary change is about to knock the door.’ Say, for this particular instance, we ignore the rumours of unhealthy practices taking part in Delhi elections, we can certainly feel the power clashing, a struggle for winning which clearly indicates that the government is not taking us for granted and will be willing to put more efforts than usual to gain our trust. And that is the key reason why we, all the while waiting eagerly for the result, can meanwhile relax and accept whatever the outcome might be. Apart from this, we can always pray that the two of the favourite party collaborate with each other and create a history, which will be like a dream come true. Sometimes timing is connected to a major unexpected turn in life, and this is what Delhi is going to see in just a few days.','Rest assured that we are in good hands!','','publish','open','open','','rest-assured-good-hands','','','2015-02-07 08:35:49','2015-02-07 08:35:49','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2738',0,'post','',0),(2739,41,'2015-02-06 18:15:01','2015-02-06 18:15:01','','delhi assembly election 2014','source: dnaindia.com','inherit','open','open','','delhi-assembly-election-2014','','','2015-02-06 18:15:01','2015-02-06 18:15:01','',2738,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/delhi-assembly-election-2014.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2741,41,'2015-02-08 13:43:39','2015-02-08 13:43:39','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">One of the most peaceful things on this earth is to watch a child sleep and the most disturbing thing is to watch a person die in front of your own eyes. Suicide, a collateral damage, that affects so many people, leaves a scar for the rest of their lives. And the primary cause of suicide is depression. Depression is not heartbreak after a breakup or sadness after losing a job or when life goes wrong somewhere. Real depression is being sad when everything is going right.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">What if you woke up tomorrow morning, only to realize there is no hope left in your life? Depression is not the opposite of happiness; it’s the opposite of vitality. You start giving up on your dreams, the people around you and every little thing that once was a matter of life and death to you. Even the mere act of eating food could be as tiring as climbing mountains. Life becomes a living nightmare and you start believing that the only ray of light at the end of the dark tunnel can be achieved through the means of death. Depression is something you live with it and in it. It’s the spouse you cannot divorce, it’s the voice you cannot ignore, it’s the feelings you can’t seem to escape.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">More shockingly, studies have revealed that what the depressives are more scared of is not the fear within them, but the fear of disappointment on other’s face that refrain them from getting help. It’s the stigma of people judging them as ‘weak’ makes them to hold it inside them and hide it, even though they are spending countless sleepless night in suffering. Why? We don\'t talk about depression, we don\'t see it on social media, something which is trending and because that’s not happy or funny. And since we don\'t see it, we don\'t realize the severity and seriousness of it. And the stigma of our society is very real, because we are living in a world where if you break your arm people run over to you to sign your cast but if you tell them you\'re depressed everyone runs the other way. And that is ignorance. We are so accepting of any body part breaking down other than brain, even though depression is one of the best documented problems we have in the world.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The real mortifying truth is that every thirty seconds, someone in the world takes their own life because of depression. It’s happening and it’s happening every single day. What is strange is that the attitude we all tend to carry towards depression and we tend to think, ‘that’s not my problem’. At the most you empathy them, but still carry the attitude of ‘so what?’ with us. Pushing it aside in a corner, pretending it’s not there and thinking it\'ll fix on its own, with this attitude of ours, is just a wishful thinking. This is procrastination of something so important, that is costing lives.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It’s time we took the initiative because depression is an issue not the identity of the person who is suffering from it. So next time you see the signs of hopelessness or signs that tell that the person is believing that things are terrible and are never going to get better, or someone who has recently withdrawal themselves from social life and lost interest in life, confront them. By simply confronting them, head-on, may just save their life and be the turning point for them. Sometimes, its not the talking that you do, but the listening. Listening to understand and not to argue or to blame and even trying to reason them with something rational. By just being there, you can be the turning point that they need.</p>','Depression, an ignorance of our society','','publish','open','open','','depression-ignorance-society','','','2015-02-08 13:43:39','2015-02-08 13:43:39','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2741',0,'post','',0),(2743,41,'2015-02-06 19:22:26','2015-02-06 19:22:26','','depresijaaa','source:kindnessblog.com','inherit','open','open','','depresijaaa','','','2015-02-06 19:22:26','2015-02-06 19:22:26','',2741,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/depresijaaa.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2747,40,'2015-02-13 15:42:28','2015-02-13 15:42:28','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Thanks to government intervention into taking down <a title=\"What is AIB? - Wiki\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/All_India_Bakchod\" target=\"_blank\">AIB</a> knockout video, now a LOT more people know about AIB. For those who still don’t know, AIB is <a title=\"AIB\'s YouTube channel\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/user/allindiabakchod\" target=\"_blank\">All India Bakchod</a> which is basically a YouTube channel that shows comedy sketches and parodies on politics and Indian film industry.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">AIB has FINALLY made it to all daily newspapers and news channels thanks to Akhilesh Tiwari who filed a complaint on 2nd February 2015 for using filthy and abusive language in the AIB Knockout. The video was of a charity “ROAST” organized in south Mumbai on December 20 and uploaded on You Tube on 28th January 2015. It raised almost 40 Lakhs in charity- an event attended who all the ‘who’s who’ of Mumbai.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This video has brought about so many contrevesies, I can\'t begin to list the issues I have with the controversies (Ah, the irony!)</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">But here are top 4 major issues:</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">1. Why are we (as Indians) not thanking AIB and other stand-up comedy artists for <span style=\"color: #333399;\"><strong>taking comedy to an international level</strong></span>- Yes! The one with Russel <a title=\"Russell_Peters Wiki\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell_Peters\" target=\"_blank\">Peters</a>, who has been in this business since 1989.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">2. Why are we not grateful that these talented people enlisted India’s name in the <a title=\"Check it out!\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_sketch_comedy_groups#India\" target=\"_blank\">World’s Sketch Comedy Groups</a>. India has <strong><span style=\"color: #333399;\">just 4 such recognized groups</span></strong> namely The Viral Fever Videos, All India Bakchod, East India Comedy and Pretentious Movie Reviews- whereas countries like Canada, the US and the US has more than 50 of these live stand-up comedy groups. Even Philippines has more such recognized groups than India- and compare the goddamn population!!</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3. If living in India, everyone has a <a title=\"Freedom_of_expression_in_India - Wiki\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freedom_of_expression_in_India\" target=\"_blank\">‘Right to Speech’</a> and if consenting adults agreed to be abused, and it was uploaded on a website which asks for consent before uploading- why is this an issue to others who don’t like the video? <span style=\"color: #333399;\"><strong>Mind your own business</strong></span>, can you? Sorry to be sounding condescending but isn’t this typical ‘Indian’ behavior, that everyone’s business is my business?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4. Why bring <span style=\"color: #333399;\"><strong>culture-religion senti</strong></span> in every issue? US and Canada collectively has almost a 100 such stand up comedians; have they become less Christian? Have they lost faith in their culture? Yes uncles and aunties of the freedom-fighter generation, youngsters do enjoy tongue-in-cheek and abusive comedy- and we are who we are. Why should our views be as ancient as the mythologies of Bhagwat Gita (#hugerespect)? And might I remind everyone Hiroo Johar was in the same audience- and she too enjoyed the show. So shouldn’t your generations learn to move on, rather than pulling back the more progressive ones of today?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em><strong>The whole nation and even people (read Indians) abroad will now be categorized into two: Ones to stand by AIB and the ones who are nuts.</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Maybe, just MAYBE the jokes were repetitive and some might feel it was crass- but in the end <span style=\"color: #333399;\"><strong>it’s the beginning of an era</strong></span>. An era of <span style=\"color: #008000;\"><em>free speech</em></span>, an era where people will go to restaurants and enjoy a <span style=\"color: #008000;\"><em>live comedy show</em></span> with a glass of beer, an era which will give <em><span style=\"color: #008000;\">employment</span></em> to many people who feel useless in a 9 to 9 job and can do something in ‘humour industry’.\nYes, the jokes will get better.\nYes, repetition will be less because these artists will be allowed to speak on whatever topic they want; not restricted by political parties and self proclaimed activists.\nYes, a lot more of such shows will come up, in every big city of the country; maybe even abroad.\nYes, you have to <strong><span style=\"color: #008000;\">learn how to swallow a pill you don’t like</span></strong>- because there this huge population who knows how to <strong><span style=\"color: #333399;\"><em>chew the pill, laugh over it and spit it out once done</em></span>.</strong></p>','Era of stand-up comedy: A beginning or an end?','','publish','open','open','','era-stand-comedy-beginning-end','','','2015-02-13 15:42:28','2015-02-13 15:42:28','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2747',0,'post','',0),(2748,40,'2015-02-08 10:25:06','2015-02-08 10:25:06','','Stand up comedy','Stand up comedy in India','inherit','open','open','','collage','','','2015-02-08 10:25:06','2015-02-08 10:25:06','',2747,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/collage.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2751,40,'2015-02-17 13:01:19','2015-02-17 13:01:19','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">For a 17 year old who enrols into college, it hardly matter where he/she will end up in 10 years. In fact they hardly know where they will be once they graduate in 3 or 4 years. But for a 24-25 year old, this question is of high concern. <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>‘Where is my life going?’</strong></span>.\nOnce we are done with education and know that yes we are now a working man- and will be for the next 40 years, life becomes more predictable. And it’s not even eventually that we start to look for options.\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">“Earn more- Live better”</span></strong> becomes the mantra. Since school we have been a part of rat race. And even in office it becomes as such – complete the targets, get the best hike, switch to a better firm, transfer to a better city, buy a better car than colleague etc.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>But what are we cluelessly giving up in the rat race for success?</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>1. Time for family</strong></span>\nThey stand by us through thick and thin; they support us when we want to move away from home for better job pursuits; they are “OKAY” if we just call on weekends; they seem “FINE” when we visit them once in 6 months or an year. But is it fair? We know what goes round comes around. Do we want to be in that situation where when we are 80, our kids call us once in a month, just to ask if the money they sent was enough?\nYes, moving up the career ladder is important; but <em><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">as we climb higher- it gets lonelier</span></em>. Wouldn’t it be good if we know how to stay grounded even when we have an 8 or 9 digit salary? To hear old stories about how bread was just Rs 3 and kids used to go walk miles for school. To <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><em>know happiness</em></span> is not a big bank balance, but lighting diyas in the verandah.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>2. Time for old friends</strong></span>\nMost of the ‘office people’ are \'colleagues\' and not ‘friends’. We tend to find solace in confiding in them, but how sure are we that the next time a bonus is around- they wouldn\'t jump over us for the opportunity? That’s why old school and college friends are helpful in bringing back the <em><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">good-old happy memories</span></em>. Would we give up those memories to work extra on a weekday? Would we trade those moments of laughter for an extra pay?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>3. Time for self</strong></span>\n<em><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">‘When was the last time you did something for the first time?’</span></em> Research shows that taking a break and indulging into new hobbies helps boost performance at work. And that seems logical too. On one hand if I had to stay home all weekend, listening to my spouse complain, watching dirty politics on TV and getting groceries- I would go back more frustrated on the Monday. As compared to if I took a road trip to a nearby lake, read a bestseller book and sipped on some green tea lying on a mat. Me time is a must! <em><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Do what you gotta do to</span></em> pump yourself up!</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>4. Time to switch off</strong></span>\n<em><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Know when to say NO!</span></em> Taking over office work at home for just 2-3 hours of extra work will not be helpful in the long run. Know when to say, ‘I am off to home now- See you tomorrow’. Be it a birthday in your family or a small headache- <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><em>why risk health today earning money; only to spend it 20 years later on treatments?</em></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>5. Morals and ethics</strong></span>\nLast but certainly not the least, adding 10 to a target figure will fetch us a pat on the back today, but <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><em>KARMA is a bitch.</em></span> Call me spiritual, call me old-fashioned, but this worked for me for a long time that I have to agree blindly. Do good and good will come onto you! Do bad and you know, <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><em>what goes around comes around!\n</em></span>We shouldn\'t forget it’s not just the paper trail that should be concerned about; it is about sleeping better in the night and not watching over our back every time something goes wrong in the company.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In my opinion, if all the above 5 are followed for getting success, we might not get THAT filthy rich so soon- but we will be happier and more content with our careers; which will give us more confidence to <strong>rise above others</strong> (and I don’t mean it just with respect to career).</p>','What would you give up for success?','','publish','open','open','','what-would-you-give-up-for-success','','','2015-02-17 13:01:19','2015-02-17 13:01:19','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2751',0,'post','',1),(2752,40,'2015-02-08 11:21:52','2015-02-08 11:21:52','','success','what would you give up for success?','inherit','open','open','','vlg_ratrace-grid-4x2','','','2015-02-08 11:21:52','2015-02-08 11:21:52','',2751,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/vlg_ratrace.grid-4x2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2759,42,'2015-02-08 12:53:57','2015-02-08 12:53:57','','aib','','inherit','open','open','','aib','','','2015-02-08 12:53:57','2015-02-08 12:53:57','',2712,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/aib.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2779,42,'2015-02-09 15:02:19','2015-02-09 15:02:19','','Freedom-of-Expression-120531mg','','inherit','open','open','','freedom-of-expression-120531mg','','','2015-02-09 15:02:19','2015-02-09 15:02:19','',2643,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/freedom-of-expression-120531mg.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2798,40,'2015-02-11 17:28:08','2015-02-11 17:28:08','<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">With valentine\'s day just around the corner, a lot of men are in a fix what to get their women.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">The <strong>bachelors</strong> are happy they have no such worries. The online shopping websites have jumped their guns by announcing <strong>customized V-Day shopping</strong>. But even then it leaves the poor men with the big billion dollar question, <em><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>\"What do women want?\"</strong></span></em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Like most of the world assumes, on V-Day, there should be gifts and a cosy romantic dinner. But I beg to differ. Yes agreed, all these ideas of flowers and chocolates and gifts have come up because women like to feel good or feel special on this particular day. But to think of it, why should such a gesture be limited only between couples? Why should the single men and women be left out?</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">To celebrate love or to express your feelings, why is buying something only for your lady love essential? Why not to celebrate with every woman around you who has been a part of your life some way or the other?\nIn fact, <strong>women aren\'t so materialistic.</strong> (Or if I put it another way, men are equally materialistic). Although all the reports and polls suggests otherwise.</p>\n\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_2799\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"550\"]<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/valentines-men-women-2014.png\"><img class=\"wp-image-2799 size-full\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/valentines-men-women-2014.png\" alt=\"what men want to gift on Valentine\'s Day\" width=\"550\" height=\"300\" /></a> What women want on Valentine\'s Day[/caption]\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">But in my opinion, sorry Jabong, Flipkart and Amazon, <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>the best gift for this Valentine\'s would be equality.</strong> </span>\nTreat women as equals. Not just on 14th, but start this 14th. Make it a day not just for celebrating love in couples, but the love of women in your life, in general.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>Be it any woman.</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"padding-left: 30px; text-align: justify;\">Because you know your <span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>mother</strong></span> works as hard as your father,\nyour <span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>female colleagues</strong></span> puts in same amount of hours as you,\nyour <span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>bfff</strong></span> (best female friend forever) finds time to meet you even if she has a job and 2 kids,\nyour <span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>girl friend</strong></span> has secretly put together a scrap book (which you\'ll put away in a corner a day later),\nyour <span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>live-in partner</strong></span> cooks you your favourite cuisine before you come back home after a bad day and\nyour <span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>wife</strong> </span>knows what to buy for each of your relative when you go home.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">And hence there should be <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><em>no age limit to celebrate Valentine\'s Day</em></span>. There should be no limit on Valentine\'s Day celebration at all. It should be a day to celebrate the love of all women in your life!</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>For a 10 year old,</strong> this should be the day he picks a <span style=\"color: #0000ff;\">girl in his football team.</span>\n<strong>For a 20 year old,</strong> this should be the day he stops telling his room-mates <span style=\"color: #0000ff;\">gossip about a popular girl</span> in college.\n<strong>For a 30 year old,</strong> this should be the day he stops<span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"> judging his colleague</span> for getting a bonus higher than him.\n<strong>For a 40 year old,</strong> this should be the day he stops <span style=\"color: #0000ff;\">taking out his mid-life frustration</span> at his wife.\n<strong>For a 50 year old,</strong> this should be the day he stops judging a younger assistant because of her <span style=\"color: #0000ff;\">dressing sense.</span>\n<strong>For a 60 year old,</strong> this should be the day he stops <span style=\"color: #0000ff;\">expecting his daughter in law</span> to cook as good as his mother.</p>\n\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_2803\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"647\"]<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/valentines-day.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-2803\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/valentines-day.jpg\" alt=\"Mark the day- each man should celebrate!\" width=\"647\" height=\"340\" /></a> Mark the day- each man should celebrate![/caption]\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">This Valentine\'s Day, <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>there is something for every man to do.</strong></span> Stop feeling like this day is only for couples (married or in love). Because this is the day you treat all women with love because clearly there is no existence of life without women. And it\'s not just one woman who deserves to celebrate Valentine\'s with you.\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>Treat them better: Treat them as equals.</strong> <strong>That\'s what women want</strong></span>; and that\'s what you should be gifting each woman around you this Valentine\'s.</p>\n&nbsp;','This Valentine\'s, know what women really want!','','publish','open','open','','valentines-know-women-really-want','','','2015-02-11 17:28:08','2015-02-11 17:28:08','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2798',0,'post','',4),(2799,40,'2015-02-11 08:42:47','2015-02-11 08:42:47','','valentines men women','what women want on Valentine\'s Day','inherit','open','open','','valentines-men-women-2014','','','2015-02-11 08:42:47','2015-02-11 08:42:47','',2798,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/valentines-men-women-2014.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2800,40,'2015-02-11 08:45:38','2015-02-11 08:45:38','','All I want for Valentine\'s Day','What do women really want?','inherit','open','open','','alliwantforvalentinesdayborder500','','','2015-02-11 08:45:38','2015-02-11 08:45:38','',2798,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/alliwantforvalentinesdayborder500.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2803,40,'2015-02-11 08:55:23','2015-02-11 08:55:23','','valentines day','Mark the day- each man should celebrate!','inherit','open','open','','valentines-day','','','2015-02-11 08:55:23','2015-02-11 08:55:23','',2798,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/valentines-day.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2816,48,'2015-02-12 17:32:32','2015-02-12 17:32:32','<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/letter-background-3.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-2817\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/letter-background-3.jpg\" alt=\"Change\" width=\"768\" height=\"983\" /></a>\n\n<strong><span data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$0:0\">Where is a change?</span></strong><br data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$1:0\" /><span data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$2:0\">Not having any fixed range</span><br data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$3:0\" /><span data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$4:0\">Might seem quite strange</span><br data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$5:0\" /><span data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$6:0\">I look around for the change!</span><br data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$7:0\" /><span data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$8:0\">Might be before you,or hidden somewhere</span><br data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$9:0\" /><span data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$10:0\">Will start from a spark,shine like glare</span><br data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$11:0\" /><span data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$12:0\">Seeking for change,I must go where??</span><br data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$13:0\" /><span data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$14:0\">It\'s within me,waiting to be found</span><br data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$15:0\" /><span data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$16:0\">To move around,without being bound</span><br data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$17:0\" /><span data-reactid=\".89.$mid=11423505038587=2ab72667dad61c6f008.2:0.0.0.0.0.0.$end:0:$18:0\">\'A change\',I heard the sound!</span>','Where is a Change?','','publish','open','open','','change','','','2015-02-12 17:32:32','2015-02-12 17:32:32','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2816',0,'post','',0),(2817,2,'2015-02-12 17:29:26','2015-02-12 17:29:26','','Need for change','What is a Change','inherit','open','open','','letter-background-3','','','2015-02-12 17:29:26','2015-02-12 17:29:26','',2816,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/letter-background-3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2826,42,'2015-02-12 20:22:36','2015-02-12 20:22:36','','indian_science_congress_PTI','','inherit','open','open','','indian_science_congress_pti','','','2015-02-12 20:22:36','2015-02-12 20:22:36','',2639,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/indian_science_congress_pti.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2849,38,'2015-02-16 12:57:10','0000-00-00 00:00:00','Education is the need of the hour and we will be producing a series of articles on the same topic. As a warmer, let us tell you why we picked education and how deeply related India and illiteracy are.\n\nThe Indian society faces a lot of serious issues, agreed and what we do realize is that each and every issue is so intricately connected to the others such that they all form a vicious cycle. Greed leads to corruption which leads to inequality which causes poverty which fuels illiteracy and because of lack of education there are more anti-social elements and this is just one small example of such a cycle. Somehow, we are convinced that illiteracy is the major issue that can be fought and we will directly be up against the fight of poverty, child labor, unemployment, overpopulation and so much more. Illiteracy is indeed the greatest of all evils.\n\nIt is not that India has been in this state from the past. Aren’t we the nation with the Vedas? Haven’t we read about Nalanda University? Historians state that it was operational from around 5<sup>th</sup> Century till 1200 CE and that is really a long time for a learning centre to sustain. What happened to the great nation today and where do we stand in terms of literacy?\n\nSeveral smaller countries like Sri Lanka, Myanmar, Vietnam, Thailand have a better literacy rate and indicate faster development. Also, we cannot blame our population as China has also increased their literacy rate so much faster. To further prove that literacy rates matter, the World Bank has established a direct relationship between literacy and the overall quality of human life.\n\nWhen you search on Google for India illiteracy, what comes up is a shame - \"<b>India</b> has by far the largest population of <b>illiterate</b> adults at 287 million, amounting to 37 per cent of the global total, a United Nations report said highlighting the huge disparities existing in education levels of the country\'s rich and poor.\" We can look at some statistics that prove the condition that India is in is actually worrisome. All figures and stats are from the official <a href=\"http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/data_files/india/Final_PPT_2011_chapter6.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Census of India</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/1.png\"><img class=\"  wp-image-2851 aligncenter\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/1-300x129.png\" alt=\"1\" width=\"440\" height=\"189\" /></a>\n\nOn first glance, we can see that there is marginal improvement in the literacy rate of India. Over the last decade, this has been the general trend. I think it is majorly due to better awareness, more efforts from our Government, several NGOs taking up this issue and a lot of individual philanthropically conscious undertakings.\n\n<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/11.png\"><img class=\"  wp-image-2852 aligncenter\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/11-300x129.png\" alt=\"1\" width=\"475\" height=\"204\" /></a>\n\nWhile the overall rate seems to be increasing, women seem to be yet behind men in terms of literacy rates. This brings back a whole box of troubles that we all know exists. This trend seems to be existent more in rural areas where people are still hesitant to send girls to school. They yet prefer getting them married at a younger age and this is majorly due to their own lack of knowledge. Guess not everyone knows the saying – “You teach a woman and you help her teach her kids and thereby you teach the nation”.\n\n<a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/12.png\"><img class=\"  wp-image-2853 aligncenter\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/12-263x300.png\" alt=\"1\" width=\"294\" height=\"335\" /></a>\n\nWhen I analyze the numbers state wise, kudos to Kerala for being on the top of the charts for as long as I can remember. They have a literacy rate of 93.91%. Can you imagine what that means? Almost 9 in 10 people in Kerala have access to good education. If only we could all delve into how that happens and spread that to all the other states too.\n\nIlliteracy is more powerful than you can imagine. It can bring down the growth that our nation needs and it is in all our hands to solve this issue. Politicians should come up with great programs to eradicate illiteracy and implement it but they seem to have other priorities.\n\nWhat can you do as a citizen? If you are here and you are reading the post, you are one of the blessed people to have access to good education. I strongly support the “each one teach one\" cause. You can always take time from your busy schedule and try to teach someone who lives around you. It could be the boy who delivers your morning newspaper or your maid’s kids. You can also sign up for programs like “Teach India” who are trying to make a difference. It can be something as simple as you teaching them the alphabet or how to write the letters of your regional language.\n\nChange does not just happen; you have got to make it happen. The time for a change is now. I am up for it, are you?','India and illiteracy at a glance','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-02-16 12:57:10','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2849',0,'post','',0),(2850,38,'2015-02-16 04:52:57','2015-02-16 04:52:57','Illiteracy-in-India','Illiteracy-in-India','Illiteracy-in-India','inherit','open','open','','illiteracy-in-india','','','2015-02-16 04:52:57','2015-02-16 04:52:57','',2849,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/illiteracy-in-india.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2851,38,'2015-02-16 04:55:49','2015-02-16 04:55:49','','1','','inherit','open','open','','1-2','','','2015-02-16 04:55:49','2015-02-16 04:55:49','',2849,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2852,38,'2015-02-16 04:56:53','2015-02-16 04:56:53','','1','','inherit','open','open','','1-3','','','2015-02-16 04:56:53','2015-02-16 04:56:53','',2849,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/11.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2853,38,'2015-02-16 04:57:44','2015-02-16 04:57:44','','1','','inherit','open','open','','1-4','','','2015-02-16 04:57:44','2015-02-16 04:57:44','',2849,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/12.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2864,40,'2015-02-26 19:49:46','2015-02-26 19:49:46','Being a middle-class Brahmin, I hear a lot about <strong>caste</strong> because of which the debate of reservation and quota always gets me excited. When as a kid, I used to see my father and some of his other \'office friends\' chat about the idea of abolishing reservation, I wasn\'t quite sure what the repuccursions would be. As a grown up <em>(or so they say)</em>, I still dont have an aswer to that.\n\nToday, in my petty understanding, <strong>allocation of reservation for students</strong> is just another political move for getting vote bank of any ‘minority group’, be it for the Scheduled Castes (SC), Scheduled Tribe (ST) or Other Backward Classes (OBCs).\n\nTalking to a <strong>Kashmiri Pundit</strong> friend recently, I realized a lot has been <del>done</del> tried for them as well but, till now, there has been no substantial development or results- be it; which is the case for most of the under-privileged sects of our country.\n\nI still remember the <a title=\"see Wikipedia for more\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2006_Indian_anti-reservation_protests\" target=\"_blank\">2006 Indian anti-reservation protests</a> which took place in opposition to the decision of United Progressive Alliance (UPA) to implement reservations for the OBCs in central and private institutes of higher education. This proposal agitated the general public as it reduced seats for the <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>‘general category’</strong></span> from the then existing 77.5% to <strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">less than 51%</span> </strong>(since members of OBCs are also allowed to contest in the General category), which it is today.\n\nThis decision seemed <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>unfair and absolutely illogical</strong> </span>to the people who DID NOT belong to these sects.\n\n<strong>Petitions, protests and prayers</strong> later, on 10 April 2008, the Supreme Court upheld the law for the provision of 27% quota for candidates belonging to the OBCs, but directed the government to exclude the \"creamy layer\" while implementing the law. However, the <strong>\"creamy layer\" exclusion would not be applied to the SC/STs.</strong> (<a title=\"see more\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reservation_in_India\" target=\"_blank\">source</a>)\n\nTo a certain extent, this seemed more logical because the already uplifted ‘creamy’ ones should not be given the reservation- thus restoring the faith in our country’s apex court.\n\nBut the quintessential question here is why isn’t such criteria in place for SCs and STs?\n\nLet’s rewind back a bit, break this problem into pieces.\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">According to the government, the philosophy behind reservation is that it is necessary to undo and counter the \'evils\' of centuries of caste system that prevailed in the country.<strong> <span style=\"color: #008000;\">OKAY.</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Currently, reservation of 15%, 7.5% and 27% seats is provided for candidates hailing from SC, ST and OBCs. <strong><span style=\"color: #008000;\">OKAY.</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">In case enough candidates do not meet minimum qualifying criteria as per written tests, SC/ST candidates are permitted a relaxation of 50%. WHY? For the time being, let’s say, <span style=\"color: #008000;\"><strong>we’re OKAY.</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">If some vacancies still exist, a further relaxation is offered with a deferred admission after 1 year of Preparatory Course study. <span style=\"color: #008000;\"><strong>OKAY.</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">But this goes against the idea of merit.</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Reservations for SC/ST are not reaching the needy.</span></p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">If more than one generation in a family has benefited in the past through reservation, why is their next generation also availing reservation benefits?</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Doesn’t this actually limit the other SC/ST people? The deserving ones who can’t get through their choice of institute given all the relaxations?</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><em>For example, child of an SC/ST IAS officer gets into IIT Delhi through quota but in NIT Jaipur through General. Obvious choice will be to take IIT Delhi. But on the other hand, there is a SC/ST villager’s kid who gets admission waitlisted and maybe doesn’t get convert this year because all reservation seats were full. Is this fair?</em></p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><strong><span style=\"color: #008000;\">Is there is need of an hour to introduce \'creamy layer\' exemption in SC/ST and all other reservations to ensure reachability of this scheme?</span></strong></p>\nShouldn’t the reservation be given on merit basis, criteria only being educational and economic background of parents?\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Imagine this</span></strong>- no reservation. Everyone writes entrance exams. 50% reserved quota for meritorious students from poor economic backgrounds. Because it’s them we are aiming to uplift right? Giving them the opportunity to study in the best of institutes which they can’t afford to otherwise?\n\n<em><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Remove the criteria of caste. Our ancestors divided us in castes. We should abolish such division- not reinforce it.</span></em>\n\nDo these policy makers favoring caste based reservation know that:\n<ol>\n	<li>Close to 2o% of reserved category students are unable to cope in stressful environment of premier institutes in under graduation?</li>\n	<li>Even if they become successful, most people do not prefer to go to a lower caste doctor?</li>\n	<li>When it comes to marriage, only people of same lower caste would actually accept proposals- others would be outraged.</li>\n	<li>Except the more-open-generation of 90s, people still do not give social acceptance/equality to people from lower castes?</li>\n</ol>\nIf such reservation policy is not helping the lower castes to uplift their status and help them be equal amongst others, <strong>what’s the whole point?</strong>\n\nWhat is the bigger picture here? Why do we have reservation? <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>Should the caste based reservation be abolished?</strong></span>\n\nIn my opinion, <span style=\"color: #339966;\"><strong>keep that 50% reservation</strong></span>- <span style=\"color: #000000;\">reserve seats for everyone, be it SCs, STs, OBCs, Kashmiri Migrants, Sons/daughters of Freedom Fighters, Physically handicapped, Sports personalities, Non-Resident Indians. Give it to everyone- with</span> <span style=\"color: #339966;\"><strong>just one condition – poor economic background.</strong></span>\n\n<strong>So that there is some equality as we move on from generation to generation.</strong>','Reservations and Quotas: To uplift the needy?','','publish','open','open','','reservations-and-quotas-to-uplift-the-needy','','','2015-02-26 19:49:46','2015-02-26 19:49:46','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2864',0,'post','',0),(2865,40,'2015-02-18 11:26:19','2015-02-18 11:26:19','','reservation in india','','inherit','open','open','','reservation-in-india','','','2015-02-18 11:26:19','2015-02-18 11:26:19','',2864,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/reservation-in-india.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2874,23,'2015-02-18 19:59:42','2015-02-18 19:59:42','<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>‘Strength and dignity are her clothing, and she smiles at the future.’ Bible (Pro 31:25)</em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Constitution bestows upon us the Right to Freedom but most girls in India are aware about how exaggerated the whole idea of freedom is. In a patriarchal society, the men can never be wrong, even as they fail to be logical. With each rape case, the men find new reasons to blame women for it. One of the most preposterous male arguments happens to be the ‘clothing of the victim.’ In such a world, can the woman really be clothing herself in strength and dignity, when she knows that a man standing at the next corner is ready to strip her off it?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As a young girl who goes to college, I can tell you that I try my best to dress appropriately. I avoid wearing shorts or skirts. I wear proper shirts to make sure that I don’t attract any sort of unwanted attention. Call me a hypocrite but I am aware of the society that I live in and I know that if anything happens then my clothing will be blamed. It’ll partly be the reason for any sort of assault on me, considering the fact that every Indian man thinks that a girl wearing short clothes is a pretty invitation card waiting to be opened. However, an instance that took place a week ago sort of shook me and while reading this story, please keep in mind that I was wearing winter clothes which means I was covered from head to toe.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Having missed my first class because of lazy winter mornings, I was sitting in the canteen area. A boy walked up to me and said he wanted to talk to me. I thought he genuinely wanted my help and  I took off my earphones and asked him what he wanted to talk about. This young man, all of a sudden, took the liberty of sitting right next to me. He said he wanted to ‘make fraansip with me’. I told him I wasn’t ready for this friendship and the expression on his face was plain scary. It felt like my rejection had hurt his male pride. While I dealt with the trauma of being one of those girls who’ve been hit on with the infamous ‘mujhse fraandship karoge’ line, my friends told me I should probably save myself from an acid attack. What really got me thinking was that I was wearing proper clothes and I didn’t look like an invitation but this boy still thought that he could take advantage of the fact that I was sitting alone.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/rape-deterrent-clothing-unveiled-in-india.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-2876\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/rape-deterrent-clothing-unveiled-in-india-300x190.jpg\" alt=\"Rape-Deterrent-Clothing-Unveiled-in-India\" width=\"300\" height=\"190\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This little incident made me realize that clothes don’t cause rape, rapists do. I’m a girl living in Indian and I’m unsafe, no matter what I wear. As a young woman, I am forced to live within the shackles of patriarchy that want me to adjust my wardrobe according to the desperation of the men. Obviously, the consensual nature of the act of sex is never taken into account. If a girl did get raped wearing short clothes, nobody would acknowledge the fact that it was a forced act. Another example of the sick society we stay in where men just assume they have a right to rape women dressed in a particular way. The men are carefully protected and siphoned off any responsibility of their action this way.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The basic freedom of expression and the right to live is countered by the dull argument of clothing and this kind of social policing is only creating new space for more rapes to take place in the country. It is high time that we become more logical as a society and start looking at more real dynamics that cause rape. In the bizarre conditioning of the Indian society, clothing is given more priority than the actual issue.</p>','The Rape Clothing','','publish','open','open','','rape-clothing','','','2015-02-18 19:59:42','2015-02-18 19:59:42','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2874',0,'post','',0),(2875,42,'2015-02-18 19:32:45','2015-02-18 19:32:45','FILE - In this Wednesday, Jan. 2, 2013 file photo, Indian women carry signs as they march to mourn the death of a gang rape victim in New Delhi, India. For decades, women have had little choice but to walk away when groped in a crowded bus or train, or to simply cringe as someone tosses an obscene comment their way. Even if they haven\'t experienced explicit sexual abuse themselves, they live with the fear that it could happen to them or a loved one. The gang rape and beating of a 23-year-old university student on a moving bus in India\'s capital has taken sexual violence - a subject long hidden in the shadows of Indian society - and thrust it into the light. (AP Photo/Dar Yasin, File)','India Gang Rape Hope for Change','','inherit','open','open','','india-gang-rape-hope-for-change','','','2015-02-18 19:32:45','2015-02-18 19:32:45','',2874,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/india_top.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2876,42,'2015-02-18 19:37:29','2015-02-18 19:37:29','','Rape-Deterrent-Clothing-Unveiled-in-India','','inherit','open','open','','rape-deterrent-clothing-unveiled-in-india','','','2015-02-18 19:37:29','2015-02-18 19:37:29','',2874,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/rape-deterrent-clothing-unveiled-in-india.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2887,23,'2015-02-20 19:32:51','2015-02-20 19:32:51','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Pearl Mali was like any other normal girl. She had all these grand dreams about finding the love of her life and living happily ever after. The clichéd stuff. However, her story had an interesting twist. She knew she’d have to run away once she actually finds the love of her life because she was sexually inclined towards the same sex. Such unions were not just considered to be sinful but punishable. Initially, like any young individual, she had full faith in the changing times and increasing ‘modernity’. All her faith snapped when her own mother got an elderly priest into the house to rape her in an attempt to cure her, of you know, the feelings she had about other girls.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In 2011, Noxolo Nogwaza’s body was found in a ditch near Johannesburg. She was last seen with a female friend in a bar. Noxolo was a lesbian and also placed a lot of her trust in the changing ideas of the world. She was one of those who believed that they could finally come out of the closet but then she also belonged to the group of those who paid a heavy price for it. She was raped multiple times before being put to death. Her body had been mutilated to the extent where her brain had been shattered and her teeth were scattered around her body. A painful death administered by those who desperately hoped that Noxolo would be born again as a cured person. They just didn’t realize that they were putting all her dreams to an end which probably didn’t have anything to do with her sexuality. Her murderers didn’t realize that they were cutting out a hole of her size in her mother’s life. Her friends would miss her for the confident and cheerful girl that she was, not for the lesbian who had been found dead in a ditch.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Thamsanqa Mduhuli, a gay man, was raped by a group of men. They claimed that by doing so, they are restoring Thamsanqa’s manhood. So this whole concept of ‘corrective rape’ targets not just the women but also men who are homosexuals. The term ‘corrective rape’ originated in Africa but it is also prevalent in India. The reason why the term isn’t used much is because people barely go report anything of the sort. In the country of Article 377, one wouldn’t dare go lodge a report that would say that they were raped for being gay. The police might add to their misery by putting them in jail.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/a.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter  wp-image-2893\" src=\"http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/a.png\" alt=\"a\" width=\"341\" height=\"274\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">India has never shied away from articulating it’s hatred for homosexuality. One can only understand that the reason for it is that the whole idea of homosexuality would make any patriarchal society insecure. But how do you justify raping someone based on your insecurity? Especially when the term ‘corrective rape’ doesn’t even capture the gravity of the act. The compromise of bodily integrity and the psychological impact can leave a person completely shattered and far from ‘cured’. Adding to the Indian situation is Article 377 which would prevent any victim from reaching out for legal help.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Sadly, there isn’t much that can be done in legal terms except for sitting and praying that one day our legislators will realize that they need to protect each citizen despite of their sexual orientation. We can start by becoming more aware and making people more aware. Raping can cure no one, especially not a gay person. As the youth of India, we can start by becoming more tolerable to homosexual individuals and less tolerable towards acts of rape.</p>','When Rape Corrects','','publish','open','open','','rape-corrects','','','2015-02-20 19:32:51','2015-02-20 19:32:51','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2887',0,'post','',0),(2889,2,'2015-02-20 19:28:32','2015-02-20 19:28:32','','dm_100511_e60_corrective_rape','','inherit','open','open','','dm_100511_e60_corrective_rape','','','2015-02-20 19:28:32','2015-02-20 19:28:32','',2887,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/dm_100511_e60_corrective_rape.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2893,2,'2015-02-20 19:36:06','2015-02-20 19:36:06','','a','','inherit','open','open','','a-2','','','2015-02-20 19:36:06','2015-02-20 19:36:06','',2887,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/a.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2902,23,'2015-02-23 14:08:49','2015-02-23 14:08:49','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are all these notions about love being priceless and pure that probably developed a long time back with, maybe, Adam and Eve. You know, back when Adam wasn’t too busy with his business and Eve wasn’t too neglected or bored. Now, everything has a price tag. One would assume that it is fun being a male prostitute or gigolo, which is a cuter term but it isn’t. The idea about men being crazy about sex was shattered the day I stepped into my job. My name is Sidharth and I’m 25 years old. I am from a tiny place in Nagaland and came to Bombay with my eyes full of dreams. Everybody thought I had the face for modeling and I internalized other’s thought process. However, what everybody didn’t tell me was that becoming a model and having the face for it were two completely separate things. After 4 years of failure, I decided to stay. Going back would be horrible. There were voices in my head of all the people making fun of me and taunting me. I did become a prisoner to my thoughts. Since I didn’t have any source of income, I decided to become a prostitute. Yes, men can sell their bodies too. It is a very real thing, as strange as it may sound. Statistics say that out of the 70% people caught for employing prostitutes, 20% are clients of the male prostitutes.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The kind of things we have to do range from decent to horrendous and I use the term decent very loosely. Women want us to do ‘sweet’ things. So the manager may ask us to take chocolates for them or tell them they are beautiful. Obviously, these are rich women looking for a little love which they don’t get from their husbands. Hence, they pay for whatever love they can get, even though they know it is pretentious. In today’s world, one can only play make believe games about concepts like companionship. This happened to me. I was in love with Naureen, a beautiful girl I met during my modeling days. We were together for 3 years and then she proposed for marriage. I agreed and had all these dreams set in my mind about our house and children and a wonderful life together. However, my profession pulled me back to the ground. The day I told her what I did for a living, she left me. She vanished out of my life. I don’t know where she is or what she does. Frankly, I miss her all the time. At times, when I’m having my food alone, in an empty house, I end up crying. Despite of this, I manage to go out and make other women happy. Men aren’t always animals of lust. At times, we just want to be held even though we wouldn’t admit it. At times, we bump into women who change our life, who become our life.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are those bad days when customers dupe me. Once a man called and asked me to come to a hotel room. When I reached, I saw 3 men in a room and it wasn’t the best experience. Whatever I did, was against my will. The saddest part is, that I can’t say no. There is always that argument that customers present where they say ‘we’re paying for it.’</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Despite of all this, I manage. I send my mother money on time and more than enough of it. I’ve told her I got into a business here. It isn’t entirely wrong. I live in a nice locality and wear costly clothes. I can tell you I’d give it all away for a normal life but it is a vicious circle now. I became a prisoner to the voices inside my head and now I’m a prisoner to my profession. Well, as long as my family can be kept happy, I’ll do anything.</p>','Let\'s Buy Love!!!','','publish','open','open','','lets-buy-love','','','2015-02-23 14:08:49','2015-02-23 14:08:49','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2902',0,'post','',0),(2903,2,'2015-02-23 14:06:51','2015-02-23 14:06:51','','male-prostitute_2_','','inherit','open','open','','male-prostitute_2_','','','2015-02-23 14:06:51','2015-02-23 14:06:51','',2902,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/male-prostitute_2_.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2911,40,'2015-02-24 18:19:11','2015-02-24 18:19:11','<span style=\"color: #000000\">Very recently, <em><span style=\"color: #0000ff\">West Bengal CM</span></em> Mamata Banerjee said this about Swine Flu: \"People have to move from one place to another. In many cases, it spreads from mosquito bites. We have asked the authorities to keep isolated beds ready to tackle the situation.\"</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">To add to the absurd remarks, <span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><em>Mumbai Mayor</em></span> Snehal Ambekar said \"Swine flu is a heart disease. Hence, BMC will plant trees, develop gardens and parks to check swine flu.\"</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">This is not the first time a politician or public servant has given a misinformed statement. In fact this just adds to the list:</span>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\">Chautala, <span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><em>Former Chief Minister of Haryana</em></span>: “Marry off girls early to prevent rape.”</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\">Chiranjeet Chakraborty, <span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><em>Trinamool Congress legislator</em></span>: “One of the reasons behind the increase in incidents of eve-teasing is short dresses and short skirts worn by women. This in turn instigates young men.”</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\">Jitender Chhatar, <span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><em>Khap Panchayat leader</em>:</span> \"Consumption of fast food contributes to such incidents. Chowmein leads to hormonal imbalance evoking an urge to indulge in such acts.\"</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\">Botsa Satyanarayana, <span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><em>Andhra Pradesh Congress Chief</em></span>: “Just because India achieved freedom at midnight does not mean that women can venture out after dark.”</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><em>Rahul Gandhi</em></span>: “Poverty is a state of mind.”</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\">Ajit Pawar,<span style=\"color: #0000ff\"> <em>Deputy Chief Minister of Maharashtra</em></span>: \"If there is no water in the dam, how can we release it? Should we urinate into it? If there is no water to drink, even urination is not possible.\"</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\">Mulayam Singh,<em><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"> Samajwadi Party Chief</span></em>: \"Ladke, ladke hain. Galti ho jati hai.\"</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\">Ashoka Singhal, <span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><em>VHP Leader</em></span>: \"Hindu couples should have 5 children else they\'ll be reduced to a minority in this country.\"</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\">Vinay Bihari, <span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><em>Minister of Art, Culture and Youth Affairs</em></span>: \"People who eat more non-vegetarian food are inclined towards carrying out rape.\"</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><em>Baba Ramdev</em></span>: \"If our parents were homosexuals, then we would not have been born. So it\'s unnatural. I guarantee to cure them of homosexuality.\"</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><em>Raj Thackeray</em></span>: “Terror attacks in Mumbai have grown due to increase in the population of the north Indians in the city.”</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\">Murli Manohar Joshi, <span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><em>Ex- HRD Minister</em></span>, after he drank ferrous sulphate solution in a school science fair and later ended up in a hospital: \"I thought it was juice.\"</span></li>\n</ul>\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">India being a free country, everyone has a right to say what they want-when they want. And that includes our elected leaders. Only, one would expect them to be more responsible in putting forward their views since they get published in the many daily newspapers India boasts about (counting millions in circulation). </span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">Today, what we say may not matter- what they say becomes a voice that reaches millions of people across the globe. What we say may not have much repercussions, what they say might change the mind-set of thousands.</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">Which brings us<del></del> to the question- why is it that our not-that-educated and some well-educated politicians end up saying absurd things when a camera or mike is pointed at them?</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">I am no expert and neither do I question if these politicians or their team regulates what is written for the speeches or if pay the speech writers enough to ensure actual facts are quoted. </span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">But there are people in some sects of our society who are uneducated enough to believe what our netas say- be it the cause of rape or swine flu. And not just the lower sects, a lot of people are, in general, influenced by the thinking of their elected leaders/politicians.</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">In that case <strong>who should be taking responsibility of quoting such wrong facts in public?</strong> Who is taking responsibility that our netas are even educated enough to address to masses regarding health or any issue for that matter.</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">They all make big promises in their manifestos about girl child education, about women empowerment, about government schools, about policies; but <strong>how much do they REALLY know</strong> about it? Who is responsible for the education of our politicians? </span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">You would think they appoint people in their office to do such things. So did I.</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">And here is the news from last week:</span>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><em>Telangana Chief Minister K Chandrasekhar Rao has appointed a Vastu consultant to his Government. All major projects and future of this newly formed state will now depend on Suddala Sudhakar Teja.</em></span></p>\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">This is after we have already heard what <em><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><span style=\"color: #000000\">Sachchidananda Babu,</span> Astrologer</span></em> has to say: \"Zodiac signs can predict how women might get sexually abused. I can suggest a mantra for its prevention.\"</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">Agreed, there are some well-educated minds behind the public voice of the politicians who get them to ‘win elections’ and \'make policies\'. Hence the <strong>politicians CLAIM to be public servants. </strong>But what message are they sending across by appointing a Vastu consultant to provide guidance in running the government? wouldn\'t their thinking and actions be aped by many other commoners?</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">These elected leaders are supposed to voice the public and not indirectly promote their beliefs in the public. </span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Who takes responsibility of the thinking of our politicians? Of uplifting the mindset of these people who are our representatives in this democracy? Who is responsible for ensuring these netas are educated enough to even promise us education for every child in the country?</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\"><strong>Whose job is it?</strong> Who scrutinizes the education of our netas?</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">One would think our apex court has a say in it. But guess what? This is what the <strong>Supreme Court</strong> has to say on the matter:</span>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><em>\"The judiciary could not restrain tainted people from contesting elections as it could not enter the domain of the legislature. It is for Parliament to decide. They know how to run the country and who should run for election. We should not step in\"</em></span></p>\n<span style=\"color: #000000\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">So in a legislative assembly, run by the netas, the netas (the same netas) would decide if there should be bar of educational qualification on them to contest election?</span> Ha! Doesn\'t sound hilarious and ridiculous at the same time?</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">I bounced this thought on <a title=\"Go to page\" href=\"http://www.quora.com/Should-there-be-a-minimum-educational-qualification-for-politicians-to-contest-elections-in-India\" target=\"_blank\">Quora</a> and here are some findings:</span>\n<ol>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\">There is one common misconception among the Indian youth that politicians need to be educated. No, they don\'t need to. Such criteria can be very dangerous to the democratic system because it will hinder people from being a politician.</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\">Educational qualifications are not relevant for all kinds of jobs. Relevant qualification for being MLA or MP is ability to understand people\'s concerns, problems and to represent their interests.</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\">Even if education was relevant, it should be left to people to decide how much importance they give to educational qualifications.</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000\">Considering education as a qualification means denying a major part of population the right to contest. If, for example, bachelor\'s degree is set at basic educational qualification then more than 90% of citizens will become ineligible to contest elections.</span></li>\n</ol>\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">I also stumbled upon a recently conducted poll by TOI:</span> <a title=\"Go to link\" href=\"http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/speak-out/debateshow/35765203.cms\" target=\"_blank\">Are educational qualifications necessary for a ministerial post?</a>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">Which brings us back to square one. Is education qualification of our politicians necessary? If yes,<span style=\"color: #0000ff\"> <strong>whose problem is it?</strong></span></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">If there a possibility that after being elected these representatives undergo a small <em><strong>training</strong></em> to know basics of things like what causes swine flu and rapes? Or better yet, should there be some <em><strong>regulation</strong> </em>on what our netas speak and what reaches to the public? </span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\">Because for all we know there are people out there in some slum fearing the next mosquito might give them Swine Flu!!</span>','Education of Politicians: Whose problem is it?','','publish','open','open','','education-of-politicians-whose-problem-is-it','','','2015-02-24 18:19:11','2015-02-24 18:19:11','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2911',0,'post','',0),(2912,40,'2015-02-24 11:17:12','2015-02-24 11:17:12','','education of politicians','','inherit','open','open','','education-of-policians','','','2015-02-24 11:17:12','2015-02-24 11:17:12','',2911,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/education-of-policians.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2923,23,'2015-02-25 20:48:27','2015-02-25 20:48:27','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">My name is Sushila. It means ‘gentle’. The day I discovered the meaning of my name, I could see a clear paradox. My life was far from gentle. In fact, it was the exact opposite. Even my name seemed to be laughing at my destiny. Another word that the world introduced me to is ‘harami’. It means that I’m born out of wedlock which is the worst thing that can happen in this society. Now that is the social meaning but for me, it just means that I don’t belong to anyone and never will. I’m as illegitimate as a prostitute’s daughter can be. However, my case is an accident of birth. I’m just born into this life and I have made peace with this fact to an extent. Yet, when I look out of my window and see people moving about freely, sharing laughter and a certain feeling of belongingness, my heart breaks a little from inside. It happens each time I look out my window, my only view to the outside world. I’ve never been allowed to go out of the brothel and I don’t even know if I will ever find a place out there, but there are days when I want to get out of my room and see what it is like.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This isn’t to say that my life in the brothel is too sad. Chhotu gives me my chai right in the morning, without me even asking for it. Only I have this privilege. Rani Memsahib, the owner of my brothel and my life, lets me have my own room. Last month, she installed a mirror too. I have young lovers who get me flowers for my hair and exotic smelling perfume for my skin. It’ll all come to an end when I get older and when men stop wanting me. The world outside my window will not stop mocking me though. I would love to go out there but I don’t want a beating from Rani ji. There is also the burden of my social identity as a ‘harami’. Seriously, when someone refers to me as that, I feel like laughing at their face. One of the respectable members of this delusional society is my father. He is allowed to go around paying to make love to a woman. The society turns a sacred act of love into a lucrative business and then puts me at the receiving end of it all by identifying me with a word that actually means a lack of identity. The society is as funny as my name. I was put to work when I was 11. Obviously, there was a demand for young girls like me. Still, the society calls me dirty. Another one of its hilarious jokes. Usually parents feel proud when their children become famous for their job. I can’t say the same for my mother. Sending me into the market completely shattered her but as I have mentioned, my life belongs to the brothel owner.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">All this makes me skeptical of the outside world and yet the view outside my window just keeps calling out to me. I feel like it’ll be the end of a dream if I actually step out into the world. You know, like it won’t be what I expect it to be. It won’t offer me the great escape that I desire so desperately. It is my dream to be able to go and be a part of that view that teases me every day but it is this dream that gives me a reason to stay. Not like I can think about ending my life. Simply because I’m not the owner of it. I pray that in another universe, in another life, I get to be free, to own myself and to feel like I belong. Till then, I’ll just look outside my window.</p>','What Is Outside The Window?','','publish','open','open','','outside-window','','','2015-02-25 20:48:27','2015-02-25 20:48:27','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2923',0,'post','',0),(2924,2,'2015-02-25 20:45:10','2015-02-25 20:45:10','','b7dcf49d2cd343243994e1f8177ffad6','','inherit','open','open','','b7dcf49d2cd343243994e1f8177ffad6','','','2015-02-25 20:45:10','2015-02-25 20:45:10','',2923,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/b7dcf49d2cd343243994e1f8177ffad6.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2928,2,'2015-02-27 16:19:09','2015-02-27 16:19:09','','Helpiez-Logomark','','inherit','open','open','','helpiez-logomark-2','','','2015-02-27 16:19:09','2015-02-27 16:19:09','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/helpiez-logomark1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2933,2,'2015-03-01 22:34:42','2015-03-01 22:34:42','','favicon-16x16','','inherit','open','open','','favicon-16x16','','','2015-03-01 22:34:42','2015-03-01 22:34:42','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/favicon-16x16.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2934,2,'2015-03-01 22:35:11','2015-03-01 22:35:11','','apple-touch-icon-114x114','','inherit','open','open','','apple-touch-icon-114x114','','','2015-03-01 22:35:11','2015-03-01 22:35:11','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/apple-touch-icon-114x114.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2935,2,'2015-03-01 22:35:53','2015-03-01 22:35:53','','apple-touch-icon-144x144','','inherit','open','open','','apple-touch-icon-144x144','','','2015-03-01 22:35:53','2015-03-01 22:35:53','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/apple-touch-icon-144x144.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2938,2,'2015-03-04 10:44:53','2015-03-04 10:44:53','','exam','','inherit','open','open','','exam','','','2015-03-04 10:44:53','2015-03-04 10:44:53','',2693,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/exam.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2943,38,'2015-03-05 15:01:40','2015-03-05 15:01:40','Who is India\'s daughter?\n\nWe all know her. Some of us know her as Nirbhaya, as Damini and as Jyoti. Almost none of us forgot the date. It was a dark Sunday, probably one of the most shameful days in Indian history. Words don\'t come easy when you have to describe the events in the bus on that night in India\'s capital city. The sheer description can make anyone feel queasy and I don\'t know how many people can picture the agony that Jyoti went through that night.\n\nRight from the next day, protests started kicking in throughout the country and it spread across the breadth and lengths of India. They were mostly peaceful protests largely consisting of students but things turned ugly when the police got involved. There were videos all over the media with police manhandling women and young students.\n\nAlmost two and a half years have gone by, the storm has passed or so people say. So what is kicking up all the dust again ? A \"controversial\" BBC documentary by Leslee Udwin was made on the incident. It isn\'t a video for the weak hearted or more so, for the strong hearted either. The video was supposed to be released on March 8th - International Women\'s day but was banned by the Indian government. The reason that they gave was that BBC did not have necessary permissions.\n\nLeslee spent 2 years in India and made this well researched documentary. How did the Indian government react to the release of the documentary in London on Wednesday and then on Youtube ? In my opinion, just like how a six year old kid would. Or wait, probably even more immaturely. Our <a href=\"http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Govt-serves-legal-notice-to-BBC-for-airing-Nirbhaya-film-Indias-Daughter-Cong-BJP-spar/articleshow/46468604.cms\" target=\"_blank\">government has now served legal notice to BBC</a> and our home minister Rajnath Singh.\n\nSo what is in this video ? I don\'t know how many of you have watched it and if Youtube will take down the video anytime soon. I wouldn\'t be very surprised if the video is taken down because come on, lets face it - we couldn\'t take the AIB roast, how can we let someone tell us that India had a dark brutal rape incident.\n\nI have watched the video twice now and it choked me up at the end, both times. This is why you should see the video, whether you are a male or a female, an Indian or not. If you are human, you should watch it for the following five reasons.\n\n1) Jyoti\'s parents represent any Indian middle class family and their emotions are candid and come across clearly. It goes from their joy at Jyoti\'s birth, outlines their support to her till the end. They occupy major screen time and their words come from their hearts. They make you feel like this could have been YOU ! It could have been anyone you know. And when that feeling sinks in, it kicks real hard.\n\n2) Jyoti was not a weak girl by heart. The movie brings out her strong attitude, her ambitions, her hard work to pursue those ambitions and her mental strength to have survived the incident and spoken about it. There are little tidbits here and there that bring across Jyoti not as a victim but more as a complete human being. A normal Indian girl.\n\n3) What will make you rethink your belief in humanity is the parts of the video with an interview of Mukesh, one of the men convicted of the rape and murder of India\'s daughter - Jyoti. He shows no remorse at any point. He goes on to describe it like it meant nothing to him, blames women for not staying indoors and taking care of their homes and states \"Only 20% Indian women are good\". Every word this man says makes your blood curl. He defends his position like it was his right to rape her and if someone is to be blamed, it should be her.\n\n4) The government\'s reaction to the protests is also in the limelight. How did peaceful protests turn into violent ones? What really happened and what orders did the police get?\n\n5) Of all people who spoke in the video, there will be one person who will stand out. The defence lawyer for the  rapists - M.L. Sharma. First, you try to get over his broken English and piece it together with lame comparisons of girls to flowers and men to thorns. I wonder if his mother is proud of the way she brought him up. Would he be okay if someone was so brutal towards his loved one ? I doubt it. Another defence lawyer for the rapists, A P Singh stands by his statement that he would burn his daughter alive if she had a relationship with anyone before her marriage. It sent a shiver down my spine. I closed my eyes and wondered what would happen if more Indian fathers were like him.\n\nThis documentary brings out all the aspects from a victim\'s family survival issues to even the accused people\'s families supporting them for what it is worth.\n\nWhile one half of the society will be debating on what laws the film maker broke while making this video, I am assured there will be a storm of statements (mostly stupid ones) from our dear politicians. And to begin with, how about <a href=\"http://www.firstpost.com/india/amid-outrage-indias-daughter-kiran-bedi-compares-rapists-pigeons-2135515.html\" target=\"_blank\">Kiran Bedi comparing rapists to male pigeons</a>? <em>Yes that was one sentence for her, and a giant leap for human stupidity !</em>\n\nI am as Indian as a girl can be and personally I don\'t think it portrays India in a dark light. It just brings out the society\'s deep dark secrets and tries to answer questions about where humanity is going. The video has already got several views world over and rest assured, more furor will follow this documentary. But we have deeper issues that plague our society. Will a girl\'s clothes decide if she gets raped or if she gets to live? Or will the society\'s mindset be changed in time to bring about a better society ? I am proud to be India\'s daughter but am I safe?\n\nLet us know what you think of the documentary in the comments section below. Did <strong>India\'s daughter</strong> get the justice she deserved?\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','India\'s Daughter - Saved or Ashamed ?','','publish','open','open','','indias-daughter','','','2015-03-05 15:01:40','2015-03-05 15:01:40','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2943',0,'post','',1),(2949,38,'2015-03-05 14:59:39','2015-03-05 14:59:39','India\'s daugher','RZsCDJi2_400x400','India\'s daugher','inherit','open','open','','rzscdji2_400x400','','','2015-03-05 14:59:39','2015-03-05 14:59:39','',2943,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/rzscdji2_400x400.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2961,23,'2015-03-08 16:14:03','2015-03-08 16:14:03','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Jyoti, a young 21 year old, got raped in 2012 by some inhumane men. Guddiya, a 3 year old, went through surgery after being abducted and raped by her neighbor. Palakh was raped and killed by her guard. These are stories of women who walk among us. They are our neighbors, friends, acquaintances. These are women we don’t personally know but we understand their struggle because we see every woman going through this struggle every day. We see women being eve teased. We have noticed women being stalked. We know that some of our female friends are going through cyber abuse and yet, on 8<sup>th</sup> March, we’ll all celebrate Women’s Day in our own little ways. Some of us will help our mothers in the kitchen. Some of the boyfriends would give their girlfriends a nice bouquet. Most of us will forward motivational messages and feel content about having wished all the women we know. However, most of us don’t think too much about this particular day. Nobody raises questions like why do we celebrate Women’s Day and should we really?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is high time that we sit down and review the situation. Living in a society where being a woman is no less being a domesticated animal, is there really a need to celebrate womanhood? The origin of the celebration lies in the 20<sup>th</sup> century when the oppression was only spurring women to fight for their rights. However, the fight really complete?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Only once you start asking yourself these questions, will you realize that the society hasn’t really transformed in a way that would be healthy for woman and hence, this celebration isn’t really complete. Ask the young girls in India if they feel that we as a society have reached a point where we can celebrate a day for women and the answers would be mixed. Some would want to celebrate the women who inspire them, while the others would laugh in your face and tell you that even the proposition of Women’s Day sounds funny. Over the centuries of disrespect and inequality, women have really lost faith in the society. Being a woman, I feel unsafe whenever I step out of my house. Walking till the market is all about looking in 10 different directions and being vigilant about my surroundings. If a young girl, living in 21<sup>st</sup> century India, does not even feel safe walking outside, then we definitely haven’t progressed much. This woman’s day, instead of sending flowers and messages to the women you love, ask yourself how you can improve the society in a way where celebrating women’s day makes more sense and from there, you’ll find that there is a long way to go.</p>','Why Women\'s Day?','','publish','open','open','','womens-day','','','2015-03-08 16:14:03','2015-03-08 16:14:03','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2961',0,'post','',0),(2962,2,'2015-03-08 16:00:04','2015-03-08 16:00:04','','womensday','','inherit','open','open','','womensday','','','2015-03-08 16:00:04','2015-03-08 16:00:04','',2961,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/womensday.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2963,2,'2015-03-08 16:02:48','2015-03-08 16:02:48','','women-day','','inherit','open','open','','women-day','','','2015-03-08 16:02:48','2015-03-08 16:02:48','',2961,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/women-day.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2977,49,'2015-03-14 19:21:59','2015-03-14 19:21:59','<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Dearest sister,</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">I do not know if you would be able to read this in any way by any means. But if you do, please do feel privileged to be living in a world much better than mine.\nI am writing this to you with a sombre expression on my face, a lump in my throat and tears in my eyes. I just finished watching the documentary which the BBC news channel made on you to commemorate international women\'s day. I am filled with both pride and shame on watching it. Pride, needless to say being you and shame, those inhuman species who took you away from us.\n16th DEC 2012, the entire country stood in shock resulting from the horrendous and barbaric cruelty meted out to you and your friend. Although, in a country like ours which has become habituated to crimes against women, the sad news about you wasn\'t really a bolt from the blue, it still had the entire nation rooted to the spot. Such was the intensity of the crime, dear sister, I understand. I failed to even imagine the pain you must have felt for even a cursory glance from a stranger makes my blood run cold.\nWhile you were battling between life and death, shock and shame, an unprecedented and tumultuous uproar in the form of protests was carried out at every corner of the country. You, dear sister, were the reason the entire nation was in solidarity. We couldn\'t take this anymore.  Seeing such outrage of extreme emotions from people I had high hopes from the law to do its best to reduce, if not totally eliminate crimes against women but sadly, sister, the scenario still remains unchanged. Every twenty minutes a woman is raped in India. Even As I write this to you, somewhere a woman is being bullied, harassed and raped while the perpetrators of your ghastly crime are probably enjoying a hearty meal in imprisonment.\nOften when me and my friends walk to and from college, there are always those few pairs of eyes gazing at us lecherously. Sometimes, they purposely push us, other times they speed up their bikes to scare us. All because, we are girls. I have been punished to be a girl. I have had to curb my dreams and passions because I am a girl. I love to travel and explore new places. I want to go on trips with my friends but I must remember i am a girl, a flower that needs protection and hence I must stay home and enroll myself in household chores. I must not dare to step out of the house alone, especially after sunset, otherwise the thorn might harm the flower. I want to go to parties and have fun just like my male friends but I must not forget that I am a girl, the one who is considered more  responsible in any case with a man. Sister, I want to break free from the shackles of codes and conducts, dos and don\'ts, but I must abide by them because I am a girl.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Dearest sister, I would like to make a number of  heartfelt apologies to you.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Apology on behalf of our financially handicapped govt. which otherwise has a lot of fund to shell out just to be in the good books of a certain visitor from the States or to garnish sportsmen with handsome cheques. But when it comes to improving the standard of security for women in our country, their pockets are empty\nApology on behalf of our legislature and judiciary which has always failed to deliver prompt justice to the victims.\nApology on behalf of the bigwigs of our country, the Ambanis, Birlas and the Khans, who are loaded with fame name and money but wouldn\'t utilise any of those and take a step forward to contribute to the safety of women in India. Apology on behalf of the so called guardians of the people,  the police officers, for their lackadaisical attitude, for being so classless and disinterested in our matters, for supporting the false when offered money.\nApology on behalf of all those selfish, self-centred people who would make no move in helping a woman knowing her to be in trouble. Of course, why would they invite trouble for themselves?\nApology on behalf of Mr honey Singh, the blatantly sexist singer who has so conveniently made a future for himself by caricaturing women, still being a favourite son.\nApology on behalf of the masterminds behind TV soaps for always depicting women to be inferior to men.\nBut above all, my dearest sister, I owe you an excruciating and shameful apology for being unable to do anything to bring you justice.\nBut you have come to me and every other woman as a great inspiration. Your determination to achieve your goals against all odds is very galvanizing. I wish with all my heart that someday your dream of opening a hospital in your village is realised.\nWith the shallow, shameless, adamant mindsets of a part of the male fraternity in this country, I will only have to hope against hope to live in a crime free India. On women\'s day I woke up to the news of a 6 year old, who probably wouldn\'t even know what rape is, being brutally raped in Ahmedabad. Tomorrow again I might wake up to the news of yet another rape, if only its reported and considered, again I will notice someone giving me licentious looks. The age of chivalry is dead sister. Humanity has failed. I do not want to live amidst such disgraceful people and their filthy thoughts anymore. Dearest sister, like I said, please do feel privileged to be living in a world much better than mine. You might not be the nearest to us but you are definitely the dearest. You are not just a daughter to your parents, you are \"India\'s daughter\".</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">- From a helpless younger sister.</p>','My Apologies to \'India\'s Daughter\'','','publish','open','open','','apologies-indias-daughter','','','2015-03-14 19:21:59','2015-03-14 19:21:59','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=2977',0,'post','',0),(2978,2,'2015-03-13 21:35:56','2015-03-13 21:35:56','Programme Name: India\'s Daughter: Storyville - TX: 08/03/2015 - Episode: n/a (No. n/a) - Picture Shows: Candle-lit vigils were held throughout India to commemorate the death of Jyoti.  - (C) Assassin Films - Photographer: Screen grab','9cba0708-2612-4676-9db8-05a9a971f8d5-620x372','','inherit','open','open','','9cba0708-2612-4676-9db8-05a9a971f8d5-620x372','','','2015-03-13 21:35:56','2015-03-13 21:35:56','',2977,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/9cba0708-2612-4676-9db8-05a9a971f8d5-620x372.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3010,42,'2015-03-28 18:33:19','2015-03-28 18:33:19','<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">Dear Smt Smriti Iraniji,At the drop of a hat, every government, including yours, says that subsidies are bad for the economy and should be done away with.Many of the subsidies in your ministry are going to those who don\'t deserve it. IITians are the most guilty of this pilferage. To make things worse, they hardly do anything for the country. Best-selling fiction is not known to help farmers.<strong>1) To begin with, this is what they cost us\n</strong>While it takes over Rs 3.4 lakh to educate an IITian per year, the student pays only Rs 90,000 per year. The rest is borne by the government. That is close to Rs 2.5 lakh per student per year, which is being paid by the tax payer. If one extrapolates this to all the 39,540 students in the Indian Institute of Technologies, the cost borne by the tax payer on educating IITians extends to 988.5 crore annually.\n\nAccording to budget estimates, Rs 1703.85 crore is to be allocated to the IITs for 2015-\'16.\n\n<strong>2) What do we get in return for the Rs 1,700 crore we spend on them?\n</strong>Inspite of producing 9,885 world-class engineers in computer science, electrical, electronic, chemical, mechanical, production fields every year...\n\na) The Geosynchronous Satellite Launch Vehicle, though successful with the Russian Cryogenic Engine, has time and again failed with the indigenous cryogenic engine. We have succeeded only once with our indigenous cryogenic rocket.\n\nb) Indigenous submarines are still a distant dream because of the technological complexity in building them. Though many projects are coming up in our own shipyards, they are happening because we are merely manufacturing them in India with foreign technology.\n\nc) The indigenous Indian Small Arms System rifles for our army, developed by the Defence Research and Development Organisation, have always been reported as problematic, and we import assault rifles from Israel.\n\nWhy could our world-class engineers, who are educated with tax payers\' money, not have built them?\n\n<strong>3) This is what our top IITians gave a miss\n</strong>A Right to Information application that was filed recently has shown that less than 2% of engineers at the Indian Space Research Organisation are from IITs and the National Institutes of Technology. Our best space programme doesn\'t get our best engineers every year.\n\nThe army doesn\'t get engineers and officers from the IITs. Between 1986 and 2006, not a single IITian has joined the Indian army.\n\nThe DRDO has a shortage of more than 2,700 scientists, and it is stretched and overworked, but our world-class engineers don\'t find it challenging.\n\n<strong>4) If an IITian wants to run an online shop, then why do I, a taxpayer, have to pay for his chemical engineering degree?\n</strong>Going by 2013 figures, Flipkart, the online mega-store, recruited seven students from IIT Madras in 2013.\n\nOne can understand the logic behind Flipkart hiring a computer science engineer. But six of the hires had studied aerospace, chemical, metallurgy, bio-technology and engineering physics.  What specialist knowledge will they bring to Flipkart?\n\nThese students do not have any interest in what they learnt in their four-year undergraduate programme, and want to erase their history by moving to a different field.\n\n<strong>5) Why did I pay for Chetan Bhagat\'s mechanical engineering degree?\n</strong>I have nothing against Chetan Bhagat, but I do know that Indian taxpayers paid to make him a mechanical engineer. He has done everything but engineering.\n\nAnother RTI filed with IIM Bangalore has revealed that out of the current batch of 406 students, 97 students are from IITs. Fifty-six of these are students with less than two years work experience.\n\nIf all these engineers wanted to be was managers, why does the tax payer need to pay for their engineering education at the IITs?\n\n<strong>6) Get a loan, why seek a subsidy?\n</strong>All students from IITs can get collateral-free loans from nationalised banks for upto Rs 20 Lakh.\n\nAnd IITians are obviously so awesome that companies are eager to pay them crores of rupees.\n\nThen why should a world-class engineer who makes crores of rupees and adds no value to India be given a subsidised education at the IITs? Can\'t they get educated with a bank loan of their own and repay it after getting their huge salaries?\n\n<strong>7) Remittances help forex? Nope, not really.\n</strong>Whenever there is a debate on brain drain from the IITs, the remittances issue pops up. Many believe that IITians who go abroad send back remittances and contribute to foreign exchange reserves. However, it is a pittance for India.\n\nA report in the <em>Economic Times</em> shows that out of the total remittances of $70 billion to India, the remittances from IITians who go to developed countries is much lower than the remittances from the Middle East to the state of Kerala.\n\nMost of the Malayalis in the Gulf are blue-collar workers, not IIT engineers.\n\nSo, why should the common man subsidise an IITian\'s college fees?\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"></div>\n<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>This article was published on <a href=\"http://scroll.in/article/715918/Dear-Smriti-Irani,-stop-giving-my-money-to-IITians\" target=\"_blank\">Scroll.in</a>.</em></div>\n<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"></div>\n<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">The original article can be read on <a href=\"https://www.saddahaq.com/human-interest/iit/dear-smriti-irani-please-stop-giving-my-money-to-iitians?lstid=lst1425905929044&amp;sld=6\" target=\"_blank\">Saddahaq.com</a>.</div>\n<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"></div>\n<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>Also read a response to this article</em>: <a href=\"http://www.helpiez.org/blog/no-smriti-irani-not-wasting-money-iitians/\" target=\"_blank\">No, Smriti Irani is not wasting your money on the IITians</a>.</div>\n<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"></div>\n<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><i>We welcome your comments in the section below.</i></div>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>','Dear Smriti Irani, stop giving my money to IITians','','publish','open','open','','dear-smriti-irani-stop-giving-money-iitians','','','2015-03-28 18:33:19','2015-03-28 18:33:19','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=3010',0,'post','',0),(3011,2,'2015-03-28 18:30:15','2015-03-28 18:30:15','','IIT_Kharagpur_Main_Building','','inherit','open','open','','iit_kharagpur_main_building','','','2015-03-28 18:30:15','2015-03-28 18:30:15','',3010,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/iit_kharagpur_main_building.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3015,42,'2015-03-28 18:44:13','2015-03-28 18:44:13','<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">The author of ‘<a href=\"http://www.helpiez.org/blog/dear-smriti-irani-stop-giving-money-iitians/\" target=\"_blank\">Dear Smriti Irani, stop giving my money to IITians</a>’ made several fallacious and superficial arguments in concluding that Indian Institute of Technologies don’t contribute to the country. Here’s why he is wrong:</div>\n<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"></div>\n<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>1) Not into Space/Defence research? Your education is useless.\n</strong>The author argues that just because India has been unsuccessful in some three space and defence technologies – cryogenics engines, submarines, and assault rifles – IITians are a waste of taxpayer money. This argument betrays the ill-conceived notions that he seems to hold about technology in today’s world. It is equivalent to my grandmother claiming that I’m a useless engineer because I cannot repair the air conditioner. Science and technology is much more than rockets and missiles.Even in defence and space research, failure to indigenously develop a technology that can otherwise be easily imported says nothing about technological development in the country. Whenever it has not been possible to easily import such technology, India has stepped up. Indigenous development of nuclear weapons and the Mars and lunar missions are a testament to that spirit.\n\n<strong>2) The meaning of contribution.\n</strong>The author also has a deeply mistaken view of what it means to contribute to a country. The author argues that IITians are not contributing anything to the country because they are not joining the Indian Space Research Agency and the Defence Research and Development Organisation in satisfactory numbers. Ironically, the author takes a dig at Chetan Bhagat and others, saying, “Best-selling fiction is not known to help farmers.”  Sadly, missiles and submarines don’t help farmers either.\n\nTo be sure, it is disappointing that ISRO and DRDO are unable to attract the best talent in the country. However, it is not just the fault  of the IITians. People go where the opportunities are. The solution is to make the opportunities in space and defence research more lucrative – not force unwilling engineers to settle for something they are not interested in, when they could do better.\n\n<strong>3) Chemical engineers in Flipkart? Traitors!\n</strong>Our education system is designed such that we expect high school students to decide once and for all what they want to do in their life. But, they do not have enough information to be able to make that choice. Interestingly, many of my friends in chemical engineering were quite surprised to learn that it isn’t really about much chemistry. Yet, we routinely admit 17-year-olds into specialised degree programmes and expect them to stick to it for life.\n\nThe founders of Flipkart didn’t want to do any chemical engineering. Instead they went on to create a great online retail company that satisfied a gaping need in the Indian economy. They have also created numerous jobs in the process. In my opinion, they have contributed much more to the Indian economy than a typical chemical engineer in a chemical plant ever would.\n\nWhat role did IITs play in their journey, though? It  provided them with the right environment and the right set of tools to be able to successfully execute their ideas. Many of my entrepreneur friends would agree. Education is holistic, not confined to narrow pockets.\n\n<strong>4) IITians are not sponging off taxpayers.\n</strong>Since IITians are successful in their professional life, the author is enraged that the taxpayers contributed to their education. They can earn lakhs in their placements, so why are they sponging off taxpayers, the author asks.\n\nWhat he failed to consider is the fact that IITians are also taxpayers. By being more economically successful than an average taxpayer, IITians also end up more tax. Here\'s a quick back-of-the-envelope calculation – even with a modest salary of 10 lakh per annum, paying roughly 20% in income tax, the taxpayers\' subsidy is cleared off in five years.  A fancy salary of one crore, which seems to have enraged the author very much, can clear off the subsidy in around six months.\n\nOne can argue that paying taxes is their duty, irrespective of the subsidy. It indeed is. However, they would not be earning as much, and the government would not be generating that extra tax revenue, if it were not for the education that they received.\n\n<strong>5) Other subsidies and spending?\n</strong>Being libertarian and shouting down taxes and subsidies all together would be logical and consistent. However, a selective grudge against subsidies for higher education doesn’t make any sense. Why spend on healthcare? Why spend on primary education? What use is educating first graders? The government needs to spend on education because, ultimately, a well-educated population is good for the progress of a country, and all levels of education are important.\n\nThis is not to say that there is no other way to fund higher education. However, if subsidies encouraged even one more person to get educated, that money is still well spent.\n\n<em>Note: I have given the benefit of doubt to the author that all data quoted is accurate, without independently verifying it.</em>\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>This article was originally published on <a href=\"http://scroll.in/article/716595/No,-Smriti-Irani-is-not-wasting-your-money-on-the-IITians\" target=\"_blank\">Scroll.in</a>.</em></div>\n<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"></div>\n<div class=\"ng-scope\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><i>We welcome your comments below.</i></div>','No, Smriti Irani is not wasting your money on the IITians','','publish','open','open','','no-smriti-irani-not-wasting-money-iitians','','','2015-03-28 18:44:13','2015-03-28 18:44:13','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=3015',0,'post','',0),(3016,2,'2015-03-28 18:40:39','2015-03-28 18:40:39','','IIT_KGP_Main_Building','','inherit','open','open','','iit_kgp_main_building','','','2015-03-28 18:40:39','2015-03-28 18:40:39','',3015,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/iit_kgp_main_building.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3017,2,'2015-03-28 18:41:00','2015-03-28 18:41:00','','IIT_KGP_Main_Building','','inherit','open','open','','iit_kgp_main_building-2','','','2015-03-28 18:41:00','2015-03-28 18:41:00','',3015,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/iit_kgp_main_building1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3026,42,'2015-03-30 06:42:42','2015-03-30 06:42:42','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Let alone disappointing one billion people in a single miscalculated run, having the immense guts to smile wide while shaking hands with Michael Clarke is the reason why I want to protect my baby from this undeserving icon called “Dhoni”. Really, my blood boils because my two-year-old son looks at the TV screen and keeps shouting “Dhoni! Dhoni!” no matter who is playing. I hate MSD for imprinting himself in everybody’s psyche so deeply that there is no looking beyond him. I almost want to be swayed by the mass excitement and worship him like everybody else, but I know how dangerous that is!</p>\n\n<blockquote>For one, Dhoni goes COMPLETELY AGAINST INDIAN CULTURE.</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I don’t want my son to grow up thinking that it is good to be Captain Cool! Which self-respecting Indian man stays calm under stress? It is not our culture to behave as if nothing is happening. I was so disheartened by his silence! Where were the <em>Maa-Behen gaalis</em>? How dare his blood not boil even as our team was quickly decaying to a shameful loss?!</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">No, I don’t want my son to become another Dhoni. Because only a stupid captain would go ahead and give credit to other batsmen when he is still the top scorer of the team. Dhoni has to be astonishingly blind to overlook 65 runs and highlight other people’s runs that are dwindling in relative mediocrity.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">What does he think he’s doing when he walks out from a pitiful loss and says “What I have done doesn’t really matter”? Who in their right mind puts the youngsters ahead of himself, just so they have the chance to bat? Dhoni is so oblivious to his own position as a captain that it is laughable!</p>\n\n<blockquote>Do I want my son to become someone who doesn’t know how to be proud of his position? No! Do I want my son to be incapable of using the power dispensed by that position? Are you MAD? NO!</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I would very much like my son to be a normal Indian human being, thank you! I don’t want him to become a somebody and then pretend as if he’s not special at all. Look at Dhoni! With the kind of attention he gets, he should get “I am Captain, B*tch” tattooed on his forehead, but he has no idea how to gloat in the limelight. What a phenomenal waste of national level cheering for one man!</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">What a joke, man! You are the captain of the Indian cricket team for almost eight years, and you always make news only for the boring reasons. It is always about how India wins under Dhoni’s captaincy. ALWAYS! I mean, where is the fun in this? There is so much he could have done with all the eyes looking at him all the time! He could have lost his temper with a white guy- you know, kick up some postcolonial vengeance in the process! He could have gotten into a scandal with a woman. I’m sure so many ladies want him! He could have done well for himself with some extra bucks with match-fixing. But he doesn’t! The stupid man doesn’t! I bet he doesn’t even have a Swiss Bank account. Seriously? Which well known Indian doesn’t have a Swiss Bank account?! I am sorry, but I can’t let my son become an alien to common Indian practices! No way!</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">And what’s with the whole deal about not seeing his daughter? Your daughter is just born and you are busy playing cricket for the country? What nonsense is that! Is this what a <em>sanskaari </em>family man does to his own flesh and blood? I am telling you, this man Dhoni has absolutely no sense of loyalty! Family must always come first, no? Who cares about the goddamn country? Other people are always around to take care of it. But no, Dhoni actually takes responsibility seriously! Who does that?? The only responsibility a decent man has is to look after himself and his family! <em>Baaki sab bhaad mein jaaye!</em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Really, I can’t think of more clear-cut reasons why my son should not start following Dhoni-ism! I put enough salt in his meals for him to behave like a real man. I don’t want my son to be all saint-like and gentle-gentle. If he does, then who will take care of family? What have these great big notions of serving the nation done to help us, anyway? Ultimately you HAVE to pay tax that will anyway be misappropriated!</p>\n\n<blockquote>Nobody should be foolish enough to become another Mahendra Singh Dhoni because only Dhoni can be Dhoni!</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Only someone like Mahi deserves to be where he is. There is enough and more proof that everything he does is not humanly possible. No, because he is beyond just a normal human being. He is God.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It takes incredible strength of character to rise up from an unknown corner in Ranchi to where he is, and still be level-headed and unassuming about it. It takes great talent to be Dhoni and even more humility to achieve a Dhoni-like greatness. It takes a Dhoni to face fame and failure with equal courage and calmness.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Who else can stand unaffected by a billion screaming voices and have all their single-minded attention on a tiny speck of a ball? Even Arjun from The Mahabharat doesn’t measure up to Dhoni- because Pride is something that Captain Cool is untainted by. Arjun was evil enough to have an opponent’s thumb cut-off. Dhoni has no such trivial insecurities.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">No, I do NOT want my son to become another Dhoni. Nobody can reach the league of Dhoni. My son can try all he likes to be Dhoni, but it will only be a life of constant pursuit of perfection. He will never be another Dhoni, and nobody else will either.</p>\n\n<blockquote>There can only be one Dhoni. Nobody else deserves to come anywhere close.</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Author’s Note:</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I’m actually pretty pleased that my son can recognize Dhoni’s face correctly, if not anybody else’s! I was terribly disheartened when the wickets lit-up red. When Dhoni was run out, I knew we were going to lose the match. But what a great man! And he deserves so much respect! I just wish I could personally tell him that he has made us proud. I am sure a lot of people tell him a lot of things, but let me add my tears of pride in this country’s ocean of love for him. For you, Dhoni- I will Bleed Blue for life!</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>The original article was published in <a href=\"http://akkarbakkar.com/dear-dhoni-you-lost-to-prove-why-i-should-never-let-my-son-become-like-you/\">akkarbakkar.com</a></em></p>','Dear Dhoni, You Lost To Prove Why I Should Never Let My Son Become Like You','','publish','open','open','','dear-dhoni-lost-prove-never-let-son-become-like','','','2015-03-30 06:42:42','2015-03-30 06:42:42','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=3026',0,'post','',0),(3027,2,'2015-03-30 06:23:39','2015-03-30 06:23:39','','MS-Dhoni-of-India-looks-up-to-the-sky-as-rain-falls-during-the-One-Day-Interna1','','inherit','open','open','','ms-dhoni-of-india-looks-up-to-the-sky-as-rain-falls-during-the-one-day-interna1','','','2015-03-30 06:23:39','2015-03-30 06:23:39','',3026,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/ms-dhoni-of-india-looks-up-to-the-sky-as-rain-falls-during-the-one-day-interna1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3030,42,'2015-03-30 18:06:29','2015-03-30 18:06:29','Recently a video by Vogue Empower, starring Deepika Padukone, emancipated reactions from everyone who watched it. Although it was an appreciative attempt at highlighting the plight of Indian women, facing criticism and unwanted scrutiny at every facet of their lives. But as a person who has watched, there were a couple of points raised which reeked of pure hypocrisy. After facing quite a furore over it by men and women alike, a person decided to make a video over those questioned \'issues\' (going by the video).\n\nSo <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/user/TheAnkurpoddar\">Ankur Poddar </a>responded with a video, a male version of #MyChoice.\n\n<em><strong>Feminism is not about glorifying womanhood by degrading males. But breaking the patriarchal mindset of society.</strong></em>\n\n<em><strong>Respect both Men and Women. Infidelity is wrong. Period. It does not changes sides with the gender. </strong></em>\n\n&nbsp;','A Reply to Deepika Padukone\'s \"My Choice\" video.... Because choices are for males too!!!','','publish','open','open','','reply-deepika-padukones-choice-video-choices-males','','','2015-03-30 18:06:29','2015-03-30 18:06:29','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=3030',0,'post','',0),(3033,2,'2015-03-30 18:10:59','2015-03-30 18:10:59','','as','','inherit','open','open','','as-3','','','2015-03-30 18:10:59','2015-03-30 18:10:59','',3030,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/as1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(3039,42,'2015-04-03 21:04:35','2015-04-03 21:04:35','<div class=\"stry ph-vw transition in\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n<blockquote>\n<p class=\"e-b ph-vw t-b txt\"><em>The century old tradition, Sunat, is deep rooted in culture. It is believed that cutting the female genitalia preserves the girl\'s chastity.</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<div class=\"e-b ph-vw t-b txt\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n\n<hr />\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"e-b ph-vw t-b txt\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"></div>\n<div class=\"e-b ph-vw t-b txt\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"></div>\n<div class=\"e-b ph-vw t-b txt\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n\nA mother watches, as her eight-week-old daughter undergoes <em>Sunat</em>. The room resonates with the sound of the baby\'s cries. Within no time, the process is done. Her mother is pleased that her daughter is now complete.\n\nSunat, or Female Genital Mutilation (FGM) as it is termed by most organizations, is banned by World Health Organization (WHO).\n\nDespite the ban,it is practised amongst Muslims in various countries. According <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/feb/06/what-is-female-genital-mutilation-where-happen\">to WHO</a>, between 100 million and 140 million women and girls are thought to be living with the consequences of female genital mutilation.\n\nThe century old tradition is deep rooted in culture. It is believed that cutting the female genitalia preserves the girl’s chastity. The sense of social obligation fuels the continuation of the practice.\n\nGirls and women are made to have their external genitalia removed fully or partially– some when they are just infants, others when they hit puberty. Girls, in the name of preserving female honour, chastity, and beauty, undergo FGM.\n\nAccording to a <a href=\"http://www.unicef.org/protection/57929_69881.html\">2013 UNICEF report</a>, more than 125 million girls and women alive have been subjected to FGM/C in the 29 countries in Africa and the Middle East in which Islam is concentrated.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\">\n<div id=\"ib-1428052997256\" class=\"e-b i-b \">\n<div class=\"fig-bx\"><figure class=\"img-fig box fade transition zoom in\">\n<div class=\"ar-hldr\">\n<div class=\"ar\"></div>\n<img class=\"\" src=\"https://saddahaq.blob.core.windows.net/multimedia/38553606-map.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"753\" height=\"489\" />\n\n</div>\n&nbsp;\n\n</figure>\n<div class=\"clearfix\" style=\"text-align: left;\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\nIt isn\'t just Muslim dominated countries - even a Buddhist majority country like Thailand is a victim of FGM. Even as the Thailand government refuses to accept the scenario, reports suggest that almost every Muslim girl in the South is cut. In Thailand\'s three southernmost provinces of Yala, Narathiwat and Pattani, ethnic Malay Muslims are a majority.\n\n<i>Al Jazeera</i> <a class=\"bdr\" title=\"http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia-pacific/2015/03/female-genital-cutting-thailand-south-150309083458995.html\" href=\"http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia-pacific/2015/03/female-genital-cutting-thailand-south-150309083458995.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">quotes</a> Julia Lalla-Maharajh, the CEO of Orchid Project, a London-based organisation that advocates against female genital mutilation, as saying:\n<blockquote><em>There is very little data or evidence about the practice outside of African countries, and this is something we absolutely need to address.</em></blockquote>\nHealth teams in Thailand feel helpless, given that they don\'t have access to Thailand\'s conflict-stricken south, where bombing and attacks are regular.\n\n</div>\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\"></div>\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\">\n<blockquote>The cutting falls under the type IV of the WHO\'s classification system - the least invasive type, typically done without removing flesh, involving pricking, piercing, incising, scraping and cauterisation.</blockquote>\n</div>\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\">\n\nAccording to a study by the University of Malaya\'s department of preventive medicine in Malaysia, in 2011, 93 percent of Muslim women in Malaysia have undergone the procedure at some point.\n\nIn 2009, Malaysia\'s highest religious authority had issued a fatwa, making the cutting procedure required for all Muslim women, unless \"harmful\".\n\n</div>\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\">\n<div id=\"txt1428050405820\" class=\"e-b ph-vw t-b txt\"></div>\n<div id=\"txt1428053691780\" class=\"e-b ph-vw media v-b v\"><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/v-cwaJJBmNs?rel=0&amp;wmode=transparent&amp;wmode=transparent\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></div>\n<div class=\"e-b ph-vw t-b txt\"></div>\n<div class=\"e-b ph-vw t-b txt\"></div>\n<div id=\"txt1428050646407\" class=\"e-b ph-vw t-b txt\">\n\nChitra Raghavan, a professor of psychology, <a href=\"https://books.google.co.in/books?id=wDbEAgAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PR9&amp;lpg=PR9&amp;dq=Self+Determination+and+Women%27s+rights+in+Muslim+societies,&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=wIdhHPKqAQ&amp;sig=6yixEWOnY2DRbW7yrUaccyFi1Lo&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=R2QeVfWbNsGQuASb9oHgBA&amp;ved=0CE8Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&amp;q=Self%20Determination%20and%20Women\'s%20rights%20in%20Muslim%20societies%2C&amp;f=false\">in her book</a>, <em>Self Determination and Women\'s rights in Muslim societies</em>, claims that from the interviews and conversations she collected, it was evident that men shared the opinion that female sunat is not necessary.\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"e-b ph-vw t-b txt\">\n\nShe quotes Suleiman, a man in his late thirties, who studied Islamic law in the middle east. He believes that Sunat is not <em>wadjib </em>(obligatory) for women, and therefore doesn\'t need to be performed. When the time came to circumcise his daughter, he refused, defending his decision against his own mother.\n\nRaghavan quoted Ahmad, a teacher in a local Madrassa as saying that there is no mention of female Sunat in the <em>Quran</em>, whereas male circumcision is referred to in the form of Ibrahim\'s sacrifice.\n\nAccording to her book, Sunat is <em>wadjib </em>(obligatory) for boys and <em>sunnah</em> (preferable) for girls. For girls, the cutting must be limited. There are varied opinions about cutting being compulsory for girls. Raghavan is even told by two women that if she converted and had sunat performed on the same day, all her past sins would be forgiven and her life will begin anew.\n<div id=\"txt1428053766839\" class=\"e-b ph-vw media v-b i-b-m\"><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/cWy47hpG3nE?rel=0&amp;wmode=transparent&amp;wmode=transparent\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></div>\n<div id=\"txt1428052124966\" class=\"e-b ph-vw t-b txt\"></div>\n<div class=\"e-b ph-vw t-b txt\"></div>\n<div class=\"e-b ph-vw t-b txt\">\n\nMany women who undergo Sunat in southern Thailand don\'t even know they have been cut. It is only in their adulthood, when they read about it, that they know.\n\n<em>Al Jazeera</em> quoted Dr Umasa, who runs a small clinic on Yala\'s main drag, as saying:\n<blockquote><em>If it\'s done by a trained doctor, they are using the right technique, then never mind!</em></blockquote>\nExperts, however, refute the thought saying there is nothing called right technique. A little mistake in cutting the baby\'s clitoris can cause infection, sepsis, haemorrhage, and death.\n\nThere are reports that there is a decline in FGM, in the numerous countries it is practised, particularly because men from the community are opposing it. According to the 2013 UNICEF report, the prevalence had dropped by as much as almost half among adolescent girls in Benin, the Central African Republic, Iraq, Liberia and Nigeria.\n\nThe age old practice continues to draw attention, with people calling a ban on what they term as a human rights violation. The term FGM reflects the reality of the practice, which looks away from the brutality of the process, and asserts its adherence as part of the culture.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>The article was originally published in <a href=\"https://www.saddahaq.com/foreign-affairs/femalegenitalmutilation/female-genital-cutting-when-culture-wins-over-brutality\" target=\"_blank\">saddahaq.com</a></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>Share your views with us in the comments below.</em></p>','Female Genital Mutilation: When culture wins over brutality.','','publish','open','open','','female-genital-mutilation-culture-wins-brutality','','','2015-04-03 21:04:35','2015-04-03 21:04:35','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=3039',0,'post','',0),(3043,2,'2015-04-03 20:58:17','2015-04-03 20:58:17','','6','','inherit','open','open','','6-2','','','2015-04-03 20:58:17','2015-04-03 20:58:17','',3039,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/61.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3057,38,'2015-04-07 05:49:18','0000-00-00 00:00:00','I understand that it is just a matter of chance that I am where I am today. We don\'t choose the family that we were born into, or choose the fact that our parents could afford to give us quality education. However, I cannot help but think about how education which is considered one of the most basic necessities in life is not available to everyone. It is governed by a lot of factors ranging from politics to socio economics. The family or the demographics that a child is born into should not determine his or her destiny. There are a lot of issues in life - hunger, poverty, corruption, freedom of rights and well life itself. An issue that is high up on the ladder that needs attention is “Education”.\n\nEducation is a social fact, a process and an institution in itself. It has a social function and at the same time it is socially determined. Education is available in different standards in different demographic parts of the world. India which is said to be a classic example of a developing economy has a very complex education system that we are all part of. The ease of availability of education can be said to be greater in the western world when compared to India. It is also reflected in the literacy rate reported recently by UNICEF. There are also some scary statistics that show that education in India is not available to a major section of the society. I personally think that this is one of the most important crisis that the Indian society is facing and it has to be thought about. A seemingly simple solution is that a lot more rural schools can be started. This brings up the question of how do you quantify education and if we are successful in it, how can we compare the standards of education of these to be established rural schools and the so called elite schools. Another problem would be bringing children to these schools. The government of Tamil Nadu had introduced several policies to sort this out. The politicians announced mid day meal scheme to provide free food to those school kids, free books, free cycles for easy commuting to schools and more recently they even offered free laptops to “deserving” students in colleges. Again this rises questions on the whole process of selecting such students and the method that is followed to classify students. It is sometimes based on their performance in certain exams along with their family situation. But this system can be modified to function better.\n\nOne way to parameterize education can be through the board of education that is followed. Talking at school level, India has several boards of education like Regional or the State Boards, ICSE, CBSE and IB etc. There is an inbuilt psychology which makes us look at people with different perspectives based on the board they come from. I have seen this happening to me personally. Every college in India is a diverse community with a lot of different people. I come from a regional state board of education and I personally felt the standard of education in the first year was a little hard for me to cope up with. At the same time, my roommate was from the ICSE board and kept topping every exam that came her way. This made me feel little and I wondered if I wasn’t good enough or whether it is my socio- economic situations that have brought me to this dilemma. I wonder if I am as talented as my roommate and maybe if I was given a different standard of education, I would be at par with the others here. Also, people have given me a blank stare when they asked for the first time my school’s name. There always seems to be more respect for IB schools, then ICSE schools then CBSE and god forbid if you are from some other board. People comment that your performance is not actually as good as theirs in the board examinations because apparently regional boards give away marks to every student. This is not necessarily true but it is a perception nevertheless.\n\nThere are so many other issues in this field including the much debated, used and abused reservation system that is based on caste. There are a lot of views on this, while some people feel that it helps the underprivileged students to come up in life. Others feel that the basis of this system is not right and it can rather be based on monetary status of the family. Education is a complex system but is the epitome of any society’s development. There are several trivial and non trivial issues in this field that have to be addressed at the earliest and it would take any society to great heights.\n\n&nbsp;','Education','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-04-07 05:49:18','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=3057',0,'post','',0),(3059,38,'2015-04-07 05:48:51','2015-04-07 05:48:51','education','education','education','inherit','open','open','','download-12','','','2015-04-07 05:48:51','2015-04-07 05:48:51','',3057,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3065,42,'2015-04-09 21:45:02','2015-04-09 21:45:02','<blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>It is a shame that the once “face it all” Arvind Kejriwal has no courage to answer the questions from his volunteers, who gave their tan, man and dhan.</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<hr />\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Prashant Bhushan, in his open letter to Arvind Kejriwal, uses the phrase “in the pursuit of power at any cost”. Having been involved with the Aam Aadmi Party since its inception, and coordinating various technical activities at a global level, I want to demonstrate here how this “pursuit of power at any cost” has perforated deep into the party, even into non-political activities.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It was early October 2014, and there were remote signs of possible elections in Delhi, with all options to once again form the government gone. The media had forgotten AAP, and the public support was also weak at that point. The party leadership calls for a meeting of various social media team members of the party, including the social media head of the party. After the discussions, it is determined that the heavy anti-Modi stand of the AAP and posts on social media are the reason people are disengaged with the party, and a long-haul strategy to overcome this is arrived at. The strategy is then presented by the social media head to a very small online group, consisting of various technology and social media stakeholders of the party, spread across the world.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A summary of the strategy is as follows: The party decided to stop all anti-Modi rhetoric through both official and unofficial channels. Also thousands of fake Modi sympathizers were to be created across the social media channels. These 1000s of fake Modi sympathizers would, then, slowly create an artificial perception that people are en masse disappointed with Modi, and would endorse Arvind as the hope of Delhi, while also subtly pushing this sentiment to journalists.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">After a thorough discussion, across several of the stakeholders, on the pros and cons of such an approach, across various perspectives such as feasibility, alternatives, morality, competitor’s strategies etc., it was persisted that this needs to be done. On October 30th, the Twitter accounts were in possession of the party. The problem is, ever since, these fake Twitter personalities have been used to trend topics and abuse anyone who raises any question against the party.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To provide a context to the above, I quote a paragraph from Prashant Bhushan\'s open letter:</p>\n\n<blockquote><em>When the Delhi elections were announced and campaigning started, you instructed volunteers to start a campaign, \'Modi for PM, Kejriwal for CM\'. I said this is totally unprincipled. It means that our party has gone down on its\' knees before Modi at a time when it was positioning itself as the main opposition to Modi.</em></blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It was in the first week of November that the AAP website carried a banner with Arvind and Modi\'s photo, with the slogan \'Modi for PM, Kejriwal for CM\'. Seeing the backlash from supporters, it was deleted. Party spokesperson Ashutosh claimed that it was outside mischief, which was totally untrue! The next day, Arvind tells media that a volunteer who joined 10 days ago did it and was fired! Both of these were blatant lies, as the banner was actually from a video done by AAP, posted on its\' official Youtube channel and then deleted due to the backlash. The reality was that, that video was posted by AAP and an over enthusiastic volunteer posted it through the official Youtube channel and website.</p>\n[embed]https://youtu.be/CFycByJStvM\n[/embed]\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Seeing the two statements from Arvind and Ashutosh, both of them were equally offending to me, for I\'m a person in the team and I know that such incidents of outside mischief or a 10-day-old volunteer gaining access never happened. It was when it became obvious to me that, \"<em>power at any cost</em>\" was needed- here the cost being the reputation of the tech team, or a volunteer being immaterial in the pursuit of power.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Following this incident, I sent an email to a group of my close AAP colleagues explaining the same and noted</p>\n\n<blockquote><em>....the party is not even bothered to see or know what happened. What bothers me, is always so believing that we only speak truth to the media, though we may selectively skip some truths (at worst) for political reasons. Being a very close spectator to this, I realize that several similar things could be happening regularly, but just that I do not know! The question now in my mind is ‘Which of I hear about or from the party is a lie?’” and signed off as frustrated.</em></blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">That was probably my last wholehearted or passionate day in the party, until which I was an obedient soldier, doing anything the party wanted me to or I thought would help the party.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Any media release or statement released by the party since then, is always seen by me with suspicion, for it has become evident that there are master story fabricators in the party, who believe that they can change any perception the public hold on the party.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Fast forwarding, even after the inner party fiascos, nothing in the party has changed. The coterie around Arvind Kejriwal is ruining the party with its high-handedness, and making no effort to understand volunteers. The PAC of the party earlier made an announcement of states getting autonomy and other fanciful rhetoric.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">However, as recent as a week ago, the Tamil Nadu social media coordinator was randomly blocked from his permissions to operate the page, with the reason being given that “Tamil Nadu page has a lot of Tamil only content, and we fear that the content could be not in support of Arvind Kejriwal. We had to block access to review the content.” Such high-handed approach resulted in the social media coordinator, who did a phenomenal job for the past year, quitting the party in view of the insult, and the page having no posts since then.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is a shame that the Aam Aadmi Party, which was seen as a symbol of volunteerism, has today become the exact opposite, with the party having no ears to listen to its volunteers, while the ideologists and power mongers are engaged in a dirty war.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is a shame that the once “face it all” Arvind Kejriwal has no courage to answer the questions from his volunteers, who gave their tan, man and dhan.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I am just like many other volunteers, who joined the party for its ideology and not individuals, standing disillusioned today.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The original article was posted on <a href=\"https://www.saddahaq.com/politics/aaprift/power-at-any-cost-even-on-social-media\" target=\"_blank\"><em>saddahaq.com</em></a></p>','Power at any cost, even on social media?','','publish','open','open','','power-cost-even-social-media','','','2015-04-09 21:45:02','2015-04-09 21:45:02','',0,'http://www.helpiez.org/blog/?p=3065',0,'post','',0),(3070,2,'2015-04-09 21:39:59','2015-04-09 21:39:59','Indian anti-corruption activist turned politician Arvind Kejriwal speaks during a press conference in New Delhi, India, Saturday, Nov. 24, 2012. Kejriwal on Saturday launched his party naming it \'Aam Aadmi, or common people. (AP Photo/Altaf Qadri)','Arvind Kejriwal','Arvind Kejriwal','inherit','open','open','','arvind-kejriwal','','','2015-04-09 21:39:59','2015-04-09 21:39:59','',3065,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/arvind-kejriwal-650.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3071,1,'2015-06-03 05:38:17','2015-06-03 05:38:17','','About','','publish','open','open','','about','','','2015-06-03 05:38:17','2015-06-03 05:38:17','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/index.php/2015/06/03/about/',9,'nav_menu_item','',0),(3072,1,'2015-06-03 05:38:17','2015-06-03 05:38:17','','Get Started','glyphicon-flash','publish','open','open','','get-started','','','2015-06-03 05:38:17','2015-06-03 05:38:17','',0,'http://ec2-52-6-199-128.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wordpress/inde